<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-DAFOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE A POSITIVE THINKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Another tie wasn't what the Bruins needed.
</P>
<P>
   But the 2-2 decision Saturday &UR;  &LR; night against the Devils at the
FleetCenter didn't turn out so bad, especially considering the way
it started, with New Jersey's Scott Niedermayer crashing into
Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe 22 seconds into the game, resulting in a
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen a replay yet, but I don't think I'm going to
fall into the corner by myself,'' Dafoe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To start the game that way, the first minute, you have another
bad-luck situation,'' Dafoe said. ``We could have thrown it in and
said, `I guess this isn't our night,' but the guys fought really
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   As ties go, this one wasn't that bad, but Dafoe wants more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting sick of these ties, the losses and ties,'' Dafoe
said. ``That's a good hockey club on that side. We played them
tough. I don't think they outplayed us by any means. It's an
important point for us. It's not a victory, there's still a sour
taste in our mouths, but we're playing better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lie to you, I don't think our mind-set is on
top of the world right now, but we're finding the positives out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   And Dafoe feels confident on the ice, although his statistics
are not as stellar as last season, when he compiled a 32-23-11 with
a 1.99 goals-against average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good out there, although I don't have the personal
numbers like last season,'' Dafoe said. ``That bothers me, but I
think it's coming and right now I'm trying to look for victories. I
don't care about my numbers. I'm trying to get the wins for all of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question Dafoe respects the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're big, there's no doubt they like to throw the puck at
the net and crash,'' he said. ``On their power play, they stick
someone right in front and they're very tough to see around and
they do create havoc and that's why they're successful at it. And,
obviously, with the new (crease) rule change, it benefits that type
of team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're pesky, they're big and tough, and they like to stir
things up, no question. It's a very smart hockey team from the
goaltender all the way out.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe realizes the Bruins are still a young team with a few
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team tends to be harder on themselves than the older guys
who have been through this many times before and they know how to
snap out of it,'' Dafoe said. ``That could be a reason as to why we
have slow starts, not being fired up as much as we should be. We're
not walking around with smiles on our faces, but we're not dragging
our heads, either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
