r s BC-FBC-HUSAK-LADN-(SLANG     01-02 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSAK-LADN-(SLANG0 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSAK PUT IN TOO DEEP A HOLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Whether it was accurate or not, Stanford
quarterback Todd Husak didn't have a problem pointing a finger of
blame following Saturday's Rose Bowl loss to Wisconsin. And the
finger was pointed squarely into the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of throws,'' Husak said when asked what was the
difference in the Badgers' 17-9 victory. ``If I make them, we win
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is too simple an explanation for a difficult
loss. Sure, there were a couple of balls that Husak could have
thrown better including one that sailed over a wide-open DeRonnie
Pitts deep down the middle of the field with the Cardinal trailing
by a point in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make a good throw there, it's a touchdown,'' said Husak, a
6-foot-3, 210-pound Long Beach native and St. John Bosco graduate.
Husak completed 17 passes in 34 attempts for 258 yards and didn't
throw a touchdown pass for the first time his 22 starts at
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   But, the errant throws had nothing to do with Stanford's horrid
rushing performance minus-5 yards on 27 attempts. Four sacks for
minus-43 yards contributed greatly to that dismal total.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their quarterback is real good,'' Wisconsin linebacker Donnell
Thompson said. ``But when you shut down the run, they became
one-dimensional. And when they are one-dimensional, they are a lot
easier to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford offensive coordinator Bill Diedrick had a similar view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd didn't lose this game for us,'' Diedrick said. ``It was
pretty much a situation where (Wisconsin) dominated the line of
scrimmage.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's offense entered the Rose Bowl averaging 37 points and
467 yards per game. Their lowest scoring output this year came in
an embarrassing 69-17 season-opening loss to Texas, but the
Cardinal managed to gain 394 yards in that contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're too good of an offense to only score nine points in the
biggest game of the year,'' Husak said. ``It was our biggest stage
of the year, we had the chance to step it up and we didn't. That is
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, in the other locker room there was a different
feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming into the game, you have to expect they will score more
than points,'' Wisconsin safety Jason Doering said. ``This is a
team averaging more than 30 points per game, so we knew they were
capable of putting up big numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers never materialized on Saturday because Wisconsin's
defensive front manhandled a Stanford offensive line playing
without its All Pac-10 center Mike McLaughlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to shut them down because we could read them and
know a little about what they were doing,'' Wisconsin linebacker
Chris Ghidorzi said. ``We made some big plays and had a great
second half. We were having fun out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin kicker Vitaly Pisetsky could have sealed the win with
a 34-yard field goal in the game's final moments, but he missed
wide left and Husak returned with a chance to engineer a game-tying
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Husak began the final drive by connecting with Dave Davis for 5
yards and then hit Tafiti Uso twice for a total of 31 yards to move
the ball to the Wisconsin 45-yard line. After an incomplete pass,
two penalties and a sack, Husak hit Pitts for a 15-yard gain to set
up 4th-and-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the way things went for us all year,'' Husak said.
``We came through when we needed to. I figured that would happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   After a delay-of-game penalty, Husak rolled right and slipped to
the turf while trying to duck Wisconsin defensive end Ben Herbert.
He had intended to stop and throw the ball down the far sideline to
running back Coy Wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I heard, Coy was open on the play,'' Husak said.
``If I could have gotten away from the defender like I've done
hundreds of time, maybe we could have moved the chains. It's one of
those things when we were one big play away.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the big play never came won't soil a tremendous
career that Husak put together. He entered Stanford with little
expectations and leaves as the fifth-leading passer in school
history. But, at least for a while, Husak's thoughts will remain on
how his Stanford career concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played a great defensive game, but I feel like we gave
this one away,'' he said. ``It hurts when you don't get it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
