A4466 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-AMERICA'SCUP-BOS &LR;      01-02 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNER WINS GRUDGE MATCH WITH JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ Last week, Dennis Conner gave Nippon
skipper Peter Gilmour a vicious tongue lashing for consorting with
the enemy. Saturday, Conner's Stars &AMP; Stripes lashed Gilmour again,
beating him in the first day of the semifinal America's Cup trials
by 55 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Both by tradition and percentage, the winner of a match race
among the IACC Class 75-footers is the boat that gets the first
windshift in the beat up the first leg.
</P>
<P>
   That rule held true in all three races Saturday in the opening
of the Louis Vuitton Cup leading to the America's Cup match next
month.
</P>
<P>
   With winds building above 15 knots from the northwest, the six
remaining challengers dueled in choppy seas that flashed with
occasional bursts of sunlight as low, steamy clouds scudded across
Hauraki Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   The grudge match of the day was between Team Dennis Conner in
Stars &AMP; Stripes and Japan's Nippon team sailing in Asura. Conner
derided the Japanese team last week for helping New Zealand in
practice races.
</P>
<P>
   Even Nippon's aggressive skipper _ the native Australian Gilmour
_ was no match for the Stars &AMP; Stripes combination of Ken Read of
Newport, R.I., at the wheel, and 20-year veteran Tom Whidden of
Essex, Conn., calling tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Whirling through a lively prestart sequence, both skippers
struggled for control, but coming off the line, Stars &AMP; Stripes was
positioned to the left and capitalized on a favorable shift as
Whidden kept the dark blue boat from San Diego to the left.
</P>
<P>
   After a drag race to the left for about one minute, Gilmour was
forced to tack away to the right, letting Stars &AMP; Stripes sail
along smoothly in the moderately high winds.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the two crossed paths again, the Japanese boat was
well behind Stars &AMP; Stripes, having sailed slower and getting
forced off to the right side of the course, with Stars &AMP; Stripes
staying closer to the middle.
</P>
<P>
   At the first rounding at the windward mark, Read and Whidden had
given Stars &AMP; Stripes a 17-second lead, one they would build on all
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But even in moderate conditions, a breakdown can strike like
lightning, wipe out a big lead, or take a boat off course. On the
fifth leg, Stars &AMP; Stripes' comfort zone evaporated when the car
got stuck in the spinnaker track, making it impossible to slide the
spinnaker pole into proper position.
</P>
<P>
   For about 2 miles of the leg, crew members worked frantically
with a hacksaw to try cutting the car free, but to no avail. The
crew set the square spinnaker for the final 3 miles, and despite
the pole sticking up at an unwieldy angle, the boat surfed home
through the building seas for a convincing drubbing of Asura.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great race,'' said Whidden, ``and there are going
to be a lot of great races. We got a little jump first and were
glad to have it the way Peter Gilmour kept coming after us all day.
After that first jump, we didn't take much out of them for the rest
of the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Whidden said the afterguard did not ease off a bit to rest on
their lead, as was suggested. ``You can never do that with Gilmour.
We had to keep the hammer down all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   In another matchup of leaders, Italy's Prada took on Dawn
Riley's America True, whose skipper John Cutler forced Prada away
just at the gun to take the slight lead across the starting line.
</P>
<P>
   For a long drag race out to the left, the boats looked fairly
even in pure speed before Prada tacked away looking for a
right-hand advantage. After three more minutes, skipper Francesco
De Angeles wheeled Italy's silver and red hull, Luna Rossa (Red
Moon), back across the course to check in with Riley's canary
yellow America True. Italy was slightly ahead on the right.
</P>
<P>
   Twice more Luna Rossa attacked on starboard, and twice made
important gains on America True. By the top mark, Prada's lead was
13 seconds. But down the run, America True, flying a large
asymmetrical headsail, was not able to take much out of Prada,
which flew a more conventional headsail. By the downwind mark,
Prada had a 24-second lead (2 boat lengths), and powered back up
the second beat, applying only loose cover to America True and
allowing it to stretch the lead to comfortable proportions and win
by a full minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was a good, close race today,'' said Riley. ``I do
the runners (backstay winches), and we had a lot of tacks. It was
one great race, and they got the right side of the course. But
we're pleased with our boat and our speed.''
</P>
<P>
   The third race of the day was between AmericaOne, skippered by
Paul Cayard, and Le Defi Francais, sailed by Bertrand Pace.
</P>
<P>
   From the first mix-up in the prestart maneuvering to the first
drag race up the left side of the course to the windward mark,
Cayard's new boat, hull 61, showed blazing speed, rounding 27
seconds ahead of France and never looking back. On the last leg,
Cayard eased off the accelerator and France edged up, though never
seriously threatening. The margin was 22 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Each boat will sail 10 races in this semifinal round.
</P>
<P>
   Pairings for Sunday feature Stars &AMP; Stripes against Prada,
AmericaOne against America True, and France against Nippon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
