<HEADER>
A4584 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-YEAR-REVIEW03-COX     01-02 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-YEAR-REVIEW03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV 1999: Funny strange, not funny ha-ha
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sitcoms looked pretty sickly and the teen
obsession was a flop, but hourlong dramas made a comeback and one
measly game show changed everything.
</P>
<P>
   Television watchers in 1999 not only chose mature women over
teeny-boppers, they picked Regis Philbin, of all people, over
everybody. It was, to say the least, a curious year trend-wise.
</P>
<P>
   The maturity factor was definitely dominant. The top-rated new
drama last fall was ``Judging Amy,'' about a soft-hearted, late-30s
judge and her sixty-something mother. Close behind was ``Once and
Again,'' about forty-something lovers, and the fast-paced political
saga ``The West Wing.'' The most talked-about new drama last year
was HBO's daring ``The Sopranos,'' about a wacky family of mobsters
led by a cold-blooded but emotionally fragile killer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fox's high-school sudser ``Manchester Prep'' was axed
before its debut, and the promoted-to-death, post-college angst
drama ``Wasteland'' was unwatched-to-death before Thanksgiving. So
much for the networks' plan to revive their sagging viewership with
an infusion of youth.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, acting on a hunch, ABC programming chief Stu
Bloomberg decided to make an American version of a game show that
was a phenomenon in England. There were hopes for its success, but
nobody imagined that ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' would become
a mega-hit. During one of the program's subsequent outings,
``Millionaire'' grabbed seven of the Top 10 slots in the Nielsen
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Conceived as a one-week experiment, ``Millionaire'' will return
for a third run Jan. 11. Its success has spawned Fox's ``Greed''
and two more entries on the horizon: CBS' ``Winning Lines'' (Jan.
8) and NBC's ``Twenty One'' (Jan. 9).
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a decade, there were more new dramas than
sitcoms last fall _ no small surprise given the current economics
of production and syndication. Dramas cost twice as much as sitcoms
to produce and are much more difficult to sell as syndicated
reruns. But that didn't stop the networks from buying more of them
in '99. And the old ones continued to thrive: ``ER'' ruled the
roost in the ratings, followed by such popular hours as ``Touched
by an Angel,'' ``Law &AMP; Order,'' ``The Practice'' and ``The
X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   With the notable exception of ``Will &AMP; Grace'' and, to a less
spectacular degree, ``Stark Raving Mad'' and ``Sports Night''
(which is really more drama than comedy), new sitcoms were
uninspired and unfunny in 1999. ``Oh, Grow Up'' tried to make us
laugh at three guys in their 30s suffering from a bad case of
arrested development, and ``Love and Money'' proposed the exhausted
premise of romance between a wealthy blueblood and a working-class
stiff. Even I can't remember the forgettable ``Then Came You'' _
and I reviewed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace'' has such clever writing and physical comedy
(the episode in which Grace's water bra sprang a leak was a
classic) that hardly anybody has bothered to complain about the
show's gay characters. Maybe Jerry Falwell learned his lesson after
trying to out Tinky Winky.
</P>
<P>
   On the news front, President Clinton's impeachment was old news
and hardly anybody watched the Senate vote in '99. Millions (70
million to be exact) did tune in for Barbara Walters'
mother-daughter chat with Monica Lewinsky, however. The news from
that much-watched debacle? Monica has exquisite taste in lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   The news stories that made the biggest splash on TV in 1999 were
the Columbine High School shootings and the death of John Kennedy
Jr. The Columbine mayhem once again stirred the debate about live
breaking news: Is it helpful, intrusive or dangerous? If the young
killers had access to a TV, they might have seen the live shots of
students escaping and taken action. The Kennedy crash raised
questions of propriety, as the TV networks spent most of a week
treating the death as a national crisis rather than the awful
tragedy it was.
</P>
<P>
   The year also saw a continuation of TV's merger madness. With
audiences shrinking and revenues dwindling, the networks are
offering themselves up for ``big bidness'' marriages. CBS and
Viacom united in a $37 billion deal, the largest media merger in
history (surpassing Disney's acquisition of ABC a few years ago),
bringing together the aging baby boomer programming of CBS and the
youth-skewed shows of Viacom's MTV and Nickelodeon. A less
spectacular deal ($400 million) united General Electric-owned NBC
with Paxson Communications, owner of PAX TV.
</P>
<P>
   As television rolls into the next century _ with the promise or
threat of HDTV and hundreds more channels _ it's anybody's guess
what the next batch of trends will be. Sitcom revival? Death of
newsmagazines? Return of quality miniseries? Anything's possible.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Holloway writes about television for the
Austin-American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
