<DOCNO> NYT20000102.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4612 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-0103-CO     01-02 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-0103-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    THE HARD WORK BEGINS MONDAY IN SYRIA-ISRAEL TALKS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ This time around, it will not be enough to just meet
each other face to face. When Syrian and Israeli negotiators meet
Monday at a secluded West Virginia resort, they confront the tough
details of peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
   The round of talks could last a week to ten days and follows the
breakthrough last month, when the two countries held their first
formal negotiations in almost four years. They are officially in a
state of war.
</P>
<P>
   A peace deal could end Israel's war in southern Lebanon, a
country largely controlled by Syria, and open Israel's relations
with most of the Arab world. Syria could regain control of the
Golan Heights plateau, which Israel captured in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak flew to the talks Sunday after
seeking the support of Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, who leads the powerful
Shas political party. Barak also met with residents of the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings were part of a campaign in preparation for a
referendum required to approve a peace deal, which Barak concedes
will require ``painful'' concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the second day of the new millennium we are on a mission on
behalf of our people to bring security and peace to Israel,'' Barak
said at the Tel Aviv airport. ``We don't need to wait for another
millennium, another century, or even another 10 years to find a way
to make peace with our neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli newspapers reported Sunday that officials in Jerusalem
hoped the meetings will end with a joint statement on the outline
for continued negotiations _ short of the preliminary agreement
originally sought.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. mediators set the talks in Shepherdstown, W. VA., about 70
miles from Washington, in an effort to focus the negotiators and
distance the media. The talks will be held at the Clarion Hotel and
Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister David Levy, en route to Shepherdstown, told
Israel's army radio that Israel will ask Syrian President Hafez
Assad to join the talks to prove he is serious about peace. So far,
protocol at the talks has been unbalanced _ Barak has headed the
Israeli team while Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa heads
the Syrian side.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that the talks are getting to the nitty-gritty, Barak
expanded his small entourage to include former Israeli Army chief
of staff Amnon Lipkin Shahak.
</P>
<P>
   Shahak, now Israel's tourism minister, negotiated with Syrian
military leaders in 1995. They focused on security matters, which
could be the toughest part of the agenda now. At issue is so-called
``demilitarization,'' just how much military might the two
countries can keep near their borders.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in early December, Shahak stressed that Israel
may concede land, but it will not compromise on security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be reasonable, but we are not going to be
flexible on security,'' Shahak said. ``We have to be convinced. The
Israeli people have to be convinced that they are serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Shahak repeated a now-famous question that he asked Syrian
officials during talks three years ago. Why, he asked, does Syria
station most of its large army on the border with Israel, even
though that border is less than five percent of Syria's
international boundaries?
</P>
<P>
   Syrian officials note that their capital, Damascus, is less than
40 miles from Israeli-controlled territory and Israel's army.
Electronic Israeli listening posts can spy on Syrians in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   As Syrian Foreign Minister al-Sharaa flew to the United States
on Sunday, leading his country's delegation, the Syrian press
expressed doubts over Israel's sincerity since the December
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making progress or suffering a failure is in the hands of the
parties in the peace talks _ especially Israel, which did not give
even a single proof of good intentions. All it offered were words
and promises, which no serious progress could be built on,'' the
Syrian daily, al-Thawra, wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's talks will be opened at noon EST by President Clinton,
who will preside over the first day. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright will remain with the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   (The Associated Press contributed to this report).
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow can be reached by e-mail at:
larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
