<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-YEAREND-UNDERWRITERS-     01-02 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAREND-UNDERWRITERS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RACE TO UNDERWRITE NEARLY SETS A RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Graphics  are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Wall Street, the 1990s ended in a virtual dead
heat.
</P>
<P>
   The total amount of money raised in the United States by
investment banks, $2.1 trillion, almost reached the record amount
raised in 1998. And the total number of stock and bond offerings in
American markets _ 17,030 _ also fell just shy of the 1998 total,
according to Thomson Financial/Securities Data.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in many ways, 1999 was a phenomenal year that will be
remembered on Wall Street mostly for its feverish market for
first-time stock offerings and for the era of European mega-mergers
it ushered in. ``It was a pretty extraordinary year in a whole
bunch of respects,'' said Mark Tercek, co-head of the
stock-underwriting business at Goldman Sachs Group.
</P>
<P>
   Never before had investors pumped so much money into shares of
companies selling stock for the first time, many of them
technology-based start-ups that had not earned a nickel of profit.
Never before had the shares of so many newly public companies
proceeded to soar, routinely doubling and often tripling from their
offering prices.
</P>
<P>
   Previous years are linked in the minds of many investors to the
spectacular debuts of particular companies: Netscape in 1995, Yahoo
in 1996, eBay in 1998. But 1999 was so chock-full of stock
offerings that rose like rockets, it is likely to be remembered for
its strength and breadth, rather than for specific success stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The powerful aftermarket performance has been in the tech,
telecom and media area,'' said Richard Kauffman, managing director
of stock underwriting at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. ``If a
company is outside that area, it is very hard to get deals done.''
</P>
<P>
   As is usually the case, at least 90 cents of every dollar raised
from investors came through sales of bonds, but the $2 trillion
American bond market drew relatively scant attention. Certainly, it
was a year in which technology stocks reigned and almost all other
investments got short shrift.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is truly a reflection that this whole notion about this new
economy that everyone's talking about, is, in fact, real,'' said
Alan Sheriff, managing director of stock underwriting at Credit
Suisse First Boston. To understand just how much the sands have
shifted, Sheriff said, ``Don't just look at what deals got done,
look at what didn't get done.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of a small number of big stock offerings by
blue-chip corporations, such as United Parcel Service's $5.47
billion initial public offering, traditional industries barely
tapped the American stock market in 1999. In general, investment
bankers wanted to sell stock for two kinds of companies: dominant,
extremely profitable franchises or anything with a dot-com attached
to it.
</P>
<P>
   Two investment banks separated themselves from the competition,
underwriting plenty of both kinds of stocks. Goldman Sachs and
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. ran neck-and-neck all year as the
leading managers of stock offerings, which yield considerably
bigger fees than bond offerings do.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Goldman, Sachs came out ahead, raising $33.7 billion
to Morgan Stanley's $32.7 billion. Goldman's own initial public
offering, which raised $3.66 billion in May and transformed the
last big private partnership on Wall Street, made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the perennial leader in total underwriting,
though not this year in fees, ranked a distant third in stock
underwriting with $17.8 billion, followed closely by Credit Suisse
First Boston. Powered by the technology banking team it hired away
from Deutsche Bank, First Boston became a formidable competitor to
the biggest investment banks in stock underwriting. First Boston
managed 111 offerings that raised $15 billion last year, up from
just $4.5 billion in 34 offerings in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill again was the dominant underwriter of bonds, raising
$299 billion through more than 1,800 offerings in a year that was
disrupted by concerns about whether the coming of the year 2000
would alter investor behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Quigley, head of Merrill's global debt-origination business,
said corporate borrowers rushed to issue bonds, in some cases in
mammoth offerings, in the first half of the year out of fear that
demand would dry up as the year-end approached. For their part,
investors stored up cash with the hope of swooping in on bargains
created by the anticipated dislocation in bond markets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fourth quarter, people realized that that investment
strategy was somewhat flawed and they had to fast-forward their
investment plans,'' Quigley said. ``Those fears really dissipated
and money started coming back in the marketplace. We finished the
year pretty strong.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Quigley said he expected that strength to carry into January, as
some borrowers rushed to sell bonds before the Federal Reserve
Board meets again in early February. The Fed governors are widely
expected to raise interest rates again at that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mark Siegel, the head of Morgan Stanley's bond-underwriting
business, said the most notable development in 1999 was the speed
with which corporations, such as Ford Motor and DuPont, were able
to sell billions of dollars' worth of bonds to investors around the
world. In one case last fall, he said, Morgan Stanley rounded up
buyers for $7 billion of DuPont bonds in 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great example of the tremendous liquidity in the
market,'' Siegel said. ``The fourth quarter was the slowest quarter
of the year in terms of new-issue volume but activity didn't fall
off a cliff as some were expecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said an ongoing boom in corporate mergers and
acquisitions should continue to fuel activity in the bond markets.
``Some borrowers have pent-up financing needs that they've delayed
because of concerns over Y2K,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the year, Morgan Stanley and Goldman, Sachs also
battled with Merrill for the crown in mergers and acquisitions.
Each of the three New York-based firms advised on deals announced
in 1999 with a combined value of more than $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman ranked first, with 417 deals globally, worth $1.3
trillion. Morgan Stanley edged out Merrill Lynch, with each
advising on deals worth about $1.1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As long as the economies in Europe and the United States remain
healthy, merger activity is likely to continue unabated, said
Steven Heller, the head of Goldman's mergers business. ``It is hard
to find a geographic or industry sector that will not be active''
in 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A wave of mergers swept across Europe in 1999, some of them
leaping across national borders and others having a distinctly
American, hostile flavor to them. At year-end, Vodafone AirTouch, a
British telecommunications company, was pressing an unsolicited
$148 billion bid for Mannesmann of Germany. Goldman is Vodafone's
main adviser and Morgan Stanley and Merrill are among the firms
advising Mannesmann on its defense.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Levy, the head of Merrill's mergers business, predicted
that 2000 would be a much bigger year for mergers. ``The celestial
bodies are all going to be in alignment this year for a very, very
active merger business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One big factor, Levy said, will be the pressure some American
companies will feel to complete acquisitions before accounting rule
changes eliminate transactions structured as ``poolings of
interests,'' in which the acquiring company simply combines the
other company's financial statements. Levy said he also expected
financial-services companies to take advantage of recent changes in
laws that have kept banks, investment banks and insurance companies
out of one another's businesses for decades.
</P>
<P>
   All told, investment banks took in about $3.23 billion in fees
for advising on mergers that were consummated in 1999, up about 11
percent from $2.9 billion in 1998, according to Securities Data.
That came on top of $12.1 billion in disclosed fees from
underwriting sales of stock and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley came out ahead of Goldman, Sachs in fees from
underwriting that were reported to Securities Data, taking in about
$1.9 billion, compared with about $1.75 billion for Goldman, Sachs.
Merrill Lynch, which ranked third with $1.5 billion in fees, was
the only one of the top five firms to take in less in fees for
underwriting last year than in 1998.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Those standings demonstrate how much more lucrative it is to
underwrite stocks than bonds. Investment banks receive as much as 7
percent of the proceeds from initial public offerings of stock,
compared with fractions of 1 percent of the proceeds from big
corporate bond offerings.
</P>
<P>
   That is why investment bankers are cheering for a continuation
of the boom in initial stock offerings and are happy to see newly
public technology companies lining up to sell more stock in
follow-on offerings. ``There could be more IPOs this year than last
year,'' said Tercek of Goldman. ``But we think there could be more
volume done on the follow-on side. It's going to be the follow-ons
that make or break those companies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-00 1612EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
