<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-YEAREND-WORLD-ART-NYT     01-02 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAREND-WORLD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN STOCKS OUTPERFORMED U.S. EQUITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Americans have not shopped abroad for stocks with
fervor since 1993. And the truth is, they have had little need to
wander the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the three major American stock indexes produced
double-digit returns for the fifth year in a row _ an unprecedented
feat _ and the technology-heavy Nasdaq index popped off the old
charts.
</P>
<P>
   But investors with wanderlust were probably rewarded in 1999.
After running well ahead of the pack for four years, the American
stock market trailed the foreign market average. From 1995 through
1998, U.S. stocks outperformed those everywhere else by an average
of 22.9 percentage points a year, according to performance indexes
compiled by Morgan Stanley Capital International.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, though, the rest of the world's stock markets, taken
as a whole, rose 28.8 percent, well ahead of the 20.9 percent gain
in the United States, according to Morgan Stanley.
   Stocks in emerging markets bounced back from a dismal 1998 to
lead the way with a gain of 63.7 percent. Europe, which was fairly
competitive with the United States in 1997 and 1998, did well again
for local investors. But the unexpected decline of Europe's new
11-nation currency, the euro, against the dollar, eroded most of
the gains for American investors. The Morgan Stanley index of the
11 euro markets and Britain, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland climbed
14.1 percent in dollar terms last year. In local currency, the
index gained 27.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the big surprise was Japan, whose stocks rose 60.6
percent in dollar terms after a decade in the doldrums. From its
high at the end of 1989, the Japanese stock market plunged 58
percent in dollar terms to its low in October 1998. Even with this
year's rally, Japanese stocks are still 16.1 percent below their
1989 peak in dollar terms.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Japanese equities, Americans have been
selling more foreign stocks than they have been buying in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   But that could change. Many Americans are noticing that their
portfolios are not doing as well as the big-name stock indexes
might suggest. At the end of the year, according to Salomon Smith
Barney, about two-thirds of the stocks traded on the New York Stock
Exchange were at least 20 percent below their 52-week highs.
</P>
<P>
   And a failure of U.S. stock indexes to meet investors' extremely
high expectations could spur more portfolio adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   Abby Joseph Cohen, the market strategist at Goldman Sachs, says
that opportunities in foreign markets could become attractive to
American investors this year. ``We see two catalysts for increased
U.S. participation in non-U.S. equities,'' she wrote in her Year
2000 outlook. ``First, if U.S. returns are good, not great,
investors may be willing to move out along the perceived risk
curve. Second, global economic conditions are less worrisome than
they have been in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally last year in emerging markets was powered by a
faster-than-expected improvement in local economies, especially in
Asia, and the ease with which Brazil and its investors negotiated
that country's currency decline last January.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best performers in dollar terms were: Russia, up 246.2
percent; Turkey, up 244.4 percent; Malaysia, 111.6 percent;
Indonesia, 92 percent; South Korea, 90.2 percent; India, 84.7
percent; and Brazil, 73 percent. Except for South Korea, all these
markets had fallen sharply in 1998. Russia's stock index, in dollar
terms, is still 141 percent from its 1997 high, although it rallied
sharply New Year's Eve on the news of President Boris Yeltsin's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The leading performers among major companies in emerging markets
were: Infosys Technologies of India, up 858.3 percent; SK Telecom
of South Korea, up 620.9 percent; and United Microelectronics of
Taiwan, up 228.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts contend that these markets, which suffered during
the global financial crisis of 1997 and 1998, should outdo Wall
Street again this year, though performance in one year is no
guarantee of future returns.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Pelosky, global emerging-markets strategist at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, said that gains could become more concentrated
in a few big and well-known companies, mirroring some of the shift
to a narrow group of leaders in the American stock market. ``The
top 100 stocks in the Morgan Stanley emerging- markets index have
already significantly outperformed the rest of the stocks in the
index this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in European stocks was led by technology, media and
telecommunications companies, as was the American stock market.
Over the last three months, the technology, media and
telecommunications stocks in a Merrill Lynch index of European
stocks have jumped 57 percent while the rest of the stocks in the
index are up just 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The top gainers included: Nokia of Finland, up 194.7 percent,
Ericsson of Sweden, up 168.9 percent; and Deutsche Telekom of
Germany, up 116.3 percent. The best markets, in dollar terms, were:
Finland, up 150.7 percent; France, up 28 percent; and Germany, up
18.7 percent. Italy fell 1.5 percent while Belgium plunged 15.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   This year could be more difficult for European stocks if, as
some analysts expect, the rebound in economic growth there is
strong enough to force the European Central Bank to start raising
interest rates. Higher rates make financing more costly for
companies and serve to depress corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reasonably cautious on the European market for the
year,'' said Plum Shipton, European equity strategist for Merrill
Lynch in London, because of the threat of higher interest rates and
the already high valuation of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, investors began scrambling back into stocks as the
government worked to shore up the banking system and as the first
signs of economic recovery appeared. The rush of mutual fund
managers and institutional investors _ who had ignored Japan for
years _ was one of the more important market moves of 1999. Their
purchases of Japanese stocks increased demand for the yen and
pushed the currency to a four-year high against the dollar. The
yen's surge forced the Japanese government to intervene repeatedly
in the currency markets in a futile attempt to curb the currency's
rise, lest Japanese exports be priced out of foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   Like Europe and the United States, much of the stock rally in
Japan has come on the back of technology and telecommunications
stocks. And like Europe, Japan provided a currency lesson for
American investors. In this case, it was a positive one, with about
25 percent of the returns posted by American investors coming from
the rise in the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Among the big stocks to post outsized gains were Softbank Corp.,
up 1,485 percent, but still well below its 1996 high, and Kyocera
Corp., up 389.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Allan, a senior vice president and longtime Japan
watcher at Scudder Kemper Investments, says the pace of economic
growth bears watching. ``Many Japanese are still worried about
losing their jobs,'' she said, and that fear is dampening the
consumer spending needed to push the economy ahead. ``Increased
consumer spending is key for a second leg of the economic
recovery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
