<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Jan. 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vigorous low pressure moving northeast from the central
Mississippi Valley will produce widespread inclement weather from
the eastern Plains to the interior Northeast. Rain will be locally
heavy near the path of the low-pressure center as it moves from
eastern Missouri early Monday to the eastern Great Lakes Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   As the low strengthens Monday afternoon, gusty winds will import
colder air through the Great Lakes states into the central
Mississippi Valley. As a result, rain will mix with snow and some
sleet over parts of the central and southern Great Lakes states
Monday afternoon. The mixture will change to snow overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Farther to the southwest, the rain will change quickly to snow
in the southern Missouri valley Monday where accumulations up to a
few inches are possible. Meanwhile, the northern Plains will have
chilly winds and scattered light snow and flurries.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the East Coast states will be unusually mild, but chilly
air will linger north of a front in northern New England. Some
sunshine will bathe areas of the Middle Atlantic and Southeast
coast where temperatures in the 60s and 70s will be common. Clouds
will thicken near the Appalachians as showers approach from the
west. A few thunderstorms will precede a cold front in the interior
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Chilly air will cover most of the West. Rain and mountain snow
will develop near the northwest coast as a warm front approaches.
Elsewhere in the West, generally dry weather will prevail, although
a few mountain snow showers will occur in the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Cold Bay's Coldest
</P>
<P>
   In much of the contiguous United States, a mild December
punctuated another very mild year. In stark contrast, Cold Bay,
Alaska, lived up to its name by measuring its coldest December and
coldest year on record. Cold Bay is 30 miles from the end of the
Alaskan peninsula at the beginning of the Aleutian archipelago.
Arctic air masses approaching from the interior of the state are
typically modified by the surrounding waters. In the past year an
unusual number of surges of chill from over the frozen waters of
the Bering Sea to the north led to the record chill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-00 1635EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
