<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KHOSLA-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINOD KHOSLA, PHILOSOPHER-KING OF HIGH-TECH VENTURE CAPITALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in grafs 9, 15 and 20 instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a late Friday afternoon in December, when most Silicon Valley
executives were heading to their Napa Valley estates for the
weekend, Vinod Khosla was tucked away in his office in Menlo Park,
Calif., talking about God.
</P>
<P>
   As an 11-year-old growing up in his native India, he says, he
came to believe that organized religion was just a centuries-old
form of social control; a fear of God was the only way to make an
unruly population behave.
</P>
<P>
   But such notions now are outdated, he says, adding that in the
next 100 years, ``traditional religion will be as relevant as witch
doctors are today.'' That is especially true, he continues, for
religious leaders like the pope, who ``chooses to talk about gays,
abortion and priests not being women, when he could use his power
in better ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Such ideas from one of Silicon Valley's premier venture
capitalists are not standard dot-com fare. But then, Khosla, a
partner in Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, is far from typical.
In the 15 years he has been a Kleiner Perkins partner, he has had
little time for small thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Khosla started his first company at age 25. Two years later, he
co-founded Sun Microsystems. At age 44, his vision has turned
metaphysical, to a time when human thought melds with computer
intelligence, blurring the lines between people and machines.
</P>
<P>
   But four years ago, ideas of a more immediate and practical
nature resulted in his most ambitious project to date. He was
struck by the notion that as the Internet was transformed into a
mass medium, telecommunications companies would soon need equipment
to push data over fiber optic networks faster and more cheaply. No
such technology existed at the time. So Khosla, who typically
concentrates on investing in promising companies, set out to find a
team of entrepreneurs to create the next generation of computer
networking.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, optical networking, as the idea came to be known, was
one of the hottest new areas in the technology sector, reaping rich
rewards for Khosla, Kleiner Perkins and the companies they had
backed. To name just the highlights, Cerent Corp. was sold to Cisco
Systems for $7.3 billion in stock, the most ever paid for a private
technology company; Siara Systems, which has yet to test a product,
announced in November it was being sold to Redback Networks for an
astounding $4.3 billion in stock; and Juniper Networks, a maker of
optical networking equipment, has seen its shares jump 900 percent
since it went public in June, giving it a market value of more than
$17.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Khosla's personality both attracts and repels.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is probably the biggest thinker I have ever seen,'' said
Joe Kraus, a co-founder of Excite, the Kleiner Perkins-backed
search engine that merged last year with another of the firm's
companies, the high-speed cable Internet service (At)Home. ``But
the challenge is in the presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   Khosla is often described as abrasive and overbearing, a
busybody who is loath to let entrepreneurs run their own show. But
loyalists say his strength is the ability to spot opportunities
that others miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say I can be too `in love' with my companies,'' he
says. ``But I've earned the freedom to be honest and more blunt.''
On his desk sits a Beanie Baby rhinoceros given to him by his four
children as a reminder of how bruising he can be. But ultimately
the only thing that matters, he says, ``is whether entrepreneurs
come back or not.''
</P>
<P>
   And come back they do, if only because his laserlike focus
commands attention in a Valley filled with white noise and hype.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Russo, Cerent's former chief executive, said some in
Silicon Valley use a Hollywood metaphor to describe Khosla: ``Vinod
is the worst director of movies, but he is the best picker of
scripts.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many who have worked closely with Khosla say they would
consider it again. Among them is Kraus, who met Khosla, an early
backer of Excite, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd need a vacation before I decided to do that again,''
allows Kraus, now a senior vice president of content at
Excite(AT)Home. ``But I'd do it.''
</P>
<P>
   This from a man whose ideas Khosla once described as ``amateur
hour.'' Worse, on April Fool's Day in 1996, Khosla tricked Kraus,
then 25 years old, into believing that Excite's public stock
offering had been canceled hours before the stock began trading.
(Khosla said he let Kraus stew for a half-hour before letting him
in on the joke.)
</P>
<P>
   But in the summer of 1996, their relationship nearly ended.
Kraus recalls one afternoon when Khosla had chided him once too
many times about an executive Khosla disliked. ``I absolutely lost
it,'' Kraus says of the incident. ``I hung up on him. After that, I
sat there stunned in my chair.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, Kraus' cellular phone rang. ``Vinod was on
the phone, laughing,'' Kraus recalls. ``He said, `That's so
good.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was classic Vinod.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this characteristic of unrelentingness,'' says George
Bell, the president of Excite(AT)Home. ``At the end of the day, you
just want to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Such tales make Khosla cringe. For him, playing devil's advocate
_ no matter how painful it can be _ is essential to helping
entrepreneurs think critically. ``I like having impact,'' he says.
``They'll also tell you that they didn't doubt my loyalty or my
passion.'' Still, to make sure entrepreneurs he has not worked with
know what is in store, he demands that they speak to past
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Khosla grew up in New Delhi, where he earned a degree in
electrical engineering from the Indian Institute of Technology. In
1976, he moved to the United States with his childhood girlfriend,
now his wife, Neeru, and got a master's degree in biomedical
engineering from Carnegie-Mellon University. He then moved to Palo
Alto, Calif., where he earned an MBA at Stanford University in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That year he co-founded his first company, Daisy Systems, a
now-defunct concern that specialized in computer-aided design. But
more importantly, he began formulating his ideas about networking
computers. He wanted to build a workstation that would handle the
complex operations that a mainframe computer could, but that was
inexpensive and easy to assemble.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, a Stanford secretary suggested that Khosla meet a
German graduate student, Andreas Bechtolsheim, who was then
licensing such a computer design for $10,000 to local companies.
Khosla suggested they build it themselves, and in February 1982,
Sun Microsystems was born. Khosla became chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   While the two men remain close friends, Khosla's intensity was
too much for the corporate suite, say former associates. Scott
McNealy, a friend who shared a townhouse with Khosla and his wife
at one time, had joined Sun at Khosla's urging and was later named
president. But while Khosla was credited with the vision to build a
Fortune 500 company, he was not as smooth as McNealy. So in 1984,
Khosla was replaced by his former roommate. Friends say he was
devastated.
</P>
<P>
   Today he says, ``I think I helped in some way to change the way
computing was done.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, Khosla, then a 30-year-old multimillionaire,
joined Kleiner but also indulged in a number of diversions. He took
up skydiving and whitewater rafting, undertook a worldwide search
to find an architect to build his Portola Valley home in the style
of Frank Lloyd Wright, threw away his calendar for a year and
started renovating a vineyard on his property. Today, his Three Dog
Vineyards, named for his pets, makes 1,000 bottles of cabernet
sauvignon a year.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Not all his early Kleiner ventures were blessed. One troubled
company was Go Corp., which in the late 1980s promised the first
pen-operated computer. After spending six years and more than $75
million, Go went bust. Khosla also had a hand in the 3DO Co., a
game maker that has survived but failed to deliver as promised.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many in the Valley say Khosla most excels at networking _ and
they're not just talking about a system for connecting computers.
For example, Khosla met Pradeep Sindhu, the entrepreneur behind
Juniper Networks, through Bechtolsheim in early 1996. At the time,
he says, Sindhu was trying to figure out how to make cheaper
routers. Khosla suggested he try to make them more efficient
instead and provided $200,000 in seed money.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions helped crystallize Khosla's ideas about optical
networking. Later that year, he met another entrepreneur who wanted
to increase network efficiency. That relationship spawned two
companies: Cerent, which now makes boxes to increase traffic over
networks, and Siara, which is still developing a product. And
Khosla says he is backing several other companies in the optical
networking field.
</P>
<P>
   If Khosla cherishes anything besides work, which he calls his
``hobby,'' it is his children. ``I still cut my 11-year-old
daughter's hair,'' he says, giggling with delight. ``I love taking
the girls shopping for clothes. I like to hear them talk.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The walls of his office are plastered with their photographs,
and his assistant keeps a log of how many times he misses dinner
with his family. Last June was a bad month: He was away eight
nights.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He often loads the family into their GMC Suburban, he says, and
heads to Big Sur, where he built a house with stunning views of the
Pacific. Like most Silicon Valley tycoons, he has a trophy car, a
Lamborghini, but the car, like his personal wealth, is not
discussed. Whatever the accuracy of Forbes magazine's estimate that
he is worth more than $1 billion, Khosla's good life includes
annual family trips to Aspen, Hawaii and Deer Valley.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of a two-hour interview, Khosla has steered the
conversation to what inspires him most _ the future of technology.
One day, human thoughts will be downloaded into computers, he
predicts. ``Experience is a collection of memories and rules that
get imbedded in the brain,'' he observes. ``So when is a human not
a computer?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He then falls silent, in a rare moment of self-consciousness.
``I should shut up,'' he says finally. ``I don't want to sound
weird.''
</P>
<P>
   But such notions are already legend among those who know him
well. Bechtolsheim says his friend's fascination with the
relationship of religion and computers drives him professionally as
well as personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's impressed by the power of the pope and is probably trying
to see how he can replicate it at a high-tech company,''
Bechtolsheim chuckles. ``It's the ultimate leverage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
