<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4633 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-Y2K-MAIN-0103-COX     01-02 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-MAIN-0103-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EXPERTS LOOK FOR LINGERING Y2K BUGS AS BUSINESSES OPEN MONDAY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As factories, doctors' offices, banks and other
businesses resume full operations Monday, computer experts will be
watching for Y2K bugs to pop out.
</P>
<P>
   But countries that already have resumed their work week after
the holiday reported no significant Y2K problems on Sunday,
suggesting computers will also operate smoothly in the United
States. For example, stock markets in Kuwait and Egypt opened
Sunday and reported no computer glitches.
</P>
<P>
   With each upbeat report, computer monitors around the world have
been growing more confident about declaring victory over the Y2K
bug, a software flaw that could have caused older computers to
misinterpret the year ``00,'' misreading it as 1900 rather than
2000. That flaw had the potential to cause massive failures of
computerized equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have worked hardest on the problem, there is ``a
great sense of relief and accomplishment,'' John Koskinen,
President Clinton's top Y2K adviser, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the triumph over Y2K appears so sweeping that many
skeptics are now saying the effort to avert computer meltdown
amounted to overkill. They question whether the U.S. government
needed to spend $8.5 billion fixing federal computers.
</P>
<P>
   But Koskinen said he knows of no corporate chief executives who
think the $100 billion they spent was a waste. As business owners
tested their computers, they discovered serious Y2K problems that
could have shut down operations on Jan. 1. The effort to wipe out
those bugs was so intensive and successful that naysayers now
wrongly think there never was a problem. ``Maybe we made it look
too easy,'' Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Y2K skeptics are pointing to the quiet date rollover in
smaller countries, saying that despite minimal spending in such
places, computers did not fail.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said there are three reasons why less developed
countries did so well. For one, smaller countries have far fewer
computers, so they had less to fix, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Second, those countries tend to use standardized software taken
``off the shelf,'' he said. That means the expensive checking and
testing was done by wealthy countries, and poorer nations were able
to obtain standardized ``patches'' developed by others.
</P>
<P>
   And third, poorer countries were able to absorb the lessons
learned by rich countries, he said. Some equipment that programmers
initially feared would have Y2K problems turned out to be in good
shape. Those programmers were then able to tell their poorer
counterparts what not to bother checking so they could focus their
efforts where most needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said that in some ways, the Y2K bug has left the world
a better place by spurring international cooperation on information
technology. Also, the tests for Y2K bugs have forced businesses and
governmental agencies to complete inventories of equipment and
software and better organize those systems. For example, the
federal government retired about 20 percent of its computerized
systems, leaving agencies with more consolidated and updated
operations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Sunday on the CBS program ``Face the Nation,'' Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson agreed that federal expenditures on Y2K
fixes have prepared the country for the new century. ``This was
worth it,'' he said. ``In this case the fizzle was good.''
</P>
<P>
   (Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is mgeewax(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
