<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FANMAKER-BOOK-REVIEW-     01-02 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANMAKER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE FAN-MAKER'S INQUISITION': THE REVOLUTION, WITH A SADISTIC
SPIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review) 
(js) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A fan is like the thighs of a woman,'' is the first line of
``The Fan-Maker's Inquisition,'' Rikki Ducornet's new novel, and
that simile summons up contradictory reactions. For one thing it is
a bit of a stretch, and that gives it a contrived, even a smug
quality. But it is also a provocative image, the fan that opens and
closes like Ms. Ducornet's story itself, which soon unfolds into a
knowing, smoldering historical tableau. By the end of this novel,
which is set in revolutionary France, Ms. Ducornet has taken us on
a moral and philosophical journey through two highly fraught
epochs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fan-Maker's Inquisition'' is an impressive performance by
a novelist whose vocabulary sweats with a kind of lyrical heat. But
impressive as Ms. Ducornet is as a stylist and a reimaginer of
historical passions, her novel is not so much a story or an
intrigue as a series of discourses, which, interesting and eloquent
though they may be, do not provide for much narrative momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ducornet, whose previous books, including ``Entering Fire''
and ``The Jade Cabinet,'' have explored the connections between
history and eroticism, sets this new novel inside a revolutionary
courtroom in Paris. A fan maker named Gabrielle, a coolly liberal
woman, is being questioned by what is identified simply as the
Comite, which is enforcing the revolution at its most repressive
and puritanical.
</P>
<P>
   One area of inquiry is Gabrielle's friendship with the notorious
libertine the Marquis de Sade, who is in prison for sexual
offenses. A painted fan showing naked figures, including an aroused
Sade, that has been seized in Gabrielle's studio is another. And so
is a subversive manuscript that Gabrielle has written with Sade, a
book that tells the cruelly demented history of the Spanish
Inquisition in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom scene is presented as a kind of annotated
transcript. The Comite asks questions or gives orders (``Are you a
Christian?''), and Gabrielle responds (``I've had since infancy an
allergy to nuns and priests''). She also reads aloud from letters
that Sade has sent her from prison, and she recites extracts from
the book they have written together.
</P>
<P>
   As the trial proceeds, a tableau of religious and revolutionary
fanaticism takes shape, one in which the French Revolution with its
daily quota of heads falling into baskets echoes the Inquisition
perpetrated by the mad and murderous Bishop Landa two centuries
before.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ducornet works out this theme with considerable rhetorical
verve and imagination. Her Sade, who speaks to us on his own in the
second half of the novel (the trial of Gabrielle having ended), is
a compelling figure, full of bitter wit and sarcastic rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Revolution has embraced sexual prudery with the same
passion a necrophiliac embraces corpses,'' he says at one point.
``Robespierre _ I know his type well _ hates a good time.''
Similarly, Ms. Ducornet's scenes of righteous, God-inspired carnage
in the Maya city of Mani, where Bishop Landa's sleep is troubled by
erotic dreams, are exercises in a kind of condensed horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, when he saw a bell rope hanging, Landa imagined
himself dangling at the end. But then he recalled the nefarious
influences under which the imagination _ that most dangerous of
human faculties _ fell sway. Unchecked, it is the imagination that
causes the most havoc, he would remind himself. And so he chased
this image from his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, one wants to ask, what does all this eloquence add up to?
Ms. Ducornet seems intent on drawing lessons from episodes of
historical fanaticism. But the lessons she draws have a warmed-over
quality: that imagination is dangerous to political power, and it
was for acts of the imagination that Sade was punished; that
revolutions cannot tolerate sensual liberation; that murder is an
act of sexual repression; that those responsible for the
revolution's many severed heads were more criminal than those, like
Sade, who rotted in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``The libertine acts upon his instincts knowing that the world
is without God and that his actions are impelled by his nature,''
Gabrielle reads in a letter from Sade. ``The corrupt ecclesiastic
acts in the name of God to justify, as Landa did, the worst crimes.
The crimes done in God's name are always the worst, crimes that the
libertine only imagines in his black room lit by fairy lights.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem, not successfully surmounted by Ms. Ducornet, has to
do with the device of the trial itself. The interrogator for the
Comite here is simply not very convincing, especially in his
condemnation of Sade's and Gabrielle's anticlerical sentiment. At
times the interrogator uses the sort of profane language that might
be used in The New Yorker these days but that seems out of place in
an 18th-century courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   The transcript also reproduces cries from the courtroom gallery
(``The whore's an atheist!'') and bracketed descriptions of
Gabrielle (``She clenches her fists, perhaps to keep from
trembling'') that appear unlikely in a trial transcript. In other
words Ms. Ducornet, searching for dramatic effect, cheats a bit on
her own format, and this robs her novel of some of its originality.
</P>
<P>
   This is too bad, especially given that Ms. Ducornet's concepts _
the fan maker herself, the correspondence with Sade, the subversive
manuscript showing the crimes that can be committed in the name of
God _ are unusual and compelling. Robespierre once said that terror
was an emanation of virtue. Ms. Ducornet, in making that idea the
center of a work of fiction, has produced a novel with serious
flaws. But she also shows herself to be a writer of eloquence and
an unsparing vision that, while not fully honed in this book, is
often startling and evocative.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   THE FAN-MAKER'S INQUISITION
</P>
<P>
   By Rikki Ducornet
</P>
<P>
   212 pages. Henry Holt. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-00 1717EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000102.0036 </DOCNO>
