<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4645 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TIMES-SQUARE-NOTEBOOK     01-02 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMES-SQUARE-NOTEBOOK-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: THE PARTY'S NEVER OVER IN THE NEW TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York awoke on Saturday morning to discover that
Times Square was still there. Perhaps the place should be checked
every morning. Times Square, after all, is dedicated to the passing
moment. When its moment passes, the spirits of place will not look
back for long.
</P>
<P>
   But until that day comes, Times Square will remain the ultimate
crossroads of space and time. These dimensions warped into a
heightened configuration on Friday night, when thousands gathered
to watch the ball drop as the Earth revolved New York City into the
new millennium's dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Even ephemeral things have a history, however. And the spectacle
we see at Times Square first took shape in 1932 in the imagination
of the German architect Oskar Nitzchke.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Nitzchke began to design a project he called la
Maison de la Publicite (Publicity House). Intended for a site on
the Champs-Elysees, the proposed building featured what people
would later call a media wall. An immense crane, attached to the
building's roof line, would be constantly at work, arranging and
rearranging an ever-changing array of illuminated commercial signs
deployed across a metal grid facade.
</P>
<P>
   Though the project was never realized, Nitzchke's media wall has
haunted the minds of architects ever since, most notably, perhaps,
the Anglo-Italian team of Richard Rogers and Renzo Piano.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, when the team presented its winning design for the
Pompidou Center in Paris, Rogers and Piano proposed that such a
wall be erected on the main facade of the immense cultural
supermarket. In addition to the exterior escalator, one of the
world's most popular attractions, the wall would be encrusted with
electronic signs and projection screens.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Nitzchke's plan, this apparatus was intended to
disseminate social and cultural information rather than to promote
commercial wares. In their presentation drawings, the Pompidou's
architects included images of soldiers in the Vietnam war. A ``Live
Center of Information'' was how they defined the entire project.
But their wall, too, remained unbuilt.
</P>
<P>
   It is helpful to keep these two precedents in mind when you gaze
around Times Square these days. Many New Yorkers profess to be
appalled by what they see there. They rant about Disneyfication,
about media power, as if it would be better for these potent
cultural and economic forces to remain unexpressed in the urban
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Henry James didn't like the skyscrapers of Wall Street,
and Lewis Mumford didn't like Rockefeller Center. No one ever
accused New Yorkers of being less than expert at not liking things.
</P>
<P>
   To my eye, however, Times Square has become something
extraordinary: It is one large building turned inside out: a
megastructure de la publicite. Though composed of individual
towers, built by different developers, designed by different
architects and inhabited by different tenants, the place is driven
by a single purpose: distraction.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings form a continuous grid on which the signs
advertise various options for distraction even as they provide a
spectacular version of it.
</P>
<P>
   Distraction was the subject of an important book by Siegfried
Kracauer, Nitzchke's contemporary and fellow German. First
published in 1930 in Frankfurter Zeitung, one of Germany's most
prestigious papers in the Weimar period, Kracauer's ``Salaried
Masses'' analyzes the restlessness of the country's white-collar
workers. It is a chilling essay.
</P>
<P>
   Before the rise of Hitler it depicted the conditions that
enabled a dictator to attain power. Cut loose from cultural
tradition, the country's middle class sought escapes into the
fantasy world provided by what Kracauer called the ``distraction
industries,'' or what we would call mass media and popular
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Thus primed, the public was ready to be held in thrall by the
pageantry of Nazism and the party's simplistic narrative of
national redemption. The audience for the big fantasy was prepared
to embrace the Big Lie.
</P>
<P>
   At Times Square the distraction industries have been coaxed into
exposing themselves in public, urban space. And they do so at a
time when they are among the leading industries in the world today.
The spectacle is both marvelous and horrifying. A place of
indiscriminate illusion, it also sits on a bedrock of truth.
</P>
<P>
   Look one way, you see MTV. Shift your gaze, and behold Nasdaq.
Not since Versailles, perhaps, has a society's cultural essence
been so accurately portrayed. And it is better to have them out in
the open in the heart of the city than dispersed via cables and
airways.
</P>
<P>
   A vision of Times Square as Media Central was sketched out in
The New York Times in November 1992, in an article that included
designs by Tibor Kalman, James Wines, Studio Asymptote and Hodgetts
&AMP; Fung. After the collapse of the original plan to build four
office towers of nearly identical design, to house investment firms
and the like, it occurred to this observer that a golden
opportunity had arisen.
</P>
<P>
   The redevelopment of Times Square could revitalize the meaning
of the street. It could bring together in urban space the producers
and consumers of information and popular entertainment. Investment
and law firms had little to do with the historic identity of the
place. The street offered an ideal medium for bringing modern media
giants into physical proximity with their audience.
</P>
<P>
   This concept has now been realized on a scale that was scarcely
imaginable just seven years ago. The result is a geographic
concentration of publishing, entertainment and news organizations
without historical precedent. The creation of storefront
broadcasting studios, record outlets, movie theaters and live
performance spaces has, in turn, generated street life of
unparalleled vitality.
</P>
<P>
   For the last year every day has been like New Year's Eve.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some people who work in Times Square are overwhelmed by the
daytime crowds. It can take 15 minutes just to cross the square,
they say. They must add another half-hour to lunch time. Stout
shoes are recommended for hazarding a short walk up Broadway. Don't
even think about dashing around the corner to buy a paper.
</P>
<P>
   I, too, am overwhelmed, but in a positive sense. It amazes me
that such a transformation could have happened so quickly. It could
never have happened purely by design. The convergence of the
mediacracy was a collective achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``interim plan,'' orchestrated by Rebecca
Robertson, former president of the 42nd Street Development Project,
after the collapse of the initial four-tower scheme, is no longer
interim. It has become, in effect, the plan. Instead of the uniform
design originally envisioned, we have the visual and functional
diversity that Ms. Robertson fought for. Reuters and Conde Nast are
being absorbed into the mix. Publicity House has found its public.
</P>
<P>
   Like others, I miss the 42nd Street of my youth, when you could
catch two double features for under $2 and enjoy erotic fantasies
about the ``City of Night.'' Yet even in those days Times Square
was a place for nostalgia. We would go there to wallow in what the
French call nostalgie de la boue: the yen for dissolute amusements
that we were free to enjoy because we were essentially tourists,
visitors from alien social and intellectual spheres.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I can't claim to be a tourist here. After all, I work for
the news organization that gave Times Square its name. I like being
part of this new megastructure and dread the thought that the
company might move.
</P>
<P>
   The paper is a living link in the evolution of media culture and
public life from the 19th century to the present. It stands for the
possibility that even amid the distraction industries there is room
for independent reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet I wouldn't object if the distractions got even more out of
control. There is an apocalyptic undercurrent sloshing around the
new Times Square. It rose to hysterical waves last week with the
approach of New Year's Eve, as fantasies of terrorist attacks and
news reports of security precautions surged into public view.
</P>
<P>
   But even on a so-called ordinary day the place seems to hover on
the verge of chaos. Nathaniel West's vision of a berserk Los
Angeles comes to mind. One pop-star fan will step on another fan's
toe, and within seconds Times Square will be convulsed with panic.
Police forces will march in to secure the peace.
</P>
<P>
   There is truth to these fantasies, also. They express an
instinctive fear of power and authority, as now represented by the
media and the economic forces behind them. The vision we had on New
Year's Eve _ of a police army called in to protect a carnival _ is
a memorable one, even for a society so driven to distraction that
it can scarcely find the time or place for remembering last week's
news, much less Oskar Nitzchke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
