<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPER-DEBT-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. PETERSBURG TIMES DEBT IS PAID BACK BY ITS PARENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   (nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that ensured the durability of one of the country's
most unusual newspaper ownership arrangements, the company that
publishes The St. Petersburg Times has paid off a $30-million debt
to the nonprofit institute that owns it.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Barnes, chief executive of Times Publishing, parent of
The St. Petersburg Times, said in a Dec. 26 letter in the newspaper
that the debt to the Poynter Institute for Media Studies had been
paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never burned a mortgage,'' Barnes wrote, ``but it must
feel the same. Ownership is secure.''
</P>
<P>
   The payment of the debt was the final act of a 1990 settlement
that ended the Texas financier Robert Bass' battle for control of
Times Publishing. The St. Petersburg Times, with a daily
circulation of 314,000, is one of the nation's most respected
regional newspapers, and numbered among the nation's 10 best
newspapers in a recent Columbia Journalism Review survey.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of independent newspapers dwindled in the last 30
years, the owners of The St. Petersburg Times, The Day in New
London, Conn., and The Delaware State News, in Dover, Del.,
developed unconventional arrangements to avoid the sale of their
publications _ a frequent consequence of inheritance taxes and
squabbles among heirs.
</P>
<P>
   A pioneer among this group was Nelson Poynter, who before his
death in 1978 established the nonprofit Poynter Institute and left
his controlling shares in Times Publishing to the institute. Those
shares are voted by the publishing company's chief executive,
Barnes, who has named Paul Tash, his second-in-command at The
Times, as his successor, though he has not announced retirement
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The institute and the publishing company have a symbiotic
partnership. The institute's financing is derived directly from the
profits of Times Publishing. The publishing company's independence
from the market-driven need for high margins is based on its
ownership by a nonprofit foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Smyth, chief executive of Independent Newspapers, an Arizona
company that owns 30 small newspapers _ the largest is the
23,000-circulation Delaware State News _ said last week that
Poynter's efforts had inspired him to create his own nonprofit
ownership arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The debt was the legacy of a two-year battle with Bass. After
acquiring a substantial portion of the common stock in Times
Publishing from the heirs of Poynter's sister, Ellen Jamison
Poynter, Bass mounted a challenge for control of the newspaper.
That challenge ended with the legal settlement in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-00 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
