<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-CHRISTIANS-0103-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    POPE URGES END TO EXPLOITATION AND NEGLECT OF CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By ADAM FREEMAN 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VATICAN CITY _ Tens of thousands of youngsters and their parents
filled St. Peter's Square beyond capacity Sunday to join Pope John
Paul II in urging an end to the exploitation and neglect of
children.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, arriving in the 16th Century Baroque square a little
before noon to lead the Celebration of Children, was greeted by
cheering and singing.
</P>
<P>
   The first major celebration thrown specifically for the Holy
Year was dedicated to the world's children, with a special emphasis
on the ``baby-soldiers'' who are forcibly conscripted to fight in
the many civil wars being waged around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Among the special guests at the celebration were a handful of
children from Sierra Leone. Event organizers said they had been
``re-civilianized'' after being forced to carry automatic weapons
and hand grenades during the civil war that has gripped the West
African nation for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the morning, Cardinal Roger Etchegaray, chairman of
the Central Committee for the Grand Jubilee of the Year 2000,
presided over a mass in St. Peter's Basilica. During the ceremony
he encouraged people to remember that children are innocent victims
of wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remember the famous photo taken in 1972 of a nude child
that was running terrified down a street of Vietnam trying to
escape from a bomb of napalm,'' said Etchegaray, who noted that in
the 21st Century there remain ``children that carry rifles,
children mutilated by mines, refugee children. . . starving, stray
children on the streets like dogs lost without a collar.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican hosted more than 50,000 participants, including
parents and their children who arrived from 30 countries, including
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Romans opened their homes to host many of the children who came
from developing nations. Some of them had the costs of their trip
paid by the Roma Soccer Club, one of the biggest in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   During his noon message, John Paul greeted his young guests in
Italian, English, French, Spanish and Polish, his mother tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of a new year, dear children and young
people, we cannot forget all those of your own age who are
suffering hunger or violence, and those who are victims of hideous
forms of exploitation,'' declared the 79-year-old pontiff.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's event was part of Jubilee 2000, which began on
Christmas Eve and will last for more than a year. It will close on
Jan. 6, 2000, the Day of the Epiphany. More than 30 million Roman
Catholic pilgrims are expected to make the trip to Rome for the
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
