<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-YEAREND-WINNERS-ART-N     01-02 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAREND-WINNERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1999: EXTRAORDINARY WINNERS BUT MORE LOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When they were hot, they were very, very hot. But
when they were not, they were losers.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the stock market in 1999 was of stocks that flew
higher than at any time in the last decade. Enough of them soared
that the major market indexes all closed the year at record highs.
The best-performing stocks leaped not hundreds, but thousands of
percentage points. By that standard, it was the year of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, all that prosperity hid some weaknesses. With interest
rates rising and oil prices soaring, many stocks struggled. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks gained 19.5 percent during
the year, but more stocks in the index fell than rose.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index leaped 85.6 percent _ a performance
that exceeded the gain for any major index in any year in the
history of stock markets in the United States. But there were a lot
of Nasdaq losers as well, and the index of financial stocks listed
on that market ended the year down 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate just how great a year it was for the winners,
compare Qualcomm, the best-performing stock of 1999 (among those
that began the year over $5 a share) with the top performers of
previous years. Qualcomm rose 2,619 percent in 1999. Twelve other
stocks on Nasdaq that started the year over $5 managed to climb at
least 1,000 percent. A further seven issues rose at least 900
percent.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in the first nine years of the decade, only one
such stock ever rose as much as 900 percent in a year. That was
Amazon.com, which soared 966 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most amazing stock of the year was Xcelera.com,
formerly known as Scandinavia. Once a closed-end fund specializing
in Scandinavian stocks, and then an operating company that owned a
hotel in the Canary Islands, it made a small investment in an
Internet company last year. Before it disclosed that investment,
the family of Alexander Vik, the company's chief executive, was
given options to buy a million shares of stock, at a price of $3.25
each. The shares ended 1998 at $3.75, or $1.25 adjusted for two
subsequent splits. They ended 1999 at $139.50, an increase of
11,060 percent. The Viks' option position is now valued at $415
million.
</P>
<P>
   There was also no shortage of hot initial public offerings in
1999. Where it once was deemed embarrassing for an offering to
double during the first day, since it indicated that the
underwriter had underestimated demand and failed to get the best
deal for the company going public, it now seems to be a badge of
honor.
</P>
<P>
   Just why that should be so is an interesting question. Perhaps
companies think that the amount of money being raised is relatively
small compared to the prestige of having a stock deemed to be hot,
and figure that in any case, they can always raise more capital
later. Perhaps they are happy to be able to provide a quick profit
for friends and family members allowed to buy shares at the
offering price.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps the market is just too hot for the underwriters to
deal with. Last month, Goldman, Sachs tripled the planned offering
price for FreeMarkets, one of a number of companies trying to find
a niche helping businesses get better deals, at lower transaction
costs, by using the Internet. Priced at $48 a share, up from a
planned range of $14 to $16, the shares leaped to $290 the first
day and ended the year at $341.31.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors was involved in two initial public offerings
during the year. One was for a company with a long business history
that included substantial profits. Buyers in that deal suffered.
The other company had almost no history. It became one of the most
successful offerings of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The poor performer was Delphi Automotive Systems, GM's parts
operations. It went public in February at $17 a share and ended the
year down 7 percent, at $15.75.
</P>
<P>
   The other offering was Commerce One, another company hoping to
prosper in the business-to-business internet arena, and which GM
has agreed to use to buy products from suppliers. Commerce One went
public in July at $7 a share (adjusted for a subsequent split),
closed the first day at $20.33, and ended the year at $196.50, for
a gain from the offering price of 2,707 percent.
</P>
<P>
   GM hopes to save money by buying through Commerce One, but it
will be a long time, if ever, before its savings from those
purchases equal its paper profit on its investment in Commerce One.
It has an option to buy 14.4 million shares of Commerce One _ now
valued at $2.8 billion _ for a total price of $480.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce One's offering was the second-most successful of 1999,
in terms of performance from the offering price, according to
calculations by Thomson Financial/Securities Data. The winner was
Internet Capital Group, a company that invests in other Internet
companies. It more than doubled its first day of trading, Aug. 5,
and that was just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the year ended, the stock was at $170 a share, even
after splitting two for one. That compared with an offering price,
adjusted for the split, of $6, and a first-day close of $12.22. The
company, which since its inception in 1996 has reported losses of
$112 million on revenue of $15 million, now has a market value of
$44 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Some initial offerings that looked great the first day, however,
soon looked quite ill. Value America, an Internet retailer, went
public in April at $23 a share and traded as high as $74.25 the
first day. It ended the year at $5.06 after announcing plans to lay
off many of its employees. Another retailer, eToys, ended the year
at $26.25, above its offering price of $20, but far below the high
of $86 reached in October.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the moves made by the winners reflects the
speculative fever gripping the market and is based on hopes that as
the Internet transforms the economy, companies that did not exist a
few years ago will become giants.
</P>
<P>
   In all that, the example of Yahoo, one of the first of the
Internet companies to go public, stands out as the shining example.
It more than doubled the day it went public _ April 15, 1996 _ and
within a few months had fallen back to the offering price. But an
investor who put $1,000 into the stock at the close of trading that
first day, and held on, would now have stock worth $80,500. That is
more than 10 times as much as someone who bought Microsoft the day
it went public in 1986 would have had after the same amount of
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
