<HEADER>
A4660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-YEAREND-HIGHLIGHTS-NY     01-02 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAREND-HIGHLIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AT THE FINANCIAL WINNERS IN '99 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Neb., Calif.)  (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You Like It
</P>
<P>
   Bill Miller did the near impossible _ again. The fund he
manages, Legg Mason Value Trust, beat the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index in 1999. It has been that kind of decade for
Miller, 49, a former military intelligence officer and philosophy
student given to quoting Shakespeare and William James. Even as
investors piled into index funds, his fund beat the S&AMP;P 500 in each
of the last nine years, the only fund to do so, according to Lipper
Inc. (Peter Lynch's consecutive win streak lasted seven years.)
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Value Trust returned 26.3 percent, compared with the
S&AMP;P's 20.6 percent gain. Miller bet big a few years ago on
technology stocks, including America Online, but in December said
he now favors financial stocks, bonds, turnaround companies and
small stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Ring of Real Money
</P>
<P>
   What product blew off the shelves in '99? Cellular phones. What
stock blew off the charts? Qualcomm, which owns valuable patents on
a fast-growing cell phone technology and decided to jettison its
phone-making operation during the year. The stock had surged
twentyfold in late December when a PaineWebber analyst said it
could double in the next 12 months, causing yet another buying
frenzy. On the last day of the year, the stock split four for one,
ending the year with a 2,619 percent gain. During the year,
Qualcomm's market value soared from less than $4 billion to $116
billion, after issuing more shares.
</P>
<P>
   A few million here, a few million there, and it adds up to real
money for Irwin Mark Jacobs, 65, an engineer who founded and runs
Qualcomm in San Diego. A year ago, Jacobs was awarded a bundle of
options, now valued at $648.7 million. As of the most recent
regulatory filing, he and his family own or have options on at
least 44 million shares, worth close to $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting It Big
</P>
<P>
   Got an idea to sell something over the Internet: furniture,
groceries, greeting cards, junk? In a year of Internet frenzy,
paper millionaires were minted almost daily as companies with nary
a profit and often no sales issued stock to the public and watched
it soar. But the most likely route to riches seemed to be creating
a company that would provide services to other companies exploiting
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai Technologies hit it right with a process to speed up
delivery of content over the Internet. It was begun by an MIT
professor, Thomson Leighton, and a student, Daniel Lewin, each of
whom held 9.6 million shares, according to a regulatory filing. If
they have held on, those stakes are now worth $3.145 billion
 &UR; apiece. &LR;  The stock rose 458 percent on its first day of trading in
late October, and by the end of the year, it was up 1,160 percent.
On average, IPO's gained 67 percent in their first day of trading
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still Thirsty
</P>
<P>
   Not every portfolio overflowed with profits last year. Warren E.
Buffet, the investing sage from Omaha, Neb., saw the share price of
his Berkshire Hathaway holding company decline 20 percent, for its
first negative year since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Dragging it down was a big stake in Coca-Cola, the longtime
beverage of champions that failed to clear government hurdles to
acquisitions abroad and experienced slowing sales. In Europe, Coke
drinkers were sickened in a contamination scare. Coke shareholders
swooned, too, as the stock lost more than 11 percent of its value.
The pressure proved too much for M. Douglas Ivester, who abruptly
announced his early retirement after just two years as Coke's
chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were left to wonder whether Coke and some other blue
chips known for years of rapid global growth had seen their best
days. Other notable decliners were Gillette, Xerox and Pfizer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
