<HEADLINE>
WHO LOST RUSSIA? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By JOHN LLOYD  
 Fe New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    For most of this decade, Russia has been consumed by the quest
to become a free, democratic, capitalist state.
 &HT;    Billions of dollars of foreign aid have poured into its reforms.
 &HT;    Bitter struggles have been waged between Russia's free-market
radicals and their Communist or nationalist foes, most
significantly in 1993, when armed struggle broke out between the
