</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GOING-BINGE-840(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RECORD YEAR FOR HIT MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Beginning with ``The Matrix'' on Easter weekend and
accelerating into hyperdrive with the success of ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' American moviegoers went on a
nine-month binge that drew record crowds to theaters, created a
record number of $100 million hits and shattered several
long-cherished assumptions about how the film business works.
</P>
<P>
   Although final figures for the year will not be available until
later this week, it is abundantly clear that 1999 was the second
consecutive record year at the nation's box offices.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibitor Relations, the Los Angeles-based company that monitors
box-office performance, estimates that Americans spent $7.5 billion
on movie tickets last year, an increase of 8 percent over $6.95
billion in 1998. Some of that increase reflects higher ticket
prices, but even in terms of ticket sales _ the number of people
attending movies _ it will be a record year.
</P>
<P>
   There was much talk in Hollywood in 1999 that the basic rules
upon which the studios have operated for years were subtly
changing, that such safe bets as big stars in long-popular genres
were not as reliable as before, that young adults in particular
preferred a more frenetic, MTV-like style of moviemaking, and that
there was, perhaps, a growing disconnect between what people wanted
to see and what studios were producing.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers tell a different story. The movies that did best
at the box office were generally sequels,  and other
mainstream films with big stars in recognizable genres.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were some enormous surprise hits _ ``The Sixth
Sense'' in second place for the year, ``The Matrix'' in fifth,
``The Blair Witch Project'' in 10th and ``Double Jeopardy'' in 12th
_ the year's Top 20 offerings included a new ``Star Wars'' movie
(No. 1 for the year), a James Bond movie (14th place), two sequels
(``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' in 3rd place and ``Toy
Story 2'' in 4th), five remakes of movies or television series
(``Tarzan'' in 6th place, ``The Mummy'' in 8th, ``Wild Wild West''
in 13th, ``Inspector Gadget'' in 18th and ``The Haunting'' in 19th)
and movies featuring box-office-friendly stars like Adam Sandler
(``Big Daddy,'' No. 7) and Julia Roberts (``Runaway Bride,'' No. 9,
and ``Notting Hill,'' No. 11).
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the talk about how 1999 broke all the rules in
terms of what films had mass appeal, I think when you look at this
list it's still pretty traditional in terms of genres and
ratings,'' said Paul Dergarabedian, chairman of Exhibitor
Relations. ``Most are still star-driven. And the traditional
narrative still rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The wealth of surprise hits (before its release, no one
predicted that ``The Sixth Sense'' would make more than $275
million, and counting) was often taken as proof that the studios
had lost contact with movie audiences. But studio executives said
unpredictability was just the nature of such a risky business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it's impossible to predict $200 million movies
like `Sixth Sense,''' said Robert G. Friedman, vice chairman of the
Paramount Motion Picture Group. ``But I wouldn't say you're
blindsided. I'd say you're pleasantly surprised. We knew `Double
Jeopardy' was going to be a successful movie, and I would have bet
it was going to make plus or minus $100 million. Would I have been
more comfortable betting less than more? Sure. We were pleasantly
surprised. I'll take pleasantly surprised all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   What struck many film executives about the year-end list was its
eclectic nature, spanning genres from romantic comedy to
action-thriller to horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the good news today is that there seems to be room for
everybody,'' said Jeff Blake, president of distribution for
Columbia Pictures. ``The audience has expanded, so you will be able
to do specialized films for a specific audience. Yet when you do
have a wide-appeal hit, the reward is even greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Amir Malin, president of Artisan Entertainment, the company that
released the year's most unexpected phenomenon, ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' found something troubling about it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of is reminiscent of the beginning of `A Tale of Two
Cities': it was the best of times and the worst of times,'' Malin
said. ``The reality is that most of the box office was generated by
a handful of films. The Top 20 films account for a good amount of
the year's box office, especially the last three or four months.
Drama films, art films and more specialized films have had a very
problematic time.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to ``Ride With the Devil,'' ``Music of the Heart,''
``Tumbleweeds'' and even ``Boys Don't Cry,'' which drew much
acclaim, but not great ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not necessarily quality oriented,'' Malin said. ``With so
many things coming at us from so many different perspectives,
audiences were much more selective about what they wanted to see.
And they were going to see more marketable films.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What struck Dergarabedian about the year was the relentlessness
with which people went to the movies and the scope of their
appetite. Over the summer there were nine consecutive weekends when
a different movie was No. 1 at the box office, and the year ended
with 17 films earning more than $100 million, another record. Some
of the films currently in theaters, like ``Sleepy Hollow'' and
``Stuart Little,'' are expected to earn more than $100 million, so
the record number is likely to reach perhaps 20 films, he said.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Phantom Menace' really got people into theaters and it got
people encouraged about more moviegoing,'' he said. ``People saw
the trailers, they saw the posters, and it was a snowball effect
that carried through the summer and right through the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the year ended on a bit of a whimper, largely
because the Christmas and New Year's holidays each fell on a
weekend, which depresses ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, some films showed unexpected strength in the final
weekend of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Initial estimates had ``Stuart Little'' in first place for the
New Year's weekend with $16 million and a cumulative total of $79.7
million since its opening on Dec. 17. Sales on New Year's weekend
represented an increase of 35 percent from the Christmas weekend.
Since Christmas Eve, ``Stuart Little'' earned $52 million, making
it the most profitable family-oriented film ever for this 10-day
period, Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Stuart Little,'' which apparently benefited from strong
word-of-mouth, ``Galaxy Quest'' did as well, earning an estimated
$9.7 million for the New Year's weekend, which, even though it only
landed in sixth place for the weekend, was a 38 percent increase
over its Christmas weekend opening.
</P>
<P>
   The word of mouth was not so good for ``Man on the Moon,'' the
Milos Forman film in which Jim Carrey plays the comedian Andy
Kaufman. It was in ninth place on its second weekend, below ``Deuce
Bigalow: Male Gigolo,'' earning just $5.2 million, a decrease of 31
percent from Christmas weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Brothers was estimating strong numbers for its two films,
$13.2 million for the weekend for ``The Green Mile,'' an
astonishing increase of 42 percent, and $13 million for ``Any Given
Sunday,'' a second weekend decrease of only 4 percent. Other
studios, however, were questioning Warner's estimates and saying
that their numbers had ``Toy Story 2'' (with an estimated $12.1
million) and ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' ($12 million) ahead of
both of the Warner films. Final and more accurate numbers (not
based on studio estimates) will be available later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Among the films sent out in limited release _ that is, to only a
handful of theaters so that they qualify for the Academy Awards
before going into wider release later this month _ Norman Jewison's
``Hurricane'' had an extremely strong opening this weekend. It
earned $295,000 in 11 theaters for a per-theater average of nearly
$27,000, more than double what other December limited releases had
earned. The film, starring Denzel Washington as the boxer Hurricane
Carter, will open in more theaters on Friday before going into
nationwide release on Jan. 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
