<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: PUTTING BAR CODES ON PILLS; PATENTS PASS A MILESTONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several years ago, Scott Sullivan had a hallway conversation at
work with Robert Hess about an idea: putting Braille on pills.
</P>
<P>
   But Sullivan, a patent agent, and Hess, a patent lawyer,
realized their concept had a flaw. What if one of the raised dots
chipped off? A blind person might misread the pill and take the
wrong medication. But as they tossed the notion around and realized
that Braille was just a code, it came to them: Why not use a bar
code instead?
</P>
<P>
   The two refined their idea and first applied for a patent in
1994. Given the vagaries of the patenting process, they could not
have hoped to time their patent to issue within days of a study
released by the Institute of Medicine that cited medical errors as
a major killer in U.S. hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   But that is what happened. At the end of November the report
made headlines with the declaratt each year tens of
thousands of people die as a result of such mistakes, many of which
are blunders with drugs. It said that every year more than 7,000
patients died because they got the wrong medicine, or took medicine
in the wrong doses or at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, Sullivan and Hess received their patent for a
method of placing a machine-readable bar-code on pills so that the
medication could be identified and tracked.
</P>
<P>
   Many health-care professionals say medication errors stem not
from incompetence but from confusion. Drugs often have look-alike
labels or sound-alike names, and come in similar shapes and colors.
The inventors say the addition of a bar code to every pill would
allow nurses, doctors, paramedics, other health-care professionals
and even people at home to always know the type and dosage of
medicine being used.
</P>
<P>
   The patent covers addition of a bar code in different ways,
depending on whether a pill is a coated tablet, or a porous, chalky
pill, or a gel capsule.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can use an ink,'' Sullivan said. ``The pill shoots between
two rollers and the bar code is printed. Colors can be chosen so
you can print a bar code the same way you print `Advil' on a
tablet. The resolution is much better for printing `Advil' than for
`M&AMP;Ms.'''
</P>
<P>
   Such printing will not work on porous pills like aspirin. ``You
can't coat the pill, because you want it to dissolve immediately,''
Sullivan said. ``If you coat aspirin, it ends up in the intestine
and not the stomach and changes the way it works. But you can print
the bar code on a gel strip that is like Scotch tape, apply a
little moisture and stick it on.''
</P>
<P>
   The bar code could consist of up to 15 digits, Sullivan said,
and might be based on the National Drug Code that the federal
government uses to assign numbers to pharmaceuticals. Once pills
are bar-coded, a patient or a health-care worker would simply scan
the medicine with a hand-held device. The scanner would read the
bar code and identify the drug. It would also be linked to a
central database.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bar code addresses a file,'' Sullivan continued. ``It
wouldn't be just 15 characters of information. You'd open up the
file, and it would say `Welcome to Prozac,' and here's 20 to 30
pages of information.''
</P>
<P>
   That data would include all the information that is normally
printed on inserts handed out with drug prescriptions, like the
hazards of taking a drug in combination with other pills, or the
risks for people with certain medical conditions. ``The user could
also upload information about a patient, like what drugs they use,
or allergies, and that could trigger an alarm,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   The inventors maintain that bar codes on pills could eliminate
many medical hazards that arise from drug mistakes. They say
medication mix-ups, tampering or switching of brand-name drugs for
generic ones would be greatly reduced. They also contend that their
patent would enable hospitals and clinics to buy drugs in bulk
form, without the costly and wasteful packaging now used to reduce
mistakes in identifying pills.
</P>
<P>
   They envision a ``robotic pharmacist'' using their pills to
alleviate the workload in pharmacies. And they say paramedics who
treat unconscious patients would be able to scan drugs found at the
scene to determine what they are.
</P>
<P>
   But Sullivan acknowledges that the bar-code system must be
standardized so that all drug manufacturers use the same system, in
order for all pills to be readable by any scanner and linked to a
common database.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the government to standardize something, because
someone has to decide what the numbers mean,'' Sullivan said. He
and Hess have written to several members of Congress to suggest
their idea and ask for help. They received patent 5,992,742.
</P>
<P>
   Patents Pass a Milestone
</P>
<P>
   Just before the 20th century came to an end, the Patent and
Trademark Office passed a milestone of its own. On Dec. 7, the
agency issued patent No. 6,000,000. It was awarded to Jeffrey
Hawkins, of Redwood City, Calif., and Michael Albanese of Los
Gatos, Calif., for an ``extendible method and apparatus for
synchronizing multiple files on two different computer systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Patent No. 1 was issued in 1836. It took 75 years for the first
million patents to follow, a milestone reached in 1911. The
2-million mark was passed in 1936, and 3 million in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Either patenting has become more popular, or the Patent and
Trademark Office has grown more efficient: Patent 4,000,000 was
issued in 1976, and it took just 15 years for the next million
patents to win approval. Only eight years have passed between the
5-millionth and the 6-millionth.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, DC 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
