<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FCC to Pick Chief Technologist
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission plans to announce Monday
that it has appointed David J. Farber, a pioneering computer
scientist and telecommunications expert, as the agency's chief
technologist. Farber, a University of Pennsylvania professor, drew
attention last year when he served as a Justice Department expert
witness in the bitter Microsoft antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Peril of Direct Internet Sales
</P>
<P>
   Just as Amazon.com has led millions of would-be entrepreneurs
toward the e-commerce promised land, so too has the success of Dell
Computer led countless manufacturers to believe that their future
success rides on the ability to sell directly to consumers over the
Internet. But manufacturers who have ventured onto the Web have
found that unless they can convince their retail partners and
distributors they are not out to steal sales from them, bad things
can happen to the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   St. Petersburg Times Pays Off Debt
</P>
<P>
   The company that publishes The St. Petersburg Times has paid off
a $30 million debt to the Poynter Institute for Media Studies, the
nonprofit group that owns it, ensuring the durability of one of the
country's most unusual newspaper ownership arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Israel Bank Chief to Stay a Week
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Frenkel, the chief of Israel's central bank, who was to
have stepped down, agreed to stay another week while Prime Minister
Ehud Barak continues to look for a successor.
</P>
<P>
   Web Stocks as Popularity Contest
</P>
<P>
   Stock market experts are beginning to acknowledge what many have
suspected for a long time: technology stocks are being kept aloft
on their own hot air. The mystery surrounding the stock valuations
may have been solved last week by the chief investment strategist
at Credit Suisse First Boston, who declared that the more popular
the Web site, the higher its ``ranking'' and the more the company
is worth.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Markets Resume Regular Hours
</P>
<P>
   U.S. stock and bond markets, which closed early on Friday for
the New Year's holiday, will return to regular hours Monday. Many
markets in Asia and some markets in Europe are closed Monday
</P>
</TEXT>
