<HEADER>
A4679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-RDP-NYT     01-02 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PRESIDENTIAL RACE IS PUTIN'S TO LOSE, AIDE SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (With RUSSIA-CHECHNYA) 
 (nk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A top aide to Russia's acting president, Vladimir
Putin, said Sunday that it is all but impossible for Putin to lose
the presidential election tentatively set for March. For now, at
least, no one seemed to disagree.
</P>
<P>
   After cramming his first two days as acting president with
campaign-style speeches, news conferences, a trip to a war zone and
a chat with President Clinton, Putin kept away from cameras Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But his staff kept the publicity going, suggesting in a news
briefing that Putin is so confident of victory in March that he
will do little traditional campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Putin will run any special election campaign as
he will have to combine the duties of president and prime
minister,'' said Igor Shabdurasulov, the first deputy chief of the
presidential staff.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said he was reluctant to make political forecasts,
Shabdurasulov said it was unrealistic to believe that anyone could
beat Putin.
</P>
<P>
   It will be better if Putin wins an outright majority in the
first round of voting, he said, because a runoff election would
only ``waste time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin had been working hard to establish just such an air
of invincibility about Putin even before President Boris Yeltsin
dumbfounded the nation on Friday by resigning and handing Putin the
job of running the country. But for once the optimism seems
justified, even though political half-lives here are as often
measured in months as in years.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's only serious rival so far, the former foreign minister
and Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, suffered a huge blow when his
political party, Fatherland-All Russia, stumbled in last month's
parliamentary elections. Another contender, Grigory Yavlinsky, the
leader of the liberal Yabloko Party, also faded after the party's
candidates did not do as well in that election as it had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves only the Communist Party, which can count on a solid
25 percent to 30 percent of the vote in any election, but not much
more.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington Sunday, Clinton's national security adviser, Sandy
Berger, warned that the mounting casualties among Russian soldiers
in the fierce battle for Chechnya's capital, Grozny, could pose
political problems for Putin if the conflict is not settled soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can't bring this to an end _ a peaceful end _ quickly,
if the costs become too high for the Russians, and the resistance
is increasing, this could become an albatross around his neck in
March,'' Berger said on the ABC interview program ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   If Putin or his aides share that view, however, they are
concealing it nicely. Despite complaints from the West about the
brutality of the war, it has remained the engine of Putin's
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Returning Saturday afternoon from a highly publicized trip to
the Chechnya front, Putin said he believes that ``everything we
have done so far has been justified.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in remarks carried on the Moscow news station Echo
Moskvy, Putin added that the Kremlin has ``no intention to liberate
anything by acting hastily.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to act in the best possible way, which means as few
losses as possible among our servicemen and no losses among the
civilian population,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of what already is starting to look like an event-a-day
campaign schedule, Putin was scheduled to meet Sunday with newly
elected members of the lower house of parliament. But all Russia
traditionally rests and celebrates in the days after the New Year,
and not enough legislators could be rounded up for a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Shabdurasulov, the presidential aide, sketched out in
barest detail Putin's plans for his transition into the presidency
and for the campaign _ plans more notable for what was not
mentioned than for what was.
</P>
<P>
   He said, for example, that Putin probably will make few changes
in the government he inherited from Yeltsin, although one
presidential adviser, Tatiana Dyachenko, ``probably would change
her status.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dyachenko, Yeltsin's 39-year-old daughter, is a crucial
Kremlin political strategist who is rumored to have been behind
Putin's swift rise to power. Shabdurasulov's ambiguous language
left it unclear whether she will remain in the Kremlin or leav her father.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Shabdurasulov said no one had decided whether to
accept the offers of two of Yeltsin's allies, Anatoly Chubais and
Boris Berezovsky, to work in Putin's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Chubais, an architect of the economic reforms that ended with
last year's disastrous financial collapse, now runs the nation's
electricity monopoly. Berezovsky, a tycoon who was a major
financier of Yeltsin's 1996 re-election campaign, is said to be a
close friend of Ms. Dyachenko.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's political class will be closely watching the fates of
the three to see whether Putin is setting an independent course or
is _ as critics charge _ a tool for extending the Yeltsin clan's
reign beyond that of its patriarch.
</P>
<P>
   The only sour note Sunday came from the media empire of another
tycoon, Boris Gusinsky, a bitter foe of Berezovsky and now, it
seems, of Putin.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly news magazine program ``Itogi,'' broadcast Sunday
night on Gusinsky's NTV network, charged that Kremlin strategists
and KGB veterans like Putin had plotted Yeltsin's resignation for
months _ perhaps without Yeltsin's consent _ in an effort to
prolong their own power.
</P>
<P>
   The program also suggested that they had probably succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broad opportunities now open up for Putin,'' it said. ``The
chances of his competitors for the post of president are now at an
incredibly low level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin has now received a full arsenal of power, almost
unlimited power, and with all of his qualities there is no need to
doubt that the president will use all of the levers to hold onto
this power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
