<SLUG> BC-BOOMER-AD-COLUMN-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: NEW CAMPAIGNS GEARED TO PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (lb) 
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The commercial opens on a car blasting the 1970s rock 'n' roll
hit ``Rebel, Rebel.'' The car spins out of a parking garage past a
startled guard and into the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the pressure to conform,'' a voice-over says, ``and
then there's the Mazda 626.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the car stops short on a suburban street and out steps a
trim woman in her 30s in a skirt and heels, with covered cake in
hand. Continues the voice-over, ``Do not go gently into that PTA
meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   The point: Sally Suburban requires a four-door sedan for her 1.7
children, but Mazda understands that inside she is still a rebel.
</P>
<P>
   For generations, advertising has sold products by reinforcing
the idea of the traditional family with the ever-attentive parents.
Mothers especially fell victim to this stereotype, having been
depicted through time as selfless martyrs only too happy to cater
to the children.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly the message in advertising to today's parents _
especially to mothers _ says that it's OK to be attractive, hip,
maybe even a bit exciting, and still be a parent.
</P>
<P>
   It is a far cry from the Ward and June Cleaver school of
casting, and that is exactly the idea behind it. The suggestion
reinforces a feeling among at least some baby boomers that they
have not become their parents _ that indeed they are still cool.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising for things like automobiles, greeting cards, even
Campbell's Soup and Parents magazine, depict parents as individuals
who sometimes do think of themselves, not just of their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making an emotional connection,'' said Tim Blett,
president of the Doner Automotive unit of Doner, the ad agency
based in Southfield, Mich., that creates Mazda's advertising.
``Buying a sedan can be a disappointing experience _ it suggests
you now have kids and responsibilities and you have to give up many
of the things that were important to you. Our message is that you
don't have to give up youthful spirit as you grow older. You don't
have to give in and give up and conform to parenthood and make a
complete sacrifice about life.''
</P>
<P>
   Doner's research for Mazda found this particular psychology
especially prevalent among a segment of the 34-to-42-year-old
population, which is Mazda's primary customer, said Blett. Doner
defines this group as ``the trailing edge'' of the baby boomers,
who grew up in the shadow of their more famous siblings of the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two strong mind-sets in this age group, Doner called one
the ``do the right thing'' traditionalists who accept sacrifice as
a given in marriage and parenting, he said. The other, dubbed the
``life keeps getting better'' group, married later and established
certain lifestyles that they want to maintain despite life's
various stages of aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who developed a way of looking at the world
that was different than any other generation before it,'' Blett
said. ``So when it came time to have kids, they want the marriage
and family, but they were also used to certain experiences,
conveniences and adventures and they don't want to give it all
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertisers tapping into this feeling came to it for
different reasons. Campbell Soup Co. _ known for homey spots that
often feature soup, Mom and a snowy day _ wanted to advertise a new
product for women. Its spot is part of a much broader campaign to
depict Campbell's in a contemporary way that fits with how people
``live and eat today,'' said Lisa Zakrajsek, vice president of
Campbell's U.S. Soup.
</P>
<P>
   Set to the song ``Just the Two of Us,'' the spot from BBDO New
York, a unit of Omnicom Group, shows a woman amusingly relishing an
evening alone without her husband and children.
</P>
<P>
   Not that selling the idea of pampering oneself is new. Consider
the ``Take Me Away'' Calgon ads of the 1970s that depicted women
transported from the stresses of life. But Ms. Zakrajsek said this
ad has a different psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a subtle but important change,'' said Ms. Zakrajsek.
``She's not complaining about her life. Our research shows the
contemporary woman is not stressed out and haggard and guilty about
working  pretty happy with life on the whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents magazine is selling the idea that parents are still hip,
as a way to expand its market of advertisers beyond the traditional
categories of baby bottles, diapers and toys.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``Look at the Facts,'' its trade advertising campaign
from Anton &AMP; Partners uses headlines like ``Believe it or not,
since becoming parents, 96 percent of our readers report no
significant loss of style.'' Another states, ``Incredibly, 97
percent of our readers didn't feel any less hip after installing a
baby seat.'' Like many of the ads trying to appeal to parents'
nonfamilial side, the ads do not use children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this misperception that once a couple becomes a
parent, no matter how hip or intelligent or affluent, they fall out
of the mainstream for these products,'' said the magazine's
publisher, Sharon Summer. ``That's just not true.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While the magazine is attracting nontraditional advertisers that
sell things like beauty, shelter and fashion products, Ms. Summer
said it is still battling to convince young media buyers that
parents have not lost their edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stereotypes die hard,'' Ms. Summer said.
</P>
<P>
   For Volvo North America Corp., talking to parents in a newer and
broader voice solves a marketing problem, said Bob Austin, the
director of marketing communications.
</P>
<P>
   He said company research showed that the Volvo brand stands for
safety and for family. The problem is that most consumers associate
family with the traditional family, which is not representative of
the American landscape, he said. To show that Volvo is an
all-inclusive brand, the company last year ran a poignant but
sophisticated spot showing a divorced family.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional family consisting of a married couple with
children under 12 represents just 25 percent of all family units in
the United States today, Austin said. ``Because we'd like to grow
the company, we want to make more people feel it would be OK for
them to have a Volvo.''
</P>
<P>
   Later this month Mazda will begin a new spot for its 626. This
one has a retro feel and shows a couple on an almost surreal road
trip along the famed Route 66, renamed Route 626 for the
commercial, and set to Chuck Berry's rendition of ``Route 66.''
</P>
<P>
   Another new spot for the Mazda MPV minivan is set to the
recording of ``Everybody Is Free to Wear Sunscreen,'' performed by
the Australian disc jockey Baz Luhrmann and based on a column
written by The Chicago Tribune columnist Mary Schmich.
</P>
<P>
   The column _ which offered playful truisms to graduates _ took
on a cultlike status among young people a few years ago when it was
mistakenly circulated on the Internet as a Kurt Vonnegut
commencement address.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the advertising that makes parents feel hip does beg
the question of whether it really is cool.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, according to Blett: `It's hip as we defined it when
we were young.`
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's all a state of mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
