<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST MAGAZINES PUTS ITS FAITH IN OPRAH   
 CHANGING TIMES AT SOYBEAN DIGEST  
 WANTED AT NEW CABLE CHANNEL: MORE TIME  
 MEGABUCKS MOVIE  
 YET MORE MEDIA  
 NEW ADVERTISING BEHEMOTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If all the hype surrounding Oprah Winfrey is to be believed,
everything she touches turns to gold: She not only transforms
humble Midwestern housewives into best-selling blockbuster
novelists but when she appears on the cover of a magazine _ as she
did on Vogue in 1998 _ the magazine is sure to be a brisk seller.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Magazines has taken that logic to the next step, and will
introduce a lifestyle magazine licensed by Ms. Winfrey this spring.
The magazine's editor in chief, Ellen Kunes, describes the
still-unnamed project as ``a personal-growth guide for the next
century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about personal growth and positive energy,'' Ms. Kunes
said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond all the growth and good feeling, the magazine will also
cover beauty, fashion, food and design. ``We'll have articles about
real people, books and human drama,'' she said. ``It is going to
help women concentrate on themselves and celebrate or perhaps even
change their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Garfinkle, the director of print media at the
advertising agency McCann-Erickson, said the magazine, from an
advertisers' perspective, is sure to be a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory is that you could put out a magazine, call it Oprah,
put her picture on the cover, and have blank pages inside and it
would still sell,'' Ms. Garfinkle said.
</P>
<P>
   But the lifestyle market for magazines is increasingly crowded.
In 1999, American Express Publishing put out the first issue of B.
Smith Style, a lifestyle magazine based on the black restaurateur
that should also hold some appeal for black women (and a project
that Hearst turned down three times).
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Hearst will test the waters by publishing just four
or six issues of the Oprah magazine this year. And in the meantime,
Ms. Winfrey has stipulated in her contract with Hearst that she can
still appear on the covers of competing magazines.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Primedia Ready to Polish `A Diamond in the Rough'
</P>
<P>
   How do you take a company known in part for its sleepy trade
magazines like Soybean Digest and Lapidary Journal and transform it
into a smoking hot new-media company?
</P>
<P>
   Before Tom Rogers became the chief executive of Primedia last
fall, the company was primarily known as a large publisher of
special-interest and trade magazines. Apart from the most
recognizable titles _ New York, Seventeen and Modern Bride _ the
company publishes more than 100 niche magazines from American Baby
to World War II, and also produces and distributes video products
like Channel One and the Law Enforcement Television Network.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers _ the former president of NBC Cable, who expanded the NBC
network into cable and the Internet _ said he intends to nose
Primedia in the direction of new media, partly by generating
e-commerce off the magazine's Web sites and putting the company's
video properties to use on the Internet. He has already implemented
a plan to exchange advertising in the magazines for equity in
new-media ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest challenge is that we need to create an awareness
of what a diamond in the rough this company really is,'' Rogers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wolzien, a media analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co., said
Primedia was well set with Rogers, as long as the economy remained
strong. ``Tom has believed in the potential of niche media for more
than a decade, and Primedia gives him a vehicle to prove that it
works in video and Web content as well as in print,'' Wolzien said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem: Rogers has not been able to accomplish much since
being named to the post in September, in part because of the
company's large staff of 7,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``More employees create more levels of management,'' Rogers
said. ``And the speed at which we can move is certainly an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   New Channel for Women Is Moving Ahead
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine Laybourne acknowledges that she could use more time to
develop the new cable channel for women that her company, Oxygen
Media Inc., will start in February.
</P>
<P>
   But she says ``there are a lot of things that have mitigated the
feeling of risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them: substantial financial support. With backers
like Paul Allen and America Online, and partners like Oprah Winfrey
and the television production company Carsey-Werner-Mandabach, Ms.
Laybourne has been able to raise several hundred million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Her confidence comes from her conviction that the female
audience is so big and underserved that the opportunities far
outweigh any concern about fulfilling what she admits are ``very
high expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Those expectations arise mainly from Ms. Laybourne's resume: She
became the most accomplished women executive in television history
as chairwoman of Nickelodeon.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Laybourne says Oxygen Media ascribes to be nothing less than
``the HBO of convergence.'' Much of the programming has a direct
Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as she notes, there has not been a successful new analog
cable channel for several years, and Oxygen is headed into areas of
the Internet where there are already established Web businesses.
</P>
<P>
   There also remains the problem of getting the new channel onto
cable systems. It will be seen in about 10 million homes beginning
on Feb. 2, a promising but by no means booming start.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, ``I've never been more sure that this is the
right market and the right time and the right technology.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Film's Startling Budget Is Defended by Disney
</P>
<P>
   The initial working title was ``Tennessee,'' for the state from
which the story's three main characters emerge, but now it is being
referred to as ``Pearl Harbor,'' for the battle that forms the
film's centerpiece. But it was not the titles that raised eyebrows
when Walt Disney Studios recently announced its latest project with
the producer Jerry Bruckheimer. It was the film's startling budget.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of increased cost-cutting, when the common wisdom is
that big-budget movies are having a harder time clicking, Disney's
chairman, Joe Roth, approved Bruckheimer's budget of $145 million.
</P>
<P>
   To put that in perspective, the average studio film is made for
$50 million to $60 million, and even films that end up costing $200
million (like ``Titanic'' ) received the green light at less than
half that figure. To give the go-ahead on a movie with a budget
that high is unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   But Disney executives and Bruckheimer defend the figure as
necessary to tell an epic story that goes from Tennessee to Britain
and from Pearl Harbor to the famous 30-second air raid over Tokyo.
It is not the size of the budget, they say, but whether it is
appropriate to the story and to the movie's potential box-office
power. Bruckheimer points out that the huge budget contains nothing
for actors. The producer and the director, Michael Bay of
``Armageddon,'' plan to use younger (and less expensive) actors in
the leading roles. All the money will go into painstaking
re-creations of the battles.
</P>
<P>
   Second-unit photography has begun as has the casting search,
with principal photography to begin this spring and continue for
months. To show how confident they are, Bruckheimer and Disney have
already announced the release date: the Memorial Day weekend of
2001.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICK LYMAN
</P>
<P>
   Sea of Media Scrutiny Grows Even More Crowded
</P>
<P>
   It is said the unexamined life is not worth living. But what
about the examined life?
</P>
<P>
   Once, you could have argued that there was a dearth of media
coverage of the media. But that was before Brill's Content, before
Matt Drudge, before the online ``magazines'' Slate and Salon began
hammering away at the media on a daily and even hourly basis,
before trade publications like The Hollywood Reporter started
online editions and before the appearance of Mediagossip.com, a
daily compilation of media stories from around the country. Even
Editor &AMP; Publisher, the once-sleepy chronicle of the newspaper
industry, is breathing with new life.
</P>
<P>
   Some say this is necessary accompaniment to the Information Age.
Others say it reflects the narcissism of the age; the storyteller
and the story behind the story are deemed as interesting as the
story itself.
</P>
<P>
   Landing in this crowded sea this year will be Powerful Media, a
Web-based media information service with a big name editor, Kurt
Andersen, some seasoned media reporters and big-money investors
like James Cramer, a founder of TheStreet.com, and the venture
capital firm Flatiron Partners.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com will be used as an economic model. Parts of the
site will be free; others will require a subscription. There will
be databases. News coverage will be aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Expect a tone of certainty. Many stories, Andersen told Salon in
an interview, ``don't get reported with a kind of cut to the chase
authority _ `Here's the real story.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very rarely do you find that in the trades,'' he said. ``In
newspapers, partly because of the accreted protocols of the form,
you can't just say what's what.''
</P>
<P>
   Some competitors say the venture will fail for lack of
resources, that Powerful Media is overestimating the obsession with
media.
</P>
<P>
   Is Andersen obsessed?
</P>
<P>
   Not really, he says. It's just that ``the way in which our lives
_ for better and for worse _ are being transmogrified into a
wall-to-wall entertainment media dome is interesting to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Ad Giants Plan to Join Forces
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most powerful names in advertising are betting that
three heads will be better than one _ or even two.
</P>
<P>
   Three giant agency companies are planning to join forces to
create the world's No. 4 advertising behemoth in revenue, at $1.8
billion, and No. 5 in billings, at more than $13 billion. The deal
would unite the two largest privately held agency companies, Leo
Group in Chicago and MacManus Group in New York, while Dentsu, the
biggest agency in Japan, invests an undisclosed amount of cash to
acquire about a 20 percent stake in the merged operation.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is for the combined agency company _ so new that it has
only a tentative name, BDM, for Burnett, Dentsu and MacManus _ to
sell stock at some point this year. That is in itself a
considerable gamble, assuming that the bull market on Wall Street
for communications stocks roars on long enough for a lucrative
initial public offering to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   There is also no assurance that merging Leo and MacManus, even
with a cash infusion from Dentsu, will be sufficient to start
closing the gaps in revenue and billings with the Big Three agency
companies: Interpublic Group of Cos., Omnicom Group and WPP Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dentsu is huge in Japan, but minuscule in the U.S.,'' said
Alan J. Gottesman, who follows Madison Avenue for West End
Communications/Consulting in New York. ``And Burnett is huge in
Chicago, kind of OK in other places in the U.S. and not really
there in places outside the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is no guarantee that the cultures of the myriad
agencies being brought under the BDM umbrella will mesh rather than
clash. They include N.W. Ayer &AMP; Partners, Leo Burnett, D'Arcy
Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles Communications, the Kaplan Thaler Group,
Mediavest and Starcom.
</P>
<P>
   _ STUART ELLIOTT
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
