<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4695 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ELDERCARE-SHORTAGE-AR     01-02 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERCARE-SHORTAGE-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTAGE OF HOME HEALTH CARE WORKERS WHO SERVE ELDERLY 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.C., N.J., Fla., Pa., Md., Conn, N.Y., N.H.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By SARA RIMER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The booming economy is worsening a severe
shortage of the low-wage workers who care for the nation's growing
numbers of frail elderly people, health care experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of home health care nurses and aides and nursing
home assistants has deepened in the last two years as better paying
jobs with better conditions have opened up for the women who have
traditionally filled those positions, which have low wages and few
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   To a lesser extent, many in the industry say, cuts in Medicare
have made the strenuous jobs even more demanding as agencies have
made up for reduced income by requiring workers to deliver more
care in less time.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every state is grappling with the shortage in some way,
according to a national survey conducted this year by North
Carolina. New Jersey recently put the recruitment of home health
care workers at the top of its list of priorities for elderly care,
and states including Florida, Pennsylvania and Maryland have
established task forces to study the issue.
</P>
<P>
   A task force has also been formed in Connecticut by the
Association for Home Care, a trade organization, with the state
participating. In New York City, with its large pool of immigrant
workers, the shortage is less severe. But the rest of the state
mirrors the country, and the state's home care association is
looking for ways to find more workers.
</P>
<P>
   Even the experts cannot find help when they need it. Mary
Mongan, a registered nurse who is vice chairman of the New
Hampshire State Council on Aging and a former state health
commissioner, knows how to negotiate the health services world as
well as anyone. But when cancer was diagnosed in her 83-year-old
sister-in-law three years ago and the sister-in-law wanted to stay
at home, in Manchester, N.H., Ms. Mongan could not find home health
care aides who could provide 24-hour help.
</P>
<P>
   Her sister-in-law was forced to move to Maryland to live with
her daughter, Ms. Mongan said. ``We couldn't put together enough
dependable help,'' she said. ``They didn't have the manpower.''
</P>
<P>
   The shortage involves the people, most of them women from their
mid-20s to mid-40s, who do the basic, unpleasant and often
dangerous work _ bathing, changing diapers, cleaning bedsores,
feeding, lifting and transferring people in and out of bed _ for
the fastest growing population in the country, the very old. And
these days, more and more of those workers find they can earn about
the same wages at McDonald's, or Target.
</P>
<P>
   With somhealth care aides financed by Medicare, the
federal health insurance for the elderly, others by Medicaid, the
federal insurance for the poor, and even more through private
payments, it is difficult to accurately estimate the numbers of
home health care aides.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics puts the figure of aides financed
by Medicare and Medicaid at 697,000 in 1996, a number that includes
paid homemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of additional home health care workers will be
needed in the coming years, experts say, with the number of jobs to
be filled expected to increase by 76 percent between 1996 and 2006.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina alone will need about 21,000 more nursing aides
and other aides _ in nursing homes as well as in the community _
over the next five to six years, according to the state's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a bad economy, when you can't get any other job, and you
have a sixth-grade education, being a home health aide is an
attractive job,'' said Carol Keintz, executive director of the Home
Health Assembly of New Jersey, a nonprofit trade association. ``In
a good economy, when Dunkin' Donuts doesn't care if you've got a
sixth-grade education, it's tough to find people.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ms. Keintz said, fast food restaurants and retail
stores like Target offer steady, full-time work, often with
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Home care, with clients whose needs constantly change and with
Medicare limiting the number of visits, tends to be part time and
unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agencies can't say, `We can promise you a job every day,'''
Ms. Keintz said. ``Suddenly, five of their patients die, or go to
the hospital, and they say to the worker, `Don't come in today.'''
</P>
<P>
   Finding workers is particularly difficult in states like
Florida, where the tourism industry offers an abundance of
relatively unskilled jobs. ``We're having a terrific problem
finding home health care aides,'' said Gene Tischer, executive
director of the Associated Home Health Industries of Florida, a
nonprofit trade association.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That same level of worker is attracted to restaurants and
hotels. It's highly competitive,'' Tischer said. ``It's easier work
to go to Arby's than to go into your house and give your dad a
bath.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here in Philadelphia on Tuesday, Charmane Ellis, 33, had just
finished giving Antonietta Mannino, 81, a gentle sponge bath in her
small rowhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she was kneeling before the older woman, pulling on her
support stockings, orthopedic shoes and the brace she wears on her
right leg. In addition to severe arthritis, Mrs. Mannino has
suffered a series of small strokes. Because she is recovering from
a recent hospitalization after a fall down her front steps,
Medicare pays for Ms. Ellis' time.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mannino's husband, Thomas, a retired milkman, died five
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about him with Ms. Ellis, Mrs. Mannino began to weep.
Ms. Ellis stroked her arm. ``It's OK to cry, Mrs. Mannino,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ellis, a certified home health aide, earns $7.65 an hour, a
little more than the average for home health care aides in
Philadelphia. On such wages, plus health insurance, she is raising
four children alone in a public housing project here. She pulled
herself off welfare nearly two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In an industry where most home health agencies report a 40
percent to 60 percent turnover in aides every year, Charmane Ellis
is an anomaly. She has been doing this work for 14 years. For her,
like so many other dedicated aides, taking care of the elderly is a
calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like this is my thing to do in life,'' Ms. Ellis said.
``It makes me feel appreciated. I figure I'm going to be there one
day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like our founding fathers,'' she added, talking about
her clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot to tell. When bread was five cents, when their
mothers used to sit them outside, their pretty dresses,
crinolines.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ellis began her morning on Tuesday with a 45-minute ride on
the trolley, and then a 10-minute walk in the cold, to spend an
hour bathing and dressing Connie Prendergast, 77, in her rowhouse.
Mrs. Prendergast has cancer and is tethered to an oxygen tank 24
hours a day. Medicare pays for Ms. Ellis' visits to her as hospice
care.
</P>
<P>
   When someone dies on her watch, Ms. Ellis said, there is no time
to grieve. ``They pay you to go on to the next person like they're
just a number,'' she said. ``I'm a sensitive person. The aide needs
an hour to pull themselves together.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of her clients are appreciative. Home health care is
intimate, hands-on work, and one or two clients, who were white,
made it clear they did not want a black woman touching them, Ms.
Ellis said. Other clients are severely cognitively impaired, and
one man threw feces at her, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She cleaned herself off, Ms. Ellis said, and went about her job.
</P>
<P>
   After Mrs. Prendergast, Ms. Ellis spent a hurried hour with Mrs.
Mannino.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, before the Medicare cuts, she would have
had twice as much time. With the new constraints, she said, she was
unable to make Mrs. Mannino's bed, fix her lunch, or do the light
housecleaning that her job description includes. Mrs. Mannino, who
cannot walk unassisted, is too weak to do any of those things. She
is fortunate to have family members who can fill in.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Mrs. Mannino, Ms. Ellis made a 45-minute trolley trip to
the home of Emanuel Saunders. Saunders, a 75-year-old retired truck
driver, is in the advanced stages of Alzheimer's disease. He cannot
talk or walk or feed himself. His wife, Lillian, 58, who works in a
car assembly factory, and his daughter Kia, 28, greeted Ms. Ellis
warmly. With Kia's help, Ms. Ellis carefully lifted Saunders from
his wheelchair into bed, and changed the dressing on his bedsore.
His diaper did not need changing this time.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ellis works for an unusual agency. HomeCare Associates is
owned by the workers. In addition to offering wages that are about
20 per cent higher than the industry average, HomeCare offers its
aides health benefits and pays for the time they spend traveling to
clients. HomeCare was started six years ago by the Paraprofessional
Healthcare Institutnprofit health advocacy group in the
South Bronx that has opened two similar worker-owned home health
care agencies, one in the South Bronx, the other in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The three agencies offer their aides four weeks of training _
the industry norm is 75 hours _ and they try to give them full-time
work, as well as opportunities for advancement. Ms. Ellis hopes to
become a scheduler, working out of the office, and, eventually, a
nurse. The idea is to treat home health care aides like respected
professionals. The three agencies all report turnovers of less than
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a nation, if we truly are concerned about our elders, we
need to become more concerned about those people who are caring for
them on a daily basis,'' said Andy Van Kleunen, director of work
force policy for Paraprofessional Healthcare. ``In the past, we
could always assume there were going to be a lot of low-income men
and women out there to do the work. We didn't have to worry about
creating good jobs they'd be interested in staying in. If we want
to have enough caregivers for the elderly, we're going to have to
invest in those caregivers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-00 1855EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
