<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4707 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-Y2K-WORKERS-DISPERSE-     01-02 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-WORKERS-DISPERSE-1215(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YEAR BRINGS AN END FOR REPAIR CORPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Calif.)  (lb) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Paul Maszczak was tapped more than three years ago to head
his company's year 2000 computer repairs, he recalled, ``I
considered it the kiss of death.'' Instead of developing new
software using the latest technology, he would be relegated to
fixing programs written years or decades earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But Maszczak now says that becoming year 2000 manager at C.R.
Bard Inc., a medical-device manufacturer in Murray Hill, N.J., was
one of the best moves in his 30-year career in data processing. The
job lifted him out of the narrow confines of the information
technology department, exposing him to all aspects of his company's
business.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with those efforts winding down, Maszczak thinks his
broader business knowledge has prepared him for a bigger management
job. As for day-to-day systems work, ``I could never go back,'' he
said. Now, he said, ``we're free agents.''
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 has finally arrived, and the vast Y2K repair corps
is being scattered to the winds, having apparently saved the world
from the widespread disasters once feared.
</P>
<P>
   But while there is great relief that few year 2000 problems
emerged over the weekend, some Y2K workers, having completed a task
that has consumed them for months or years, must now struggle with
what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   Like Maszczak, some workers expect to go on to bigger and better
things. Most others are simply going back to previous jobs, as
corporate information-processing departments return to work they
had put aside in their race to repair year 2000 flaws. Yet for many
others, the end of the readiness efforts means the end of their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   For Randall Bart, for instance, year 2000 work proved to be a
short-lived bonanza. After being laid off from Unisys, the computer
maker, in 1988, Bart did not find work as a programmer until 10
years later, when Y2K made what he calls his ``obsolete
experience'' worth $45 an hour. But his last job ended in August
and Bart, 43, who lives in Los Angeles, has been unable to find
work since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping for some big disaster somewhere to hit,'' he said,
only half joking.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, year 2000 work is not ending abruptly. It has been
ratcheting down for months, and thousands of people have already
been dismissed, but work will continue, because computer problems
might still arise over the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Rubin, a consultant and head of the computer science
department at Hunter College in New York, who surveyed big
corporations about their preparedness activities, estimates that as
many as a fourth of the 2 million information technology workers in
big companies in the United States did Y2K repairs at one time or
another.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, computer people are not the only ones who got
involved. Many others were swept up in the effort _ contacting
suppliers and customers to assess their readiness, surveying
factory machinery, planning for contingencies and so on. All told,
many millions of people throughout the world were involved in year
2000 preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Many people profited handsomely, taking their share of the more
than $250 billion the world is estimated to have spent to enable
computers and other electronic machinery to recognize that a year
can begin with 20 instead of 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``It absolutely made our company,'' said Peter A. Allen,
president of Data Dimensions Inc., a computer consulting concern
that grew from about $1 million in annual revenues in the early
1990s to $115 million in 1998, 80 percent of it from year 2000
work.
</P>
<P>
   But that work has already slowed significantly, and the
Bellevue, Wash., company has laid off about 300 of its 850 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said the customer contacts and skills the company has
developed doing year 2000 work will help it move into other areas,
like electronic commerce. But investors are not so sure. Data
Dimension's stock price has fallen from a peak of almost $40 in
late 1997 to under $3 today.
</P>
<P>
   About two years ago there were predictions that the world would
not have enough programmers to scan billions of lines of code and
fix any date problems. Some programmers were lured out of
retirement to fix programs they had written decades earlier, and
there was even talk of enlisting prison inmates.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, salaries for programmers and systems analysts did jump,
and many companies offered retention bonuses to keep programmers
from jumping ship until well into 2000. Union Bank of California,
for instance, gave year 2000 workers bonuses equal to 10 percent of
their salaries in 1998 and 1999. Those who stay until March will be
eligible for an additional bonus equal to 20 percent of their
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   But the great shortage never materialized. Many companies that
were started to do year 2000 work for others got far less business
than they had anticipated. While early predictions were that
repairs would cost $1 or $2 for each line of code, prices dropped
to 25 cents a line or even lower. And many retirees did not find
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that the repairs turned out to be less complex
than had been imagined, in part because software was developed to
help automate the process. Indeed, the year 2000 was quickly
transformed from a problem involving older computer programs to a
generalized business, political and legal issue, as companies
wrestled with contingency planning, supplier and customer
relationships and questions of legal liability and public
relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The code really has been the smallest issue in all of this,''
said Lou Marcoccio, research director at Gartner Group, another
consulting company. In many companies, he said, the nonprogrammers
working on the problem outnumbered the programmers.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, companies were able to handle it, even if they
occasionally had to strain to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, the consultant, said that on average, big companies spent
about 10 percent of their information technology budgets over three
years of year 2000 repairs, although for peak periods the issue
consumed as much as half the computer budgets of some companies.
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., for instance, spent $520 million over several
years on its year 2000 effort, but the brokerage spends $3.2
billion a year on information technology.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies did the job in-house, even if it meant pushing
other work aside. It was cheaper that way and the company's own
programmers were most familiar with the software that had to be
fixed. Edison International, which owns Southern California Edison,
did its year 2000 work for $70 million after rejecting a
contractor's offer to do it for $171 million, said Eric Trapp, who
managed the job for the utility.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies contracted work to firms in India, where wages
are lower. But some industry officials say there was also less of
that than had been predicted.
</P>
<P>
   For repair companies and individual programmers wondering what
to do next, the good news is that there is an overall shortage of
computer people, especially as software development that was
postponed to deal with year 2000 work moves back up companies'
priority lists.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that the greatest demand is for people who can
design Internet software, especially for electronic retailing; the
expertise of most year 2000 companies and workers lies in older
computers and programs, known as legacy systems.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
