<DOCNO> NYT20000102.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4708 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-Y2K-WORKERS-DISPERSE-     01-02 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 BCRKERS-DISPERSE-2NDTAKE-NYT  
 UNDATED: legacy systems.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``These people built up the Latin of technology,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Still if the episode taught the world anything, it is that these
legacy systems are vital and are not going away any time soon.
There is still a lot of work to be done on them, including enabling
them to connect to Internet software. And many companies have put
off these other jobs while they focused on the year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been building up a really nice backlog of things to
do,'' said Lee Kirkpatrick, senior vice president and year 2000
manager for Union Bank, who said the priority would shift to
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch rushed to finish most year 2000 work by June 30 so
it could devote more resources to designing its online
stock-trading system, said John McKinley, the brokerage's chief
technology officer. Now, he said, former year 2000 programmers are
being put on jobs like getting the company ready for 24-hour stock
exchanges and decimalization of stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   With Y2K, computer professionals, often stereotyped as geeks and
loners, found themselves the life of the party, sought out by
laymen friends for counsel on whether the world was really going to
end on Jan. 1. More people within corporations and in society came
to appreciate the importance of their work.
</P>
<P>
   But the limelight was not always comfortable. After all, it was
programmers who created the year 2000 problem by representing years
using two digits instead of four, a tactic that seemed rational in
the early days of computing as a way to conserve scarce computer
memory and data storage. If Jan. 1 had brought a rash of mishaps,
the computer profession would have faced even more criticism for
shoddy work, and perhaps pressure for government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, now that the date rollover appears to be going
smoothly, some critics are saying that the threat was exaggerated
by computer professionals out to make a buck.
</P>
<P>
   While there were clearly some charlatans, many programmers still
recovering from an exhausting, nerve-racking race against an
immutable deadline are now feeling like victims of their own
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm already hearing that from my own family _ that it's all
been overblown,'' said Celia Murray, a systems analyst with the
Office of Real Property Services, a New York state agency. ``I
think it could have been really bad, no question about it. A lot of
people worked really hard. That's the reason people can sit here
and say it's all overblown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
