<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4723 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1100(TR     01-02 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1100(TRIMS)-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL AND SYRIA WILL ATTEMPT TO SURMOUNT OLD OBSTACLES TO PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Having done little more than break the ice in their
first encounter last month, Israeli and Syrian leaders enter
knottier terrain Monday as they resume U.S.-brokered negotiations
ambitiously aimed at reaching a peace accord by the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The mere fact of their meeting was achievement enough when the
Israelis and the Syrians revived their peace effort in December
after a four-year stalemate. This time the two sides will be forced
to tackle directly the tangle of issues that have bedeviled their
previous efforts at peacemaking: borders, security, and the
establishment of normal relations.
</P>
<P>
   But with an apparently strong will to overcome their
differences, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and Foreign
Minister Farouk al-Sharaa of Syria, both of whom left for the
United States Sunday, have agreed to lock themselves and their
delegations away with U.S. mediators in a West Virginia hotel for
the next week to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   U.S., Syrian and Israeli officials have been careful to damp
expectations that the talks would produce anything concrete, and
Israeli officials distanced themselves from earlier assessments
that a general declaration of principles or some kind of written
document would emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Barak's departing words as he left Ben Gurion Airport
near Tel Aviv made it clear that he saw his trip as significant
enough to be placed in the context of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here on this runway, Menahem Begin took off to Camp David, and
this is where he returned from Camp David,'' Barak said, invoking
the legacy of the late prime minister who made peace with Egypt 20
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``And here from this runway, Yitzhak Rabin took off to bring
peace with Jordan, and thereafter with the Palestinians,'' Barak
said, referring to the assassinated prime minister who was his
mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright Sunday described ``a huge
historic opportunity'' in the renewed negotiations, but she
declined to predict how many rounds of talks it might take to reach
an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's official newspaper, reflecting the dour public posture
that Syria has taken since talks resumed last month, expressed
pointed doubts about the possibility of accomplishment. ``The
outcome of the first round does not give us reason to be
optimistic,'' the daily Al-Thawra said.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak's ultimate goal for the negotiations is clear. And in
the last few weeks, he has started to build a case for why Israelis
should coalesce to support a withdrawal from the Golan Heights _
the sine qua non of a Syrian-Israeli accord.
</P>
<P>
   It is a mixed message, combining scare tactics with appeals to a
battle-scarred nation's fantasies of peace. But it presumes that
the negotiations, to be held at a hotel in Shepherdstown, W.Va.,
will bear fruit in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Barak dreams aloud of a near utopia if the
peace effort succeeds: not only an end to battle but harmony in the
Middle East, ``unprecedented economic growth'' in Israel and a
``sky high'' international image for his country. On the other, he
warns of violent cataclysm if it fails.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has also tried to lure Israelis with the prospect of
bringing Israeli soldiers home from southern Lebanon by summer,
even of shortening the compulsory three-year military service.
Israeli officials leaked last week that the prime minister had
approved a plan to withdraw from Lebanon, which is controlled by
Syria, as soon as April, if the atmosphere in the negotiations is
positive.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to revive an old-fashioned Zionist self-righteousness,
Barak has also appealed to ``this generation'' to be unselfish
enough to make sacrifices that will benefit the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price of even the most successful war is immeasurably more
expensive than the price of peace, no matter how heavy,'' he wrote
during the weekend in a rare published message to the nation. ``So
we must not be deterred from this decision. At the moment of truth,
Israel will discover its courage for the sake of peace and
security. This will be the complete triumph of Zionism, its
pinnacle and realization.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Barak has scrupulously avoided public discussion of the issues
that will be on the table in this week's talks. Instead, already
strategizing for a national referendum on peace _ in which he is
expected to enlist U.S. consultants as he did during his election
campaign _ he aims to focus Israelis on the grand picture.
</P>
<P>
   But the details are what will sit between Barak and al-Sharaa
when they meet behind very closed doors at the Shepherdstown
Clarion Hotel, some 68 miles from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials were describing ``Sing-Sing'' or ``siege
conditions'' for the negotiators, who will be prevented from
entering or exiting at will to create an air-tight _ and leak-proof
_ diplomatic environment.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, although depriving Israelis of their cellular
telephones is tantamount to cutting off a critical life support
mechanism, the rules of the game will require them to turn off
their phones.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear if Barak will stay put or come and go. Several
world political leaders, including Russia's recently resigned
president, Boris Yeltsin, are expected to pass through Israel when
they travel later this week to Bethlehem for an Orthodox Christmas
celebration organized by the Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Barak will be accompanied by a delegation of about 25
negotiators, including Foreign Minister David Levy and Tourism
Minister Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, who held negotiations with the Syrian
army leader when he was Israel's army chief of staff in the
mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   As in December, al-Sharaa will represent Syrian President Hafez
Assad, 69, who is considered too weak to travel and reluctant to do
so at this stage.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After a welcoming speech by President Clinton, the Israelis and
the Syrians are expected to break into working groups. Barak's
office said that security and water will be discussed before the
thorny issue of borders, but the Syrians have maintained that the
issue of borders is paramount and must come first.
</P>
<P>
   Syria demands the full return of the Golan Heights, which Israel
captured during the 1967 War, down to the June 4, 1967, border.
They see this border as reaching the shoreline of the Sea of
Galilee. While Israel appears ready to concede territory, it is
unwilling to withdraw beyond the international border established
in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   The distance is a few square miles, what Barak has called ``a
stone's throw,'' but it is a crucially located few miles, and the
dispute has stymied the negotiations for years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To avoid getting bogged down and to better assess Syria's
flexibility on another issue, Barak prefers to start with a
discussion of security issues. The Israelis would demand an
internationally run monitoring station on Mount Hermon, between the
new Israeli and Syrian borders. Israelis have long insisted that
there should be an Israeli force in that station, which the Syrians
reject entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrians reportedly prefer a satellite and aerial inspection
system, according to accounts in several Arab newspapers. They hope
to convince Barak, a former general, that warning stations on the
ground would provide inferior intelligence to aerial systems.
</P>
<P>
   Israel and Syria will also negotiate the deployment of Syrian
troops and their proximity to the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next week or 10 days, we will learn a lot about their
readiness to accept our security demands,'' said Cabinet Minister
Haim Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   In his campaign to win public support for the talks, Barak has
received a direct assist from President Ezer Weizman, who is
expected to remain neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Endorsing a withdrawal from the Golan Heights, Weizman has
called this a critical juncture in which ``peace has to come before
everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   If a peace agreement with Syria were reached, and a peace
referendum failed an Israeli national vote, he would ``go home,''
Weizman said.
</P>
<P>
   When right-wing groups protested that he should be the president
of everyone and not take sides, Weizman shrugged and said it was
``too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesting Barak's ``campaign of propaganda,'' Uzi Landau, a
Likud Party legislator, called on the opposition to reveal ``the
throwing of sand in the eyes.'' Some, indeed, have criticized the
way that former generals, colleagues of Barak, are now re-assessing
the strategic value of the Golan Heights that was long considered
an invaluable geographic defense against Syrian aggression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it all a fraud? Was it 30 years of brainswashing?''
Emmanuel Halperin, who anchors a television news show, asked a
former general, Ori Orr, recently. ``Were the opinions of all those
American generals who said the Golan was indispensable to Israel's
survival completely invalid?''
</P>
<P>
   And even some ardent members of the peace camp have questioned
the eagerness of many Israelis to accept a new reality overnight.
Eitan Haber, a former senior aide to Rabin, responded to Barak's
constant praise of Assad and to a glowing account in an Israeli
newspaper from a reporter who sneaked into Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly it turns out that the Syrian dictator, Hafez Assad,
is a brave, visionary, intelligent leader, a pursuer of peace, a
great man and a real sweetheart,'' Haber wrote in a newspaper
column. ``And the Syrian people? Darlings. Damascus is wonderful.
Generations of Syrians have been praying for nothing but peace.
Every morning they wake up to the sound of ``Hatikva,'' the Israeli
anthem, ``and kiss the picture of Theodore Herzl.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
