<HEADER>
A4732 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ILL-SCHOOL-JACKSON-43     01-02 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILL-SCHOOL-JACKSON-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE TO RULE SOON ON EXPULSION OF 6 STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DECATUR, Ill. _ A federal judge has announced that he will rule
in early January on whether the expulsions of six students involved
in a melee at a high school football game here will be overturned.
</P>
<P>
   In hearings last week before Judge Michael McCuskey of U.S.
District Court in Urbana, Ill., lawyers for the students, all of
them black, contended that the school district acted improperly by
expelling them as a group and not judging the cases one by one.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed by the Rainbow/PUSH Coalition, the civil
rights organization headed by the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson, who led a
series of demonstrations in November to protest the board's action.
The case has sparked a debate over the fairness of so-called
zero-tolerance behavior policies, which have become common in
schools around the country.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony at the hearing, it was disclosed that black
students accounted for more than 80 percent of the expulsions in
Decatur in the last four years, even though they made up less than
half of the enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   School officials testified that they followed the usual
procedures in meting out two-year expulsions for the disturbance on
Sept. 27. They said race played no role in their consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Boehm, the principal of MacArthur High School, witnessed the
brawl that swept through the grandstand and told the judge that the
parents and students at the game, between MacArthur and Eisenhower,
had been terrified by the violence. Three of the students in the
case also face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 27 years, I have never experienced anything like this,''
Boehm said. ``I think you had to be there to appreciate the
turmoil, the stress and the fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The board cut the penalties to one-year expulsions and offered
to let the students attend an alternative school immediately after
Gov. George Ryan, a Republican, came here to try to broker a
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson rejected the offer, saying the district should allow
the students to return to school in January. He urged the school
board to order the students to undergo counseling, noting that no
weapons were involved in the brawl and that no one was seriously
injured.
</P>
<P>
   While Jackson initially said race did not play a major role in
the case, he said last week that it was ``very apparent'' the
students were given harsher penalties because they were black. But
he added that strict discipline codes were also being unwisely used
to punish white students around the country. ``Students, whether
black or white, are in some cases being treated as expendable and
thrown away,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last week, the school board said it would allow the two seniors
to graduate in June with classmates if they earn enough credits at
the alternative school. The board also offered to let the other
students return to school as early as this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the hearing, McCuskey bristled when lawyers for the school
district tried to call witnesses to discuss the academic records of
the expelled students. The judge noted that school board officials
had earlier testified that they had not examined the students'
academic records before deciding to expel them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in what they looked at, not in what they could
have looked at,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also blocked testimony from school officials about gang
activity in Decatur, an industrial city of about 80,000 people in
central Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Delphine Kendrix, a mother of one of the expelled students,
testified that a school official had discouraged her from appealing
the expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   School district officials strongly denied that they had told any
parents not to fight the expulsions.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Perkins, one of two blacks on the seven-member Decatur
school board, said the board's discussion of the expulsions had
become heated.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, who cast the lone vote against expulsion, testified
that one board member had characterized the students involved in
the fight as ``running about like a pack of dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `If it was seven white students, we wouldn't be having
this discussion,''' Perkins testified.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the students said the only previous two-year
expulsion in Decatur involved a student who brought a loaded gun to
school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-00 1952EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
