<DOCNO> NYT20000102.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4733 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ROSTENKOWSKI-PROFILE-     01-02 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSTENKOWSKI-PROFILE-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 YEARS OUT OF PRISON, ROSTENKOWSKI IS BACK ON THE SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Dan Rostenkowski bounds out of his office and barks:
``Grab your coat, let me show you the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the house, he says, his house, the one his Polish
grandfather built from the ground up. There, across the street, is
the famous church, St. Stanislaus Kostka, the one he moved a
highway to save. His eyes are gleaming, twinkling, as he lurches
from tale to tale. He looks trim, stylish even, in his soft gray
turtleneck. He's swapped steak and potatoes for fish and linguine.
And make that one martini, not four. ``I sleep better at night,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Back inside his office, there's a photograph on the credenza of
the one-time, all-powerful chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee snuggling with his brand-new grandchild, a big smile
across his face.
</P>
<P>
   Cuddly, debonair, sparkly eyed _ Dan Rostenkowski, the man who
made colleagues quake and lobbyists cower? Has Rosty, the
quintessential deal-maker, turned into a bit of a softy? ``I'm
riding the crest of the wave,'' Rostenkowski admits.
</P>
<P>
   It has been two years since he finished his ``sabbatical'' at
the Oxford, Wis., prison compound and the halfway house that came
next. He paid his 17-month penance for using taxpayer money to buy
chairs and crystal domes for his friends and to hire people to mow
his lawn. Suddenly, he's popping up all over Washington, a place he
feared might throw a permanent sneer his way.
</P>
<P>
   Catch him at Morton's for dinner. In his office in Arlington,
Va., for business. On ``Hardball'' on MSNBC for some political
analysis. On Fox News to gab about the Gore-Bradley debate. (He
actually debuted on Fox in Chicago soon after his release.) This
week, it is the American Enterprise Institute panel to talk about
Bill Bradley and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   His probation is up, too. ``I'm a free man,'' he shouted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that for the first two years out of Oxford, I was kind
of looking at my shoes and my belly button,'' said Rostenkowski,
72, during a chat in his office, which is attached to his house on
the northwest side of the city. ``I kept my eyes down. I was
embarrassed. I was ashamed. I didn't know how people would accept
me. I didn't think then that I would be a commentator on
television, that I would be a senior fellow at a university, that
I'd be lecturing to corporate boards and be paid for consulting. I
didn't think those things would be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The psychic turning point came just two months ago, when he set
foot for the first time on Capitol Hill, the scene of his 35-year
rise and fall. He was there to attend a book party for Richard E.
Cohen, the author of ``Rostenkowski: The Pursuit of Power and the
End of the Old Politics,'' an account that summed him up as a
powerhouse who got important things done. But the event felt more
like a coming home party for the man who ruled and protected his
committee with an iron fist.
</P>
<P>
   All his old pals were there _ Rep. Charles Rangel of New York,
now the ranking Democrat on the committee; Commerce Secretary Bill
Daley of Chicago; former Rep. Tom Downey, who served on the
committee at one time.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago, Rangel held a Ways and Means reunion for
the Democrats at a Georgetown restaurant. ``He called everybody up
and said the chairman's going to be there, the chairman's going to
be there. And people felt an obligation to go out. As a matter of
fact, although everybody says this after the second cocktail, there
was a possibility of us forming an alumni association of the Ways
and Means Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite his recent rebound, there is one place he hasn't had
the heart to visit: the Ways and Means Committee room, now occupied
by Rep. Bill Archer, a Texas Republican who Rosty froze out of
committee negotiations. ``Can you imagine how my heart would have
broken if I was defeated but I was still in charge? The salve in my
defeat is I can't picture myself sitting to the right of Bill
Archer and listening to him vacillate.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot that depresses him about Washington politics
nowadays, he says. ``It's amazing to me how McCain can talk about
Washington as if he's from Arizona,'' said the former chairman, the
ultimate insider, about Sen. John McCain, the candidate for the
Republican presidential nomination. Dumping on Washington,
Rostenkowski said, is ``a cop out.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's no teamwork anymore, he said. With such a narrow
majority in the House, nobody wants to make the rough decision,
take the tough vote. ``I feel sorry for the country because we're
standing in place,'' he said. The Republicans still haven't figured
out how to govern, he said. ``It's one thing to make the snowballs
and throw them. It's another thing when the ice melts and you've
got to start constructing something that's going to lead the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that explains his own re-emergence: ``People remember that
there was a certainty and stability in Rostenkowski that there
isn't today.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He still raves about former President Bush, who deserves more
credit for today's robust economy, he says, and he thinks highly of
former Speaker Newt Gingrich even though he is easy to poke fun at:
For example, there was the trip to the Persian Gulf during Desert
Storm, when Gingrich sat ``talking about Gen. Foch and Petain. What
the hell. We're going over there for photo ops with all the kids,
where you can fry an egg on the damn helmet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I admire Gingrich in that he had a goal and he beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Gingrich's recent marital troubles, he smirked, and said,
``Thank God, all my girls are dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman has always had a soft spot for President Clinton.
``He was kind of like a kid brother to me,'' he said. ``Geez, he
was bright, and a convincing brightness, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned Clinton about ``biting off more than he could chew on
health care. You're not in Hot Springs, Ark., anymore. You're in
the major leagues.'' Today, he regrets not being more insistent.
``He was a novice,'' Rostenkowski said, looking back.
</P>
<P>
   And if you ask him what was the most physically tiring moment of
his life, he wouldn't say the indictment and going to prison. ``It
was the '86 tax act,'' he said, referring to the landmark bill he
helped fashion and land on President Reagan's desk. ``I was that
close to a nervous breakdown,'' he said, making the universal
gesture for teeny with his thumb and index finger.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He takes a decidedly rosy view of his conviction, except for the
toll it exacted on his family and staff (``I paid all their legal
bills,'' he said). His Capitol Hill secretary still works for him,
and his former press secretary said they all refer to themselves as
``staff for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rostenkowski continues to insist that he did nothing wrong. The
old rules for getting things done changed and changed again, and he
didn't take notice. ``I mean, giving gifts away,'' he said. ``I
don't want to read in your article that we were all doing it,
because I don't know that we were all doing it. But I would be
surprised if we weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I was more extravagant than anybody else,'' he added.
``But then again I was a bigger man than everybody else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
