<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000102.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4737 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-PARTY-POLITICS-3TAKES     01-02 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-POLITICS-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITIVE RACES DWINDLE AS MORE CANDIDATES OPT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Texas, Maine, Colo., Neb., Ky., Nev.)  (nk) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINTER HAVEN, Fla. _ Rick and Julie Dantzler thought they had
made their decision back in April: Despite the pleas of party
leaders, despite the lure of an open seat, Rick would not run for
Congress this year.
</P>
<P>
   They were still burned out and bruised from his unsuccessful
campaigns for both the Democratic nomination for governor and
lieutenant governor in Florida in 1998. Their daughters, Liz, 13,
and Margaret, 10, were thriving, and as Julie put it: ``We get one
shot at 10 and 13. We only get one shot at that.''
</P>
<P>
   But as 1999 wound to a close, and there was no Democratic
candidate in the race, the Dantzlers found themselves wrestling
with the decision one more time, while Democrats in Florida and
Washington watched in suspense. One question kept coming up. ``Can
you make enough of a difference there to really justify what you're
going to be missing here?'' Dantzler asked, surrounded by his
family on a quiet December afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In a year like 2000, when the two parties are locked in an
furious battle for control of the House, the civics books would
suggest that candidates like Dantzler would be lining up to join
the fray. In fact, while both parties hail their success in getting
experienced, high-quality candidates to run, many potential
candidates will agonize over the decision and quite a few will
ultimately say no.
</P>
<P>
   The reluctance of these candidates is part of the explanation
for a striking reality in American politics this year. For all the
talk about the battle for the House, perhaps as few as a tenth of
the congressional districts will have truly competitive races, with
a fair contest of ideas and agendas. And the more that strong
candidates bow out, the fewer real battles there will be.
</P>
<P>
   In most districts, held by well-financed incumbents, there will
probably not be much of a battle at all, many political
professionals say. ``I think the dirty little secret is out, that
94 percent of all incumbents win,'' said Charles Cook, a longtime
analyst of congressional campaigns who publishes a political
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   It is a paradox for what was intended by the framers as ``the
people's house,'' so responsive and closely attuned to the voters
that it needed the Senate to keep it in check.
</P>
<P>
   And this lack of competition has consequences for how Congress
operates, some scholars and analysts say _ like the creation of an
ever more polarized House, with incumbents increasingly insulated
from challenges from the other party that would push them to the
center. It may also help explain such political puzzles as the
impeachment of a president in defiance of the public opinion polls,
some say.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to tell exactly how many districts will have
hotly contested races this year, but some analysts predict no more
than 35 to 45. In 1998, 94 districts were completely uncontested by
a major political party, the highest number since 1958. And many
more are contested in name only; in a third of the contested races
in 1996, for example, one candidate outspent the other by more than
9-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   The deterrents to running for Congress these days are huge _ the
extraordinary demands of fund-raising, the all-consuming nature of
modern campaigns, the cost in time and stability to young families
and dual career marriages, the slender prospects of defeating an
incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   And many campaign strategists say that at the end of the decade,
there are special reasons for an ambitious politician to sit it
out: Even if that candidate wins, he or she faces the possibility
of having to begin all over again in a reconfigured district, with
a lot of different voters, after the congressional districts are
redrawn following the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in an election like 2000, at the very end of a
redistricting cycle, congressional elections tend to become far
more stable; the obvious mismatches and political opportunities _ a
liberal congressman representing a conservative district, or vice
versa _ have been corrected by the voters by now.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the current political climate, a time of relative
peace and prosperity, with much less anger toward Washington than
was bubbling before the great upheaval of 1994, when the
Republicans took control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give me a recession, a gridlocked Congress and a war, and
I'll show you candidates coming out the woodwork to run,'' said
Stuart Rothenberg, another congressional analyst who publishes a
political newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say it is to the parties' advantage to contain
their field of battle and thus focus their resources on a small
number of targets; a net shift of just five seats would change
control of the House, meaning that neither party needs to move a
lot of seats.
</P>
<P>
   But political scientists say it is hardly healthy for much of
the country to be excluded from the battle for the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a terrible aspect of our politics, if voters are
not even offered an opportunity to vote for the party of their
choice,'' said James E. Campbell, professor of political science at
the State University of New York at Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas E. Mann, an expert on Congress at the Brookings
Institution, sees it as an odd tradeoff: After four decades in
which the Democrats seemed a permanent majority in the House, the
two parties are now nearly evenly matched; the Republican majority
of 222 was among the smallest of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   So there is intense competition between the two parties, he
says; it is simply being brought to bear on a small percentage of
the seats, like Cold War superpowers vying for a tiny piece of
strategic terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional politics has a way of bucking longterm predictions
and transforming itself very quickly, and nobody knows how enduring
this pattern will be. What is clear is that running a serious race
for Congress these days is a series of high hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   And Sandy Maisel, a professor of government at Colby College in
Maine, said, ``I think the cumulative effect of those deterrents is
that high-quality candidates for one reason or another opt out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Money: The Chilling Effect Of Raising Funds
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, in a study financed by the National Science Foundation,
Maisel and Walter J. Stone of the University of Colorado began to
survey potential candidates in 200 congressional districts, trying
to determine who runs for office, who does not, and why. Among all
the deterrents, from a loss of privacy to a fear of negative
advertising, one factor was cited twice as often as any other:
having to raise the vast amounts of money necessary to run.
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly true for potential candidates considering a
run against incumbents, who nearly always have an easier time
raising money. Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center for
Responsive Politics, an independent group that tracks campaign
finance, said that the average incumbent had $315,000 in the bank
at the end of June, 18 months before the next election. ``You've
got to be nuts to jump in as a challenger in a situation like
that,'' Makinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The money factor also has a chilling effect on potential
candidates for open seats, which ordinarily invite competition.
Even those who decide to take the plunge swallow hard over the
money and what it portends.
</P>
<P>
   Florida state Rep. Adam Putnam, 25, a Republican whiz kid who is
already in his second term, has estimated that it will take
$750,000 to $850,000 to wage his campaign for Congress this year in
the 12th District, a seat now held by Rep. Charles T. Canady, a
Republican who is retiring. And then there's the money that will
pour into the district from outside groups, said Putnam, considered
the leading Republican in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really just gives you heartburn to think about,'' he said
at a restaurant in Bartow not long ago. ``Not as much the financial
implications as what that message is going to be that these
out-of-towners are going to be saying about you or on your behalf,
which you have no control over. That's spooky to me.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Lori Edwards, a 42-year-old Democrat who has won four
terms in this region, also saw a campaign for Florida's 12th as a
``natural progression'' _ at least initially.
</P>
<P>
   The 12th District is a slice of ``Old Florida'' in the central
part of the state, east of Tampa, dotted by lakes and citrus groves
and still largely oriented toward agriculture. When she first
looked at the race, the money needed to run there seemed ``real
doable'' to Ms. Edwards, who describes herself as solidly middle
class: Canady had never had to spend more than $350,000 on a
campaign. But the popular incumbent had managed to avoid a huge
television campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Edwards began to prepare for the race, she learned this
was no longer possible. ``All of a sudden the price tag for this
race was going up to $1 million,'' Ms. Edwards said, an assessment
not that far off Putnam's.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that was the prospect of immediate redistricting, at
the hands of a state Legislature led by Republicans. ``So even if I
was elected, not only would I have to turn around and raise $1
million again, but the Republican-controlled state Legislature is
not going to be too happy about losing this seat,'' Ms. Edwards
said.
</P>
<P>
   In October, five months after she entered the race, Ms. Edwards
withdrew, with money a major factor. ``It wasn't even that I didn't
think it could be done,'' she said. ``It was because I didn't want
to do it. My deepest worry was that after you do all that begging,
and after all those people give you all that money, how can you
keep your independence? My experience in the state Legislature
showed it can be done, but I never had to beg for a million
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost of Texas, who for several years was chairman
of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, said of the
money demands: ``I'd prefer that it be different, but you play the
hand you're dealt. But it does discourage some people from
running.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Family: Weighing the Cost Of Time and Travel
</P>
<P>
   It was not the money that deterred Joe Hogsett, who considered
running for an open seat in Indiana this year. It was the sheer
amount of time and energy that it takes to run in a competitive
district these days, balanced against the demands of family.
</P>
<P>
   Hogsett, a 43-year-old Democrat, was no political novice, after
six years as Indiana's secretary of state, an unsuccessful Senate
race in 1992 and an unsuccessful bid for Congress in 1994. He said
he knew what it would take, and he knew it was too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very young family,'' he said. ``My spouse and I have
a young son and we hope to add to our family in the future. So
ultimately the decision this year weighed what I knew on the one
hand were the enormous responsibilities of running for Congress _
the time, the energy, the resources _ with maintaining my
obligations as a spouse, as a father, with work, practicing law
here in Indianapolis.''
</P>
<P>
   Many political professionals say that running a competitive
campaign essentially means giving up your job for a year. Then
there's the privacy factor, at a time when personal lives are just
one more line of inquiry in a political campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, who for several years was chairman
of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, said people would
tell him: ``I don't want the scrutiny. I don't want the divorce I
had 20 years ago to be examined. I don't want my kids to go through
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if candidates make it through these pitfalls, they face the
complicated task of working in Washington, keeping a strong
presence in the district on the weekends, and somehow fitting a
family life in between. Rep. Anne M. Northup, R-Ky., who heads her
party's effort to recruit candidates for the House, said
``everybody asks the same questions'' and the logistics of family
life are at the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're looking at candidates who have a lot to offer, one
of the reasons they have a lot to offer is because they've carried
big responsibilities,'' Ms. Northup said. ``They have a whole
demanding life _ jobs, responsibilities _ and there are going to be
a lot of people who have to make adjustments if they run.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark James, a Republican state senator in Nevada, was another
top-tier candidate who was urged to run this year _ against a
Democratic freshman who won with less than 50 percent of the vote
in 1998 _ but decided he could not because of his family. James,
40, has a 10-year-old son and a 12-year-old daughter; he could not
see how he could maintain a bicoastal household and get enough time
with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't that I don't want to serve, or don't want to make
sacrifices,'' he said, adding that he would not rule out a race in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dantzlers were torn over whether the difference Dantzler
could make in Washington would be worth the cost in family life.
They were a seasoned political family, having lived through a
statewide campaign and several high-profile races for the state
House and Senate, where Dantzler had served for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   But they have a rooted life in Florida, they said. Mrs. Dantzler
works as a mental health counselor, the daughters are involved in
soccer and theater, their families go back several generations in
the state. If he ran and won, the Dantzlers think the family would
stay in Florida, at least in the beginning, which would mean a
bifurcated life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that my kids will be fine,'' Rick Dantzler said as he
envisioned that life. ``And I'm sure that Julie and I will stay
together. But I'm not sure that I want to miss it. The idea of
getting on a plane on Monday and coming back on Friday and asking
Julie how it was with the girls for the last three days ...''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, ``I'm only 43, I enjoy public
service and I like to think there's another race in me yet.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Julie said they planned to make their decision after the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Consequences: An Electoral Process With Fewer Battles
</P>
<P>
   The sum total of all these personal decisions is less
competitive politics, some analysts say. They disagree on how much
of that is due to short-term causes _ the peace-and-prosperity
political climate, the stable congressional politics that is often
a hallmark of the end of a decade _ and how much is due to
deterrents less likely to change, like huge fund-raising
requirements and virtually nonstop campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But some scholars say that whatever the causes, the lack of
competition has consequences, particularly when incumbents grow
accustomed to it. As Maisel and Stone wrote in their study,
``Representative democracy depends fundamentally on a competitive
electoral process.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, some potential candidates are looking
elsewhere. Ms. Edwards has decided to run for supervisor of
elections in Polk County, Fla. She says it is a good and
interesting job where she believes she can make a contribution.
</P>
<P>
   And, she added, ``The cost of the race is a manageable one, and
the outcome of the race will depend much more on my grass-roots
effort, talking to people, shaking hands.''
</P>
<P>
   She was clearly looking forward to the coming campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
