<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WORLD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKING TO MAKE FOREIGN POLICY HIS FOCUS IN NEW YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For much of his presidency, Bill Clinton's own
aides have frequently complained that his attention to foreign
policy was sporadic. The trait got him in trouble in Bosnia, and
often resulted in some nasty surprises _from the defeat of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty last fall to a tear-gas-filled week
in Seattle that badly damaged his global economic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But some of his biggest victories in 1999 were also scored
abroad, from the air campaign over Serbia that largely halted
ethnic bloodshed to the agreement in Northern Ireland that offers
the first prospect of peace there.
</P>
<P>
   And now Clinton's aides describe a president who has determined
_ for reasons as practical as political reality and as personal as
the emptiness of his residence _ to make foreign policy the focus
of his last 12 months in office.
</P>
<P>
   It is the one arena where he believes he can stand out and
continue to wield power as two major political campaigns _ one
starring his wife, the other his vice president _ take more and
more of the spotlight, his aides say.
</P>
<P>
   And it is an escape from a White House that one of his close
advisers calls ``a very lonely place these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's schedule calls for a constant stream of foreign trips,
each casting him in a different role: peacemaker, international
financial architect and missionary seeking converts to
American-style democratic capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   He starts this week by shuttling in and out of Shepherdstown,
W.Va., by helicopter to coax along Israel and Syria in what, if
successful, could prove to be a peace accord as important as Camp
David.
</P>
<P>
   But that will be only the opening move in a blur of diplomatic
motion _ driven by the president's desire to avoid looking like a
lame duck, and fueled by his determination to make up for time lost
during the impeachment battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never uses the word `legacy' but he talks about it all the
time,'' one of his longtime friends said.
</P>
<P>
   Others say Clinton is driven to look abroad in part because
there is little reason to stay in Washington. While there is still
a chance of a deal with Republicans on Medicare or other major
elements of Clinton's domestic agenda, the president himself has
told aides in recent meetings that the likelihood fades as the
summer draws near.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hillary Rodham Clinton is making one of the most
public early departures from the White House by a first lady in
presidential history in anticipation of a possible run for the
Senate. She is moving the family's scant collection of furnishings
to a new house in Chappaqua, N.Y., a place where few expect the
president to spend much time next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's happier on the road,'' said one Cabinet member who has
accompanied the president on several recent trips, ticking off the
possible stops in 2000: India, Nigeria, Okinawa, several
destinations in Europe, a possible trip to Russia after the June
election of a new president there, and perhaps even a visit to a
place about which he spent much of his youth debating: Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't campaign for Gore,'' the Cabinet member said during a
holiday party, referring to the vice president's effort to distance
himself from Clinton. ``Fund-raising is a chore. But he's come to
love the puzzle of the geopolitics.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, it was a love that took time to kindle. But since this
past August, when he interrupted his vacation with regular morning
calls to Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and other Middle East
leaders, Clinton has acted like a man in a race against time to
bring about a final settlement with the Palestinians and, now, with
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Monday in Shepherdstown, he will once again insert
himself into the negotiations. Dipping in and out of the talks at
strategic moments, aides say, Clinton is expected to play a
critical role, both coaxing along the two sides and offering
American financial and technological assistance, to both Israel and
Syria, as the two countries negotiate over mutual security
arrangements that would be part of the return of the Golan Heights
to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides say Clinton has blocked out most of the next
two weeks for the negotiations, and he is prepared for another
round in February if Shepherdstown proves inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   But any deal that calls for an increase in American aid to
Israel or the beginning of financial assistance to Syria _ probably
a total in the billions of dollars over the next few years _ would
require congressional approval. In an election year, that could
prove tricky, and Clinton's recent track record, as evidenced by
the defeat of the Test Ban Treaty, is hardly reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a vote on the Middle East aid package, if an accord is
reached, could come at roughly the same time as a vote on granting
China permanent trade status, part of the deal under which it is to
enter the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The issues are completely different, and so are the
constituencies pressing for passage. But both will be difficult
votes, and some in the White House are quietly questioning if
Clinton has the clout to prevail in two major foreign policy votes,
both in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The China vote may become the most visible symbol of two other
aspects of Clinton's foreign policy legacy. It will determine
whether he has any claim to have changed the nature of America's
influence on the world's most populous nation. And it will be a
major test of whether his signature effort to redefine America's
role in the world _ through a strategy of economic integration and
globalization _ can recover from the damage done in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has argued that if China is inside the World Trade
Organization, which sets global trading rules, the world will have
a far better chance of influencing its behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But the same groups that took to the streets of Seattle, arguing
that the WTO places the priorities of trade above those of workers'
rights and human rights, have vowed to block permanent trade status
for China. Clinton's biggest argument will be with his own party,
not with Republicans, especially as Democratic candidates in
November try to maintain the party's traditional constituencies
that support these two causes.
</P>
<P>
   And the Republican leadership, relishing the opportunity to
embarrass Gore, has already hinted that it will seek to delay the
vote several months so that a fractious split among the Democrats
will occur in the midst of the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The president's advisers vow to press on. ``I don't think there
was lasting damage from Seattle,'' Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S.
trade representative and chief architect of both the successful
China negotiations and the Seattle fiasco, said in an interview
before Washington emptied out for the holidays. ``The reality is
that the WTO will continue to function and global trade will
continue to grow. So well go full bore at putting it back
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, himself a
former trade lawyer, expressed similar optimism that the setback is
temporary. In retrospect, he said, the divisions between developing
countries and wealthy countries, and between Europe, Japan and the
United States, make it ``hard for this to congeal _ in hindsight,
even without the people outside'' breaking windows and blocking
Seattle's streets.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself made the problem far worse at Seattle. By
announcing that he ultimately wanted to make labor and
environmental standards a part of all trade agreements, he cemented
the opposition from developing nations, especially India, that are
convinced that the United States is trying to rig the system to its
advantage. That issue, along with peace with Pakistan, would
probably dominate Clinton's tentative trip to India, which he would
like to take in March.
</P>
<P>
   Those, of course, are the predictable problems Clinton will face
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's two biggest nuclear challenges _ defusing the
India-Pakistan confrontation and taming North Korea _ are both
situations that could veer into crisis at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   So could Russia, where the administration is seeing how Boris
Yeltsin's resignation and designation of an heir apparent plays out
while pulling back on its early enthusiasm for spending large sums
to convert Russia to capitalism. In the next three months, each
decision to extend or withhold aid will inevitably be seen in
Russia as an indicator of Washington's attitude about the acting
president, Vladimir Putin, whether it is really intended to be or
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's plenty,'' one of Clinton's aides said this week, ``to
keep him going all year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
