NYT-01-02-00 2043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000102.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4754 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCON-YEAR03-COX     01-02 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCON-YEAR03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `So many times we had a chance to win'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves has been in the NFL all but
one year since 1965 as a player, player-coach, assistant, offensive
coordinator or head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other time, when his 1990 Denver Broncos went from a
Super Bowl team to 5-11, has Reeves seen this much go haywire in a
season for one of his teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons were 14-2 last season and went to the Super Bowl
with a ball-control offense that also had quick-strike
capabilities, plus an opportunistic defense that was outstanding
against the run and key to a league-best plus-20 turnover ratio.
</P>
<P>
   They also has minimal injuries and uncanny chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, the 4-11 Falcons will play the 4-11 49ers for third
place in the NFC West, both teams long ago eliminated from playoff
contention.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta had absolutely none of the aforementioned ingredients
this season, despite minimal personnel turnover in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Reeves' agent, Robert Fraley, and good friend and pro
golfer Payne Stewart died in a plane crash, just two of several
people Reeves knows who passed away this year.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution beat writer Matt Winkeljohn talked
with Reeves not so much to dissect the problems, but to gauge their
effect on Reeves, who is 13 months removed from quadruple heart
bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has this been the worst year of your professional life, and
your personal life?
</P>
<P>
   A: Our expectations were high because we'd been to the Super
Bowl the year before, and to have a season where you don't even
challenge for the playoffs is really disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   And personally, I'm just at a point in my life, at 55 years of
age, where that's the way it's going to be.
</P>
<P>
   The last four or five years, my daily prayer list gets longer
because I have more friends and relatives that are sick, have
cancer, heart problems, or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the tragic one was when someone dies unexpectedly
like Robert did, and Payne did ... that was tragic, but also
happens in people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   (Assistant to head coach/pro personnel) Marvin Bass' (only son
died), one of our secretaries is having some problems, a good
friend in Denver passed away. But I don't think anybody is
interested in all that.
</P>
<P>
   It was just difficult on top of everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you reached a point where the peaks are not as high, and
the valleys seem even lower than ever?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's always been true, but it seems to magnify itself. You
expect the wins, but the losses take a lot more out of you.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the low point of the season?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's been so many. The first St. Louis loss (35-7) was bad
because we got embarrassed. Losing at San Francisco (26-7). There
were so many times we had a chance to win and didn't get the job
done.
</P>
<P>
   Every loss hurts. None of them are easy to deal with. You keep
trying to get it turned around. We never did get turned around to
where we felt we had things under control, and ... thought
everything was going to be good.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Excluding injuries, what of all the elements of failure has
been most disappointing _ the lack of a running game, the poor run
defense, or the change in turnover ratio?
</P>
<P>
   A: What's been most disappointing is I thought we had a chance
to win.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of reasons. Defensively, we didn't have that many
changes (in personnel) or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   That goes to show you how important your offense is at helping
your defense out, because we haven't controlled the time on the
clock and kept them off the field.
</P>
<P>
   We haven't given them outstanding field position. Even when we
got takeaways, we always seemed to be in our end of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You said after your heart surgery you were going to delegate
more responsibility. Have you?
</P>
<P>
   A: I did put a lot more on the coaches in the offseason as far
as getting things done because we've been together a while, and I
think they understand what we're doing. I did delegate more
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did that contribute to the way the season has gone?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. There's definitely things we've got to do better as a
coaching staff, don't get me wrong. It's not just the players. We
didn't do a good job, either. But I don't think it's because I
delegated more authority.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has been the greatest failure of the coaching staff, and
front office?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think we got our reserves to play as well as they're
capable of playing, for whatever reason, whether it was motivation,
or getting them to play up to their ability, or misevaluating (the
talent) of our backups in the offseason. We just didn't get the job
done.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was more difficult, the time after your surgery, or
coping with this year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Those three or four weeks after heart surgery. You have
trouble shampooing your hair.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Rumors that you're going to step down as head coach and
continue as executive vice president of football operations have
persisted for weeks. Do you plan to honor the two final years of
your contract, as both head coach and executive vice president?
</P>
<P>
   A: I plan to. Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do you think these rumors have surfaced?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've been around long enough to know that's part of it. Part
of it's the fact I've been around 19 years as a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What needs to happen for this team to get back to winning?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's what we'll do next week is find out what our
priorities are. But without even talking to the staff, we've got to
get a cornerback, got to get a running back because we got four
people coming off knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   We're going to have to resolve our deal at defensive line
because we've got (three) free agents there, and we need to shore
up our offensive line, and get a wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   And we got to make sure we've got a backup quarterback that we
can win with.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, everything is fine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
