<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4755 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-02 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHEN TREATMENT IS DENIED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Legal Aid Society has sued the state to try to force it to
provide residential treatment for severely mentally ill children
who now are on waiting lists and languish in inappropriate settings
for months, sometimes more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   But the shortage of residential treatment facilities is just
part of a much larger crisis in the delivery of services to
thousands upon thousands of mentally ill children who are suffering
grievously, and who often are a threat to themselves or others.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki and the state Legislature have taken some
recent steps to address this problem. But far more attention is
paid to the needs of mentally ill adults, and services for them get
the bulk of the state's money. The children get what's left, which
isn't much.
</P>
<P>
   So you get situations like that of a boy, now 11, who was
profiled in a report put out a few weeks ago by the Citizens
Committee for Children of New York. The boy was diagnosed as
psychotic at a very young age and behaves, to put it mildly,
bizarrely. When he became angry with a teacher named Mrs. Siegal he
went to the beach, killed a sea gull and brought it to her.
</P>
<P>
   The report said his speech is disorganized and he suffers from
delusions. He received day treatment for a while, but once his
condition stabilized he was sent back to his public school
classroom. There, according to the report, ``he fell apart.'' He
was ostracized by classmates. He placed a Molotov cocktail in the
tailpipe of a car belonging to a teacher he disliked.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was hospitalized several times and received residential
treatment for a while. But eventually he was sent home. The report
said he no longer attends school, is not receiving clinical support
and no longer gets medication. And there is no plan for ongoing
mental health treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a surprise: The youngster has been in trouble with the
police.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Pataki announced plans to spend an additional $36.2
million on mental health residential and support services for
children. Advocates like Gail B. Nayowith, executive director of
the Citizens Committee for Children, have generally been pleased by
the initiative. But they said it is not nearly enough to offset the
many years of neglect and chronic underfunding of children's mental
health services.
</P>
<P>
   So, for example, in addition to the long waits for admittance to
residential treatment facilities, there are drastic shortages of
other mental health services for children because of arbitrary
Medicaid spending caps and other harmful cost-cutting measures
imposed by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means there are many, many kids who don't get things like
outpatient therapy, medication, crisis services, day treatment or
partial hospitalization,'' Ms. Nayowith said. ``We like what the
governor did in November. But we want the state to build on that
$36.2 million foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   The suffering of mentally ill children who do not get treatment
can be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got voices telling them what to do,'' said Ms.
Nayowith. ``They've got hallucinations. They have anxiety
disorders, which means they can never sit and relax, or
obsessive-compulsive disorders _ hand-washing, pacing. They have
phobias and horrible eating disorders. Some are cutters _ you know,
they mutilate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens with these kids is that they suffer from an
illness that has a treatment but, basically, they're denied
treatment. So they're not getting relief from their pain. It would
be as if your kid had asthma or diabetes and you just never
provided an inhaler or insulin.''
</P>
<P>
   The price paid by others for not treating these kids can be
extreme. Ms. Nayowith mentioned the youngsters who are very
aggressive sexually, who are subject to uncontrollable anger or
mania, who physically attack others, set fires, mutilate animals.
The violence, at times, is homicidal.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nayowith also noted that mentally ill youngsters frequently
are the victims of sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   A close look at the tragic plight of the many thousands of
mentally ill children in New York should convince anyone that bold
new steps need to be taken to alleviate the gruesome psychic pain
that these youngsters experience, and to lessen the threat that
their illness can pose to the rest of us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
