<DOCNO> NYT20000102.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4758 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-02 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., S.C., Mich.)  
 COMMENTARY: McCAIN COULD WIN  
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sea change has taken place in the American
election system without our noticing it. The ``independentation''
of the primaries will determine our next president.
</P>
<P>
   In olden times _ a decade or so ago _ state primary elections
were often battlegrounds for partisans within each party. Liberal
Democrats would wrestle with ``new'' or ``blue dog'' Democrats to
choose candidates, just as economic conservatives would joust with
social conservatives to pick GOP nominees. Nor was it only
ideological: Young Turks would go up against entrenched leadership.
</P>
<P>
   There was a tidiness to this. Voters were given an incentive to
join a party: By signing up, you could vote twice _ first to choose
your party's nominee, and then for whomever you preferred in the
general election. Independents didn't get to vote in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   It's all been changing. In the crucial early primaries of the
next seven weeks, unaligned voters _ not hard-core party regulars
nor activists in organized pressure groups of left and right _ will
decide the nominees of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   This was unplanned. It has given an unremarked kick in the head
to the two-party system. The generation-old rise of the primary was
supposed to devolve power from party bosses to party members. But
this year the opening of both parties' gates is transforming
presidential politics. No party registration is required in the
three launch-pad states. Independent voters will be decisive in
choosing party standard-bearers.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, independents may vote in either party's
primary, which is why both Bill Bradley and John McCain are polling
so well against the party establishments' Al Gore and George W.
Bush. The bigger the independent turnout, the likelier a pair of
insurgent victories.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina _ Bush's ``firewall state'' in case McCain
beats him in New Hampshire _ there also is no party registration.
Jennifer Martin Donohue of WNDS-TV in New Hampshire, a distant
cousin who awakened me to this phenomenon, reports that the South
Carolina GOP expects a turnout of 300,000 this year, 5 percent more
than in 1996. Polls of Republicans have been showing Bush with a
four-to-one lead.
</P>
<P>
   That's largely because pollsters fail to take into account the
new political paradigm. One-third of S.C.'s 2 million voters are
habitual switchers, and the only primary action this year is
Republican on Feb. 19 (the Democratic ``firehouse caucuses'' come
weeks later).
</P>
<P>
   Bush is counting on the previous governor's ``machine'' and on
Pat Robertson's marshaling of the religious right's support of soft
money. But McCain has Rep. Lindsey Graham, the most popular figure
in the state, saying that campaign finance reform bolsters sound
conservative government.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 400,000 veterans _ highest percentage anywhere _ are
largely independents. All they have to do to become eligible on
primary day is to declare a GOP preference.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes Michigan, also with no party registration, which has
its GOP primary three days later on Feb. 22. Again, Bush is heavily
favored because Bushie Gov. John Engler has the party machinery.
But any of Michigan's 2 million independents charged up by coverage
of a South Carolina upset can walk in and become a Republican for a
day.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's Democratic caucuses should be duck soup for Gore,
with his union backing. But Bradley's secret weapon is the mail-in
ballot: Any independent (who may have voted for McCain two weeks
before) can send in a ballot declaring Democratic preference and
choosing Bradley. Those ``absentee'' votes probably will count.
(This recalls Jack Valenti's ``When I die, bury me in Texas because
I want to remain politically active.'')
</P>
<P>
   What will the addition of the new ``party temporaries'' to the
old-fashioned party regulars mean to 2000's primaries? Gore and
Bush strategists will deplore ``the invasion of the party
snatchers'' because they know it will strengthen Bradley and McCain
_ by how much, nobody knows. But certainly on the GOP side, the
coming three-state unregistered ramble requires a rethinking of
Philadelphia Conventional wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, by virtue of the wide-openness of the three launch-pad
primaries, is no longer a long shot. And if independents in party
clothing do help make the happy hero the GOP nominee, McCain could
claim to be more likely than Bush to beat the Democrat. (Unless
it's the maverick Bradley. Then everything's up for grabs.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
