<HEADLINE>
ELIZABETH DOLE, WITH EYE ON VP SLOT, TO ENDORSE BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Elizabeth Dole, who placed second to Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas in many national polls before she dropped out of the
race for the Republican presidential nomination, will announce on
Tuesday that she is endorsing Bush, Republican officials close to
both politicians said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   These officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that
Dole would probably make her decision known at a joint appearance
with Bush in New Hampshire, where Bush is locked in a tight contest
with Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement represents an important, albeit predictable,
development for the Bush campaign, in that Dole is one of the most
prominent women in the Republican Party and a respected leader
whose approval ratings remained lofty even though her candidacy
failed to catch fire. Dole dropped out of the race in late October
because, she said, she could not raise enough money to compete with
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement also reflects Dole's interest in the vice
presidency, people close to her said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win for both of them,'' said Nelson Warfield, the press
secretary for the 1996 presidential campaign of Bob Dole, Elizabeth
Dole's husband. ``It's another indication that the Republican
establishment is solidly behind George W. Bush, and that if all
else goes wrong, the thing that will get him across the finish line
is their support.''
</P>
<P>
   Warfield added, ``Elizabeth Dole would like to be considered for
the V.P. spot, and it's hard to see a scenario where she remains
silent or endorses somebody else and still gets considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Bush said that it was much too early to think or
talk about vice presidential prospects, and that Dole has several
marks against her, including the early failure of her campaign and
the fact that she has never been elected to office.
</P>
<P>
   Although there had been some speculation in Republican circles
over the last few weeks that Bob Dole was leaning toward endorsing
McCain, a close friend and longtime colleague in the Senate, people
close to the Doles said Sunday that the former Kansas senator would
probably not endorse anyone until the Republican contest was
essentially over.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole created a stir last May when he said in an interview
that he had thought about donating money to the campaign of McCain,
one of his wife's opponents. But associates of the Doles said he
was intent now on presenting a united front with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Dole's political game right now is to get his wife on the
ticket,'' said a Republican operative close to the Doles. ``I'd be
surprised if he endorses anyone now, but he'll embrace the
presumptive nominee this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to McCain said they were not surprised by Mrs. Dole's
decision and said McCain had done little to woo her. They seized
the development as another opportunity to cast Bush as the charmed
insider and McCain as the scrappy outsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good endorsement for a campaign that's been
built on endorsements,'' said Mike Murphy, a Republican strategist
working for McCain. ``We're not running an endorsement campaign.
We're running a message campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   An adviser to Bush said that Elizabeth Dole would probably fly
with the governor on Tuesday from New Hampshire to Iowa and make
several additional appearances in Iowa, which holds its caucus on
Jan. 24. The New Hampshire primary is Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The adviser said that it was unclear how much campaigning Dole
would do, but that Bush would like her continued help.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can draw a crowd, and it's a different kind of crowd,''
the adviser said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Referring to Elizabeth Dole's third-place finish behind Bush and
the wealthy publisher Steve Forbes in the Iowa straw poll in
August, the adviser added, ``She really did turn out different
voters than traditionally participated; she showed a strong appeal
to women and young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, a Cabinet member under two Republican administrations and
a former president of the American Red Cross, was the first woman
to be taken seriously as a presidential candidate, and Bush's
advisers clearly hope that her endorsement will solidify his
already strong standing among women who vote.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not at all clear that her base overlaps Bush's. And
after she left the race, some of her supporters went to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials said that Dole had decided to endorse Bush
several weeks ago but that the announcement was deliberately
delayed until the beginning of the final, monthlong sprint toward
the first statewide contests.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers even considered saving the announcement of the
endorsement as a last-minute boost going into the New Hampshire
primary, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Reed, who managed Bob Dole's 1996 presidential campaign,
said the endorsement was important largely as a way to control news
coverage for a few hours or days and lessen the odds that something
unplanned derails Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal right now, for a front-runner, is to play beat the
clock,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole will follow two other former Republican presidential
candidates, Rep. John R. Kasich of Ohio and former Gov. Lamar
Alexander of Tennessee, in endorsing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle, who also dropped out of the
race, has not endorsed anyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
