<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW YORK'S CLOSED PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Jan. 3:
</P>
<P>
   Long ago, political parties had a heavy hand in picking their
presidential nominees. Now, in most big states except New York,
voters do the picking in primaries or political caucuses. Through
an arcane system that requires even candidates who have qualified
nationally for federal election funds to amass signatures and jump
through qualifying hoops, New York's political parties have, by
mutual legislative agreement, limited the candidates on their
ballots to two Democrats, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen.
Bill Bradley, and as few as one Republican in some areas, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have made it easier for candidates' names to
appear on their ballot, requiring a campaign to get only 5,000
valid signatures statewide, as opposed to about 20,000 for the
Republicans. But even the lesser requirement is onerous,
undemocratic and outdated. New York's entire ballot-qualification
exercise ranks as a political throwback to the old party-boss days
before voters could see and assess the various candidates on
television. For that reason, states like California automatically
add names of those considered ``viable'' by the media. Some states
include any candidate qualified for federal funds or ask for a
modest filing fee. Unlike New York, these states want to offer
voters a basic political right: the ability to choose among all
available candidates for a given office.
</P>
<P>
   California's vote, which comes the same day as New York's, is
expected to have more than 20 names on the ballot, including three
Democrats _ the third being Lyndon LaRouche _ and six Republicans.
But the principle here is simple. It is better to have an unwieldy
ballot than an election fixed by Albany power brokers, party
kingpins and clubhouse patronage hacks.
</P>
<P>
   For the supporters of Bush, of course, New York state's
presidential primary is just the ticket. Bush, like Bob Dole four
years ago, is the state Republican Party's establishment candidate.
That means Bush has a ready-made Republican apparatus to gather
signatures correctly in each congressional district in order to
stamp his name on the state's ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican candidates cannot ``just add water,'' as they
refer to the Bush-Dole method of gaining access to the ballot.
Instead, they face a maze of rules and a mountain of signatures
clearly designed to scare off the anointed Republican's
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Three Republican candidates have given up the battle, but Sen.
John McCain and Steve Forbes are still at it. Forbes is expected to
hire petitioners at a cost of $750,000 to collect signatures in
each of the state's 31 districts, and McCain, who is also trying to
present petitions by this week's deadline, has filed suit to open
his party's ballot.
</P>
<P>
   State Republican leaders argue that their system filters out the
frivolous candidates. This is a fancy excuse for the hijacking of
New Yorkers' ability to vote in an open election. Besides, as
filtration systems go, this one is more like a brick wall.
Nitpicking disqualification rules mean, for example, that a
Republican candidate who needs 20,000 valid signatures would
probably have to collect 40,000. These names must be secured in
about a month, over the holiday season. Moreover, Republicans can
sign only one petition, so as the party regulars call their
established lists of voters for Bush, they automatically shrink the
pool of possibilities for McCain or Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   There is still time for New York to have a primary on March 7
that has not been fixed by a blockaded ballot. Three men have the
power to make that happen through special legislation. It is time
for citizens to call Pataki, (518) 474-8390; Joseph Bruno, the
Senate majority leader, (518) 455-3191; and Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver, (518) 455-3791, and tell them to meet their
obligation to guarantee free and fair elections. By inaction, they
become guardians of a corrupt system that is a national
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-00 2114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
