<SLUG> BC-NY-HUDSON-RIVER-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI PROPOSING A HUDSON RIVER RESEARCH INSTITUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki announced Sunday that he would propose
establishing a 500-employee research institute to study the Hudson
River, an initiative that several environmental leaders said could
represent a significant milestone in the decades-long struggle to
restore the river.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said that the center, to be called the Henry Hudson
Institute for Riverine and Estuarine Research and Education, would
be modeled after the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institute in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of oceans, you think of Woods Hole,'' Pataki
said in an interview. ``We think we have the potential to do the
same when you think about the Hudson River and estuaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Previewing part of his state of the state address on Wednesday,
Pataki said he would propose spending up to $1 million this year
for a task force that would address such questions as where the
institute would be located, how it would be financed and who would
control its operations and research. The financing would have to be
authorized by the state Legislature. But Pataki said that he hoped
the institute would be up and running in five to 10 years, with an
annual operating budget of about $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Woods Hole has 850 employees and an annual budget
of $85 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``An idea like this has been discussed for 30 years and never
gotten anywhere,'' said John Cronin, chief advocate of Riverkeeper
Inc., a nonprofit conservation group that closely monitors the
Hudson River. ``This is the first time a governor has proposed
this, which is why I think it's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Cronin said that debates over the pace of industrial and
residential development along the Hudson are perpetually bogged
down by the absence of credible, independent research on the river.
``What we don't know about the Hudson is a lot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With a major research institute unbeholden to either industry or
public interest groups, Cronin suggested, this void could be
filled, helping to shape development along the river. Pataki's
initiative, he added, comes at a time when there is an
``unprecedented push'' to reindustrialize the Hudson basin,
particularly by utility companies hoping to build power plants
along the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a substantial, bold proposal,'' Cronin said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, said he was proposing the institute as a
way to build on the advances already made in cleaning up the
Hudson, once a struggling ecosystem with a river bottom despoiled
by industrial wastes along much of its 275 nautical miles. While
the Hudson is cleaner than it has been in decades, parts of it are
still contaminated with polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs,
cancer-causing industrial chemicals that were dumped for many years
by factories in the upper reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made tremendous progress with our environmental
initiatives,'' Pataki said. ``We were thinking, `What's the next
step?'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The governor said he rejected an idea to start with a small
teaching center, or perhaps an aquarium, and instead urged his
environmental aides to ``take it to the largest possible vision of
what we could have.'' While the state would most likely pay a major
part of the cost, private foundations, colleges and the federal
government might also be asked to contribute, aides to the governor
said. Pataki has designated John P. Cahill, commissioner of the
state's Department of Environmental Conservation, to flesh out the
details.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the revival of the Hudson ``an incredible opportunity
economically,'' the governor said that the proposed institute could
expand and coordinate existing research efforts and provide a firm
foundation of science for tapping the Hudson's economic potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be looking to the future and that requires academic
research,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he added, a ``world-class and world-renowned''
science center focusing solely on rivers and estuaries could yield
important research results with broader benefits for environmental
policy makers across the country. While there are several
well-respected oceanographic research centers like Woods Hole and
Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory of Columbia University, which lies
on the Hudson, Pataki said that rivers and estuaries had gotten
less attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just think it is an unbelievable opportunity and the time
is right,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Sullivan, executive director of Scenic Hudson, an
environmental and land trust organization, said Pataki's plan had
the potential ``to significantly and dramatically expand the amount
of scientific research'' into the Hudson, which, he added, remains
at risk both from contaminated sediments and a new generation of
power plants. Such plants kill fish by drawing them into their
intakes, along with cooling water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is particularly long-sighted of the governor to propose
establishing an institute that could build a baseline of data about
the condition of the river,'' he said, ``so that citizens and
policy makers can work together to set long-term goals for
improving the quality of the river, cleaning up the toxic threats
and restoring the fisheries that have been suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project holds real promise for realizing the full
potential of the Hudson River.''
</P>
<P>
   One crucial area for the institute, he said, will be setting
priorities for research _ and doing so without undue influence from
corporations and developement companies that might be affected by
the results. ``I can't imagine that happening on Governor Pataki's
watch,'' he said. ``He's really been the greatest champion of the
Hudson we've ever had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
