<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-935&AMP;A     01-02 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-935&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TRIAL TO BEGIN IN LOUIMA CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Justin Volpe told a federal judge last month
that a fellow police officer had been wrongly convicted of helping
him brutalize Abner Louima in a Brooklyn station house, he cast
renewed doubt on whether the legal system had identified the right
man as his accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   The second trial stemming from the attack opens Monday, and it
may help shed light on the issue: Was it Charles Schwarz who held
Louima down as he was attacked in a station-house bathroom with a
broken broomstick _ as the government claims and the jury found, by
convicting him? Or was the accomplice another officer, Thomas
Wiese, as Volpe now maintains? Or did Volpe act alone on Aug. 9,
1997, as lawyers for the defendants in the second trial have said?
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, the new federal trial is about an alleged conspiracy
to cover up the crime that formed the basis of the first trial,
which ended in June. The second trial is to determine whether
Schwarz, Wiese and another officer, Thomas Bruder, obstructed
justice shortly after the assault by concocting a story for
investigators to get Schwarz off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   In the first trial, Wiese and Bruder were both acquitted of
charges that they had beaten Louima in a patrol car en route to the
station house and had conspired to assault him in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   The question of who, if anyone, helped brutalize Louima is
crucial because the single charge in the case accuses Wiese, Bruder
and Schwarz of obstructing justice by conspiring to cover up
Charles Schwarz's role _ an allegation that would seem to require
first proving that Schwarz was, indeed, involved.
</P>
<P>
   If Schwarz was not in the bathroom that night, the government
would apparently have little ammunition against the three
defendants. If Wiese was there, there is a chance, albeit slim,
that federal prosecutors would charge him in the assault. And if
Volpe was there alone, then the notorious attack, which blackened
the eye of the New York Police Department for months, could be
written off as the work of one aberrant, troubled officer.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn, where the trial will be
held, has repeatedly refused to comment on its planned strategy.
But the evidence presented against Schwarz in the first trial was,
in part, circumstantial and was based on the testimony of two
officers from the 70th Precinct who said they had seen Schwarz
leading Louima toward the bathroom, but not into it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the officers, Detective Eric Turetzky, testified that he
had seen Schwarz take Louima, still handcuffed and with his pants
and underwear around his knees, from the front desk of the station
house down a dead-end hallway that leads to the bathroom. The
second officer, Mark Schofield, recounted seeing Schwarz leading
the prisoner toward the hallway but not down it.
</P>
<P>
   But the most direct evidence placing Schwarz in the bathroom
that night was far from clear. Louima testified that the officer
who had beaten and held him down _ whom prosecutors identified as
Schwarz _ was the same officer who had driven the patrol car that
had brought Louima to the station house.
</P>
<P>
   Although police records show that Schwarz was behind the wheel,
Louima gave confusing accounts of the identity of the driver during
his cross-examination and was never able to identify Schwarz as the
second attacker, even though he unflinchingly picked out Volpe as
the first.
</P>
<P>
   An additional piece of evidence was used successfully against
Schwarz, but it, too, has been contested. In the first trial,
records were introduced showing that Schwarz had made a six-minute
call to Volpe from a pay phone hours after Internal Affairs
investigators first descended on the scene of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution argued that this phone call was a smoking gun,
suggesting that a panicked Schwarz ran to a phone to tell Volpe
that Internal Affairs was already onto them.
</P>
<P>
   But Wiese, a precinct union delegate at the time, claims that he
had borrowed Schwarz's phone card and had placed the call himself
to warn Volpe that a police investigation was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most damaging to Schwarz was the fact that two people
who could have testified that he was not in the bathroom at all
that night were never heard from at the first trial.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was Volpe, who pleaded guilty in midtrial. He was
never called as a witness, because Schwarz's lawyer in the first
trial, Stephen Worth, assumed that the jury would not believe
Volpe, who had damaged his credibility by confessing his guilt
after denying it for 21 months. Volpe, who was sentenced to 30
years in prison, is expected to testify on Schwarz's behalf at the
second trial.
</P>
<P>
   The other witness who could have exculpated Schwarz was Wiese.
Early in the investigation, Wiese told the Brooklyn district
attorney's office that he walked in on Volpe moments after the
assault and saw him _ alone, with a stick in his hand _ standing
over an inert and sobbing Louima.
</P>
<P>
   Those statements, however, were ruled irrelevant to the assault
charges at the first trial and were kept from the jury. But now the
prosecution is using the same statements as the basis for its
contention that Wiese lied about what he had seen to exonerate
Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three defendants has much to lose in this round of
prosecution, though none more than Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   If he is found guilty, he faces a five-year prison term. But
more important, a guilty verdict would probably weaken his chances
of successfully appealing his conviction in the first trial, for
which he faces life in prison.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ronald Fischetti, Schwarz's current lawyer, has said he plans to
use the second trial to lay the groundwork for an appeal of the
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Wiese and Bruder seem to have less at stake, because they were
acquitted at the first trial. Still, both men face five years in
prison if convicted of the obstruction charges.
</P>
<P>
   The second trial is Wiese's first opportunity to rebut in court
_ if he chooses to testify _ Volpe's claims that Wiese witnessed
the attack on Louima but did nothing about it. He did not testify
at the first trial.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Wiese has maintained, through his lawyers, that
he walked into the bathroom at the end of the incident, and that
Volpe acted alone. Moreover, the government itself has openly
scoffed at the accusations against him by Volpe and his lawyer,
Marvyn Kornberg, saying neither man is trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Bruder seems to have the most straightforward role in the second
trial. He has repeatedly claimed, through his lawyers, that he saw
Volpe escorting Louima into the bathroom on the night of the
assault and that he saw Wiese standing outside the bathroom door.
</P>
<P>
   By maintaining that Schwarz was never in the bathroom, he has
placed himself in opposition to the government's version of events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-00 2129EST &QL; 
