<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: JERI CLAUSING 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   `E-Conversion' Paying Early Dividends at Oracle
</P>
<P>
   In June, Lawrence J. Ellison, the chairman of Oracle Corp.,
announced that the company would reinvent itself as an e-business _
a company that uses the power of the Internet in every aspect of
its operations. He set a goal of reducing annual costs by $1
billion in 12 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, many analysts brushed off the announcement as more
hyperbole from a chief executive known for the same. But as the
months passed, it became clear that Ellison was putting his money
where his mouth is _ and reaping some early returns on the
investment. In the quarter ended Nov. 30, Oracle exceeded Wall
Street's earnings estimates, in large part because of a 5.5 percent
gain in profit margin that the company attributed to cost-cutting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we think we can continue as we convert to an
e-business,'' Jeff Henley, Oracle's chief financial officer, said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the savings are obvious. Oracle will convert 60
nation-specific corporate data systems scattered around the globe
to one system, to be housed at the company headquarters and
accessible via the World Wide Web. The company estimates $200
million a year in savings from that move alone. Executives say they
can trim the $500 million annual travel bill by 10 percent just by
using a Web-based application from eTravel, a company Oracle
acquired last year for $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger shifts will take longer and represent greater gambles _
but they could also pay even bigger returns. For example, Oracle
recently announced plans to sell its software over the Web at
standardized prices. That will, for the first time, make its
products accessible to small businesses, a market the company has
long overlooked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRENCE FISHER
</P>
<P>
   A Merger Sets Off An Information Rush
</P>
<P>
   The merger last year of Doubleclick and Abacus Direct was the
first official marriage of companies that gathered information
about people's activities online and offline. Doubleclick, which
serves advertisements on thousands of Internet sites and monitors
users' activities on those sites, could suddenly combine that
information with catalog purchases tracked by Abacus.
</P>
<P>
   Previously Doubleclick had ignored the personal identity of Web
surfers, but by using information about users' offline purchases,
it can charge higher ad rates. Since the merger was announced in
June, Internet advertising companies have forged ahead with efforts
to identify people on Web sites, find out more about their offline
lives, and show them ads that match that information.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy advocates denounce the practice, saying that it gives
companies too much information about individuals. They point to the
laundry list of information that offline companies gather _
including data on hobbies, home values and stock portfolios, to
name a few _ and note that Internet companies will be sifting
through that data even as they watch users surf the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The ad networks insist that such practices benefit Internet
users by giving them more relevant advertisements. Besides, they
say, users can, with a few clicks of a mouse, choose not to have
personal information gathered about them. But privacy advocates
argue that users should not have to lift a finger to protect
themselves against what they regard as intrusive behavior, and 2000
could be the year that the administration and Congress push
legislation to address those concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doubleclick had a good profiling model, which they used to
deliver targeted messages for advertisers and still protect the
user's privacy,'' said Marc Rotenberg, executive director of the
Electronic Privacy Information Center. ``But once they crossed the
line with Abacus and said, `Here are where the big bucks are,' they
also took a big gamble, because that's where the big privacy battle
is. And when the clock ticks on industry self-regulation, they may
have a very big problem on their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BOB TEDESCHI &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
