<HEADLINE>
AT NEW YORK CITY BUNKER, Y2K IS A-OK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By midafternoon Sunday, only an essential core of
employees remained inside New York's emergency management center,
the lookout post for Year 2000 computer catastrophes. Some were
watching the Jets game.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the transition to the year 2000 was going so smoothly
that at 6 p.m., Jerome M. Hauer, the director of the mayor's Office
of Emergency Management, shut down the command center for the
night. ``From our perspective, things have gone well,'' Hauer said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said the bunker, as the command center on the
23rd floor of the World Trade Center is known, would reopen with a
full staff at 6 a.m. Monday, ready to react to a belated New Year's
crisis if employees returning from the holiday weekend encounter
problems when they boot up their computers. But they also said that
the reactivation was intended more as a precaution and that they
did not expect any significant trouble. ``We have to be cautious
until we get through a normal work day,'' Hauer said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also stressed that the signs were encouraging.
After reviewing the results of a weekend of exhaustive computer
testing, Brian T. Cohen, director of the city's Year 2000 project
office, predicted a normal workday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agencies have been testing their systems all weekend long,''
Cohen said. ``Everything has gone through the testing with flying
colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports from utility and transportation officials were also
upbeat. For example, the only New Year's-related power failure in
New York City occurred when a foil party balloon in Queens rose and
struck some wires, blacking out 151 customers for 58 minutes on
Friday night, said Joseph Petta, a spokesman for Con Edison, the
utility company.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, emergency workers said they would be ready Monday
morning for almost any surprises. Hauer said nearly all of the 114
work stations in the center would be occupied by representatives
from the city, the state and the federal governments, as well as by
officials from banks and the securities and utility industries.
</P>
<P>
   Should any large-scale computer problems occur, officials said,
the city will be ready to apply quick fixes. For example, a
stockpile of $750,000 worth of spare parts set aside for Year 2000
computer repairs remained in a store room in the city's computer
center in Brooklyn on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   While city officials said it was too early to say that no
computer repairs would be needed in the days ahead, they emphasized
that it was increasingly evident that something remarkable had been
accomplished: After years of dire predictions and costly work, the
city's systems had held up.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two-thirds of the employees had left the command
center Sunday, and some of those who remained were watching the
fourth quarter of the Jets-Seahawks game, Cohen summed up the
situation as he saw it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly,'' he said, ``I think that Y2K is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
