<HEADLINE>
PLAYING TO FORM, GIANTS STUMBLE TO THE FINISH
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for rewriting throughout) 
(nk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ There was a certain air of hopelessness about
the Giants from beginning to end Sunday, despondency coupled with a
dazed bewilderment, an aura of despair that pursues the team into
the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys' 26-18 victory at Texas Stadium was just the
final act in a spiritless, daylong dissolution for the Giants. It
began with the Green Bay Packers' defeat of the Arizona Cardinals
in an early-afternoon game, a result that all but mathematically
eliminated the Giants from playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   True, the Giants knew as they took the field that they could
still make the playoffs with an 81-point victory. Then they kicked
off to start the game.
</P>
<P>
   And Dallas returned the kick 79 yards to set up the game's first
score. The Cowboys (8-8) scored often and early, sprinting to a
16-0 halftime lead and then cruising to a victory that earned them
the final National Football Conference wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   In a game that could have been a metaphor for their season, the
Giants (7-9) started slowly, peaked at the midpoint, then stumbled
badly to the finish. They also did not play with aggression,
confidence or any of the mettle requested of them by the team
co-owner Wellington Mara, who uncharacteristically addressed the
club last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who had once been a first-place team with a 5-3
record, closed their season with a 2-6 second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had lots of high hopes,'' safety Sam Garnes said. ``And
then we went straight down the drain.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the first losing season under Coach Jim Fassel, who did
not scold or admonish his players in the locker room after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they gave it everything they had,'' he said. ``We
weren't good enough. It hurts because we're used to winning at the
end around here. But it characterizes the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a shell of a team right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mara was in the locker room after the game as he normally is but
declined to make any comment.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel and the Giants were aware of the Packers score as they
began the game, though few admitted it affected their play.
</P>
<P>
   Free safety Percy Ellsworth, however, conceded the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only human nature,'' he said. ``You're going to be a
little down when you know you're out of it. Everybody tried, but
yeah, there was disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Several players acknowledged another obvious and likely outcome
of Sunday's game and a failed season _ that changes will be made in
the team's makeup. The specifics of those changes weren't discussed
and several players said they thought the team had been forced to
overcome a particularly onerous succession of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there will be some changes, but honestly, we've been
a patchwork team for a long time,'' said defensive end Michael
Strahan, who had another quiet game. ``We stood in there and
fought. It's very frustrating because no one goes to training camp
and does all that work to finish one game worse than last year's
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no one goes to training camp and says, `This guy is only
going to play five games,' and `This guy from the practice squad is
going to play 10 games.' You don't expect those things either.''
</P>
<P>
   From the opening kickoff Sunday, it took no more than a few
seconds to figure out which team had something to play for and
which team did not. Dallas' Jason Tucker slipped the tackle attempt
of Garnes just after taking the opening kickoff and then raced 79
yards to the Giants 11-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Three rushing attempts by the Cowboys failed to get the ball in
the end zone, but when Dallas' Eddie Murray kicked a 20-yard field
goal, the rout was on even if it was just 3-0 and just 2 minutes
and 18 seconds into the game.
</P>
<P>
   On the Giants first possession, the flat, disjointed attack that
would typify their offensive effort for most of the game was
obvious, and it was equally obvious that Giants Coach Jim Fassel
was not going to approach the game with a nothing-to-lose attitude.
</P>
<P>
   In eight plays, the Giants moved to the Cowboys 36-yard line,
where they faced a fourth-and-five. Fassel did not elect to go for
it, instead punting _ a maneuver that gained 16 yards when the punt
became a touchback.
</P>
<P>
   On their next possession, the Cowboys had little trouble moving
through the Giants defense again, though they again stalled at the
Giants goal line and settled for another Murray field goal.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of the Giants defense, they were playing without
nearly half their starting lineup. Linebacker Jessie Armstead was
on the sideline for long stretches of the first half resting his
sore right knee and so was defensive tackle Christian Peter, who
missed much of the first half with dizziness and a rapid heart
beat, and defensive end Cedric Jones, who has a tender knee.
</P>
<P>
   Two other starters from the beginning of the season were also
out of the game: cornerbacks Jason Sehorn and Phillippi Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   And the Giants defense certainly wasn't getting a lift from the
team's offense, which was moving the ball but barely threatening to
score. Collins would throw for 314 yards, completing 31 of 48
passes but did not have a touchdown pass until the game's final
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Joe Montgomery had just 36 rushing yards on 12
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman, meanwhile, was picking apart the
Giants pass defense, which seemed not only a step slow but passive
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Cowboys first touchdown, a 4-yard second-quarter
touchdown pass from Aikman to Raghib Ismail. Ismail, split to the
right, ran a crossing route underneath the heart of the Giants
defense, passing a Giants safety and two linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   No one touched, nudged or tried to impede Ismail, who caught the
pass from Aikman as he stood at the goal line. Aikman completed 23
of 32 passes for 288 yards and two touchdowns. Dallas' Emmitt Smith
ran for 122 yards on 22 rushing attempts.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, the Cowboys had padded their lead to 16-0 with
another Murray field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants hardly seemed intent on mounting a serious
second-half threat. With the first possession following
intermission, the Giants gained 2 yards in three plays and gave the
ball back to the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   After a Giants field goal midway through the third quarter,
Dallas put the game away for good when Aikman connected with Tucker
on a quick slant pattern in front of Giants cornerback Jeremy
Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker caught the ball at the Cowboys' 17-yard line, spinning
away from Lincoln, who made a poor, one-armed effort at a tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker then raced 90 yards up the left sideline for the
touchdown that sealed Dallas' victory.
</P>
<P>
   A 71-yard pass from Giants quarterback Kerry Collins to wide
receiver Joe Jurevicius set up a 1-yard touchdown run by Joe
Montgomery early in the fourth quarter, but the fans inside Texas
Stadium were already celebrating their unforeseen good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't very mature today,'' Collins later said. ``I don't
know, maybe that's what we have to learn from all this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
