<HEADLINE>
ASIAN EXCHANGES USHER IN SMOOTH START TO CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first worldwide trading day of 2000 opened without
difficulty Monday morning at stock exchanges in Hong Kong,
Singapore and Malaysia, reassuring market officials that the global
market is coping with the computer-related hurdles that arrived
with the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic trading systems at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
and the Chicago Board of Trade, which handle trades in futures and
options, also opened for business Sunday night without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   The computer and communication systems that handle financial
transactions _ stock trades, interbank payments, credit-card
transactions _ had all been tested successfully throughout the
weekend in preparation for Monday's opening bells. Indeed, some
small stock exchanges in the Middle East conducted weekend trading
without difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Financial executives caution that problems could emerge in weeks
or even months, with attention now focusing on how well computers
handle Feb. 29, a leap-year anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   But even with two major markets, in Tokyo and London, closed
until Tuesday because of scheduled holidays, Monday is nevertheless
the first major stress test of how well the world's financial
software is handling years that begin with 2.
</P>
<P>
   And as of Sunday night, key international banking systems seemed
to be functioning normally, said Joseph Pawelczyk, vice president
of systems development at the New York Clearing House, which
handles transactions for 78 international banks.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were there any reports of problems in foreign currency
trading. Peter Trager, the chief foreign-exchange trader at Fleet
Boston Financial, said that while Far Eastern trading was off to a
slow start, ``everything seems to be working fine.'' He and other
traders emphasized, however, that they would be more than usually
cautious about dealing with small banks or unknown customers until
confidence grew.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals trading online through U.S. brokerage firms seemed
calm but cautious Sunday night, and online trading volume Sunday
was low but largely trouble-free.
</P>
<P>
   The non-Internet economy seemed to be taking the date change in
stride. The manufacturing plants in the United States that are
clients of EDS Corp. started up Sunday night without serious
problems with computer-controlled systems, according to Reed Byrum,
a spokesman for EDS, which had been monitoring client operations in
55 countries through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Credit-card transactions also moved smoothly _ although there
were alarmed calls after the manager of a steak house in St. Louis
told diners he could not accept credit cards because the restaurant
was unable to process the transactions.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that the restaurant's credit-card processing
terminal had been unplugged, said Linda Locke, a spokeswoman for
MasterCard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
