<DOCNO> NYT20000102.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HUNGARY-1STLD-WRITETH     01-02 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNGARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL FUROR OVER MOVING OF HUNGARY'S CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS spelling of ``Esterhayzs'' in 20th graf; CLARIFIES that
Carter had crown returned in 24th graf; CORRECTS spelling of Attila
in 27th graf) 
 (rk) 
 By DONALD G. MCNEIL JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST, Hungary _ And now, said Hungary one day late: Let the
millennial celebrations begin.
</P>
<P>
   Not the worldwide ones, but rather those marking 1,000 years
since Hungary became a nation. And what a nation: a windswept
battlefield settled by Siberian horsemen on the doorstep of Europe,
a vast plain whose borders have always been up for grabs, a history
of angry subjugation at the hands of Ottomans, Austrians and
Soviets, a disenfranchised nobility scattered across the globe, and
all of it linked by a language whose only living relative _ and not
a close one at that _ is Finnish.
</P>
<P>
   And the only nation on earth whose nationhood historically
resided in a crown. Not in a crowned head nor an imperial line, and
not remotely in the consent of the governed nor in any sceptered
isle, but in the physical lump of bejeweled gold itself: the sacred
crown of St. Stephen, presented to him by Pope Sylvester II exactly
1,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But heavy lies the pillow that wears the crown _ because the
simple act of moving it has split the Hungarian nation.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of this new millennium, in a glorious
procession fraught with pomp and armored cars, that venerable crown
with the pearl tassels, the rainbow of icons and the bent cross was
transferred from a small room in the national museum to the ornate
rotunda of the spectacular houses of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1945, we protected this crown from both the fascists and
the eastern dangers,'' intoned Jozsef Vitez, the last surviving
member of the old Crown Guards, looking resplendent in his historic
hussar's uniform but a bit bowed beneath its heavy shako. ``I am
handing it over to you _ guard it as we did,'' he concluded to one
of the newly reconstituted Crown Guards, who stood before him
looking boyishly nervous behind his drawn saber.
</P>
<P>
   But what right, demanded the opposition parliamentarians who
boycotted the ceremony, does a king's crown have to a place of
honor in a republican democracy?
</P>
<P>
   What right, retorted the government that not only moved the
crown but tried to write a reference to it into the constitution,
do our liberal opponents have to deny Hungarians the symbol of
their traditions?
</P>
<P>
   What, ask many average Hungarians, is going on here?
</P>
<P>
   A full answer is tricky. The government says honoring the crown
is simply part of the 1,000th birthday festivities, on which it
will spend $140 million this year, commissioning new statues,
films, symphonies and conferences.
</P>
<P>
   The government's critics say the crown is part of the mantle of
righteousness it has drawn around itself as it intimidates those
who oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   They say corruption, xenophobia and a dangerous pan-Hungarian
nationalism are on the rise and the government abets them because
its allies include small right-wing parties and opportunistic
tycoons.
</P>
<P>
   Elemer Hankiss, a sociologist and political commentator who is
optimistic about Hungary's future, calls it all an
``inside-the-Budapest-Beltway battle.'' Right-wingers still
dreaming of Greater Hungary are only 2 percent of the populace, he
said, and ``Crown-gate is a stupid issue'' dividing former allies.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For an Eastern European country, Hungary is doing relatively
well. It has the fastest-growing economy in the first wave of
candidates to join the European Union. Elections have been held
since 1989 without problems. But some observers say they spot
anti-democratic trends.
</P>
<P>
   In February, for example, about 300 skinheads met at Budapest's
mountaintop castle to mourn the Waffen-SS troops and their
Hungarian Arrow allies who died there.
</P>
<P>
   When the police appeared at their nightclub to check passports,
they rioted.
</P>
<P>
   Quieter anti-Semitic and anti-gypsy incidents, like threatening
letters, have been reported.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The crown ceremony Saturday drew groups of men waving the flags
of the Arpad family, who led the first Hungarians over the
Carpathians in the 890s. Others carried the flags of Greater
Hungary, showing the borders before chunks were lost to Romania,
Slovakia and the Ukraine in the treaties ending World War I. To
some, their yearnings have disconcerting echoes of Greater
Deutschland of the 1930s and Slobodan Milosevic's Greater Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, some of the flag-bearers waiting in the snow to
see the crown Saturday said they were detained on sight by the
police for two hours. Their Hungarian Truth and Life Party is a
small member of the ruling coalition, which suggests that the
police aren't politically influenced, even if they haven't yet
grasped freedom of assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Some Hungarians even worry about the revival of the old nobles
association, while others consider it harmless nostalgia. Counts
and princes from the Hungarian diaspora pop up everywhere, from
Laszlo Almasy of ``The English Patient'' to the Esterhazys who
figure in the South African wine industry. But there is little fear
they will demand ancient lands back; they couldn't even get
Parliament to restore the florid titles they lost under communist
rule.
</P>
<P>
   To historians, the new fight over St. Stephen's legacy is
frustrating, because the crown has been kicked around plenty over
the centuries, and this looks like a whole new political football
league.
</P>
<P>
   The crown was given to Stephen, known here as Istvan, when he
was merely king, but he had embraced Christianity and agreed to
spread it in the way then fashionable _ by the battle ax.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being bent by some clumsy retainer, the crown was lost
on a roadside by Otto of Bavaria circa 1310, stolen by the pregnant
widow of Albert von Hapsburg for her unborn son in 1439, ransomed
back in 1463, shuttled back and forth between Buda, Bratislava and
Vienna on Hapsburgian whims, and buried for four years in a futile
attempt to save it from Austrian troops crushing the Hungarian
rebellion of 1848.
</P>
<P>
   It even spent 33 years in Fort Knox, Ky. As the Third Reich fell
in 1945, the Crown Guards fled west with it to evade pro-Nazi
putschists and invading Soviet troops, and surrendered to Americans
instead. President Carter had it returned during a brief 1978 thaw
in the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   (Stephen's right hand, by the way, has separately toured Europe
as a holy relic and was also Allied war booty very briefly. It now
rests in St. Stephen's Basilica in downtown Budapest. The rest of
his body is in the royal tombs in Szekesfehervom, but where exactly
is unclear because they were vandalized under Ottoman rule.)
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, historians say, this latest move to another
nitrogen-filled glass box has left behind the delicate cloak of St.
Stephen, the only element of the royal paraphernalia that everyone
agrees really is 1,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pains me personally that this group is broken up,'' said
Attila Zsoldos, a medieval historian. ``You can't just haul a
1,000-year-old piece of textile from place to place.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Even if Stephen actually wore the cloak, the other items that
followed the crown in Saturday night's procession _ a sword,
scepter and orb _ probably were acquired later and officially
declared his former property by later kings, who in the old days
could legally pull such shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   The sacred crown itself is suspect because it is riveted of gold
bands of different chemical make-up, one with Greek writing and one
with Latin.
</P>
<P>
   Among its icons are King Geza I and Emperor Michael VII of
Byzantium _ both of whom ruled after Stephen's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this act,'' said Balint Magyar, president of the Alliance
of Free Democrats, who were in the government but are now in
opposition, ``they have transformed the crown from an honored piece
of our history into a tool of their daily political goals. If they
think it doesn't belong in a museum, they don't understand 20th
century Hungarian history.''
</P>
<P>
   Magyar feels a certain family expertise; his great-great
grandfather was the prime minister who buried the crown to save it
in 1849.
</P>
<P>
   The government's allies scoff. ``We want to honor the crown
without over-emphasizing it,'' said Bela Pokol, a leader of the
conservative Smallholders Party. His party formed the new ruling
coalition with the Fidesz-Hungarian Civic party, which began as an
anti-Communist youth movement in the 1980s, but has shifted _ some
say opportunistically after election losses _ into a mixed
traditionalist, Christian, pro-big-business stance.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance, which embodies urbanized intellectualism, ``always
opposes traditional values,'' Pokol said. He also criticized the
media as ``unbalanced in favor of liberal/leftist/Socialist
circles.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of talk is how the government gets portrayed as
anti-intellectual _ which in eastern Europe is sometimes read as
anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Pokol's liberal targets accuse the government of
throttling them. Last year it cut 90 percent of its grant to the
Institute for the History of 1956, a think tank of academics once
jailed for opposing the Stalinist crushing of Hungary's 1956
rebellion. The money went to a rival think tank favored by Prime
Minister Viktor Orban, who wasn't even born until 1963.
</P>
<P>
   The government also closed the country's second-biggest paper,
the liberal Kurir, letting the Post Office Bank that owned it
shutter it as a money loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is freedom of the press here, but there's pressure
too,'' said Gabor Szucs, Kurir's last editor. ``It's like the
Chinese proverb: To scare the monkeys, kill a chicken in front of
them. They sent a message _ behave.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a grenade was thrown at the offices of a weekly
paper that accused relatives of party officials, including Orban's
father, of enriching themselves and evading taxes. The party sued.
A few weeks earlier, the car of a satiric journalist was
anonymously firebombed.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been arrested. Hankiss said he thought even such
events were overblown in a country still learning how to respond to
free speech with more speech instead of with the 1956 bullet holes
that still dot downtown walls.
</P>
<P>
   But the joke among some of those watching the parade Saturday
was that Orban wants the crown nearer his office so he can try it
on at night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
