<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4786 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     01-02 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLOWOKANDI BATTLING INJURY AND JABS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARSON _ Michael Olowokandi was trying to lead with a limp. He
was sacrificing his aching knees for the good of the team, or so he
thought.
</P>
<P>
   If Olowokandi were a receiver or defensive tackle on the
Stanford football team, this would have been been a very good
thing. His teammates, drawing on his inspiration as if it were pure
oxygen, would have gone out and put quite a scare in a much better
team.
</P>
<P>
   But Olowokandi's team is the Clippers so you know what that
means.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of kudos, there were incriminations.
</P>
<P>
   The shots were fired Thursday, after the Clippers suffered a
22-point loss at Houston (on the heels of a 23-point defeat at
Denver). Maurice Taylor, the team captain, blasted Olowokandi, the
team's second-year center, for ``not doing much on offense.... He
has to step up because right now he's nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments revealed more about Taylor than Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   To zoom in on Olowokandi's stats _ six blocked shots, four
points and four rebounds in 25 minutes against the Rockets _ is to
frame the picture all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to have the eye of Clippers general manager Elgin
Baylor to recognize the hitch in Olowokandi's gait the past couple
of weeks. He has been running the floor as if it were a court of
sand near his home in Manhattan Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, concerned by Olowokandi's noticeable limp, took the
conscientious 7-foot center aside recently and asked if his knees
were bothering him. Olowokandi shrugged off the questions, because,
after all, aren't former No. 1 picks supposed to be bulletproof?
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, Derek Anderson already had gone down with an
injury. So had Eric Murdock and Brian Skinner. Olowokandi didn't
want to join them and risk having the players in dress clothes
outnumber the players in jerseys on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we're all dropping, one by one,'' Olowokandi
explained Sunday. ``I felt a responsibility to be out there with
the team. If I wasn't at 100 percent, at 75 percent or 50 percent I
thought I still would have helped. If I can give something, I'll be
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds pretty selfless to us.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a thought: Maybe what the Clippers need to get out of
their funk is fewer Taylors and more Olowokandis. We dare them to
bounce that opinion off the locker room walls (with the doors
closed, of course).
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi might have told Taylor he was hurting but Taylor
didn't give him the opening. He took a gripe that should have
stayed in the locker room and broadcast it in such a way that
Olowokandi was the last to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   With people like that watching your back, who needs
back-stabbers?
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi was a no-show at practice on Friday, the morning
Taylor's comments appeared in print. The surprise is it wasn't
because he was canvassing the city, buying up all the day's
newspapers so he could set the sports sections on fire in the South
Bay's biggest New Year's Eve bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I did not hear about (what Taylor had said about
him) until Saturday night when I talked to my agent,'' Olowokandi
said.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, we'd like to believe half of what we heard at the
Clippers' practice, their first to include both Taylor and
Olowokandi since Taylor took his teammate to task. But so many
contradictory remarks were made, after a while we started to feel
like we had taken a wrong turn and wandered onto the set of a new
game show called, ``Truth or Lie?''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor said any hard feelings between Taylor and Olowokandi had
been smoothed over. ``It's all been resolved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Baylor was talking, Olowokandi was shooting baskets with two
assigned teammates at one end of the court while Taylor did
likewise at the opposite end, their paths looking for all the world
like they were designed not to cross.
</P>
<P>
   If we had been in coach Chris Ford's Nikes, we would have run at
least one two-man drill and made sure Taylor and Olowokandi were
paired. Just to facilitate peace, love and understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Ford didn't see the need to, having presided over an
air-clearing meeting before practice. ``We did it within the team
atmosphere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's message wasn't the problem, Ford said, it was his
choice of messengers. ``Peer pressure is fine,'' Ford said. ``It's
important... for guys to get on one another. You say what you
think, you say what you feel. (But) it doesn't go outside the
locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 22 and a third-year pro, has been in team sports long
enough to know dressing room decorum. He blamed his behavioral
lapse on a stretch that has seen the Clippers lose two straight
games in sloppy fashion after winning five of their previous seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose, a lot of frustration sets in,'' Taylor said.
``You tend to try to be a critic of everyone's game. I was
disappointed in the way the team played. I tried to put some
pressure on Michael to step up. I was trying to light a fire under
Michael and I did it the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   The next time Taylor decides to tie a teammate to the stake for
the offense of not playing hard enough, let's hope he talks to him
before turning up the flame. In the meantime, Olowokandi wouldn't
mind an apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Taylor) hasn't said anything to me, personally,'' Olowokandi
said upon emerging from a post-practice weight-lifting session.
``It would be kind of nice if (an apology) happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. This issue is supposedly forgotten and Taylor
hasn't even asked yet for forgiveness?
</P>
<P>
   Pardon our confusion, but we assumed an apology by Taylor would
form the foundation of the resolution Baylor alluded to and of the
air-clearing meeting Ford spoke of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Maurice must have forgotten (to apologize),''
Baylor said, backpedaling. ``He said he wanted to talk to Michael.
He wanted to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth? It wouldn't have cut into Taylor's afternoon too much
to walk with Olowokandi to the weight room and spot him during a
couple bench press sets. What better way to strengthen muscles and
bonds?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think whatever he said he knows it was out of line,''
Olowokandi said. Told that Taylor said he was merely trying to help
motivate him, Olowokandi dryly replied: ``When I'm in need of a
personal psychologist I'll hire one. That's what I say to that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the most dignified response of the day. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-02-00 2200EST &QL; 
