<SLUG> BC-Y2K-FINANCIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL WORLD GETS ITS BIG TEST MONDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Also moved in financial designation)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The company's Pillow Room, an old elevator shaft
converted into a napping nest, was empty. The Stress Relief Room,
with a pinball machine and Mortal Kombat video game, had few
visitors. And red hotline telephones perched on wooden stools were
silent.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a dearth of signs of millennial anxiety, employees of
Thomson Financial's electronic settlements group in downtown Boston
spent Sunday night in the glow of computer screens, watching Asian
stock markets open as the world's financial system gradually
awakened for business for the first time in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all very optimistic that things will work beautifully,''
said Howard Edelstein, chief executive of the group, which is an
electronic housekeeper to the securities industry, processing
around one-third of the 4 billion or so shares traded globally each
day. ``But one never knows until the major markets kick in.''
</P>
<P>
   Having crossed into 2000 with few technological glitches,
financial services institutions from Beijing to Bonn to Boston face
their true test Monday, when much of the world resumes work and
millions of financial and retail transactions pass through computer
systems for the first time in the new year.
</P>
<P>
   Some markets, like those in Singapore, will have closed by the
time New York bankers and Boston fund managers wake up. European
stock exchanges will be winding down just as Wall Street kicks into
high gear. London and Tokyo markets, closed Monday for traditional
New Year's holidays, reopen Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Markets were closed on New Year's Eve, so remedies against the
year 2000 computer bug have yet to be tested in actual working
conditions. The bug causes unprepared computers to read 2000 as
1900 and possibly to malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Despite few, if any, reports of computer glitches during the New
Year's Eve rollover, most brokerages, banks, fund firms,
back-office processors, and exchanges kept their Y2K war rooms
staffed through the weekend to prepare for their real-life test.
</P>
<P>
   With power plants, telephones, and other utilities functioning
normally, the companies are waiting to see if the resumption of
business will cause any internal glitches. Having spent tens of
billions of dollars and several years remedying countless lines of
computer code against the Y2K bug, as well as held elaborate tests,
financial services firms will find out in coming days if everything
from mutual fund share prices and wire transfers to employee
paychecks and internal accounting systems function under regular
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Smooth sailing expected
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday evening, few observers were predicting problems with
the computers that drive the world's financial labyrinth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence suggests there probably will be very little
disruption'' when US financial markets _ the biggest in the world _
reopen Monday, said former Treasury secretary-turned-investment
banker Robert Rubin on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Some Japanese brokerages experienced minor glitches Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But John Koskinen, who oversees year 2000 efforts at the White
House, told a Washington briefing that ``we do not expect any
significant problems in banking, finance, and retail operations
here'' or in other developed countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get through Monday or Tuesday as well as we have gotten
through this weekend, then I think we will feel very comfortable
that there aren't any major problems,'' Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, amid growing debate over whether the uneventful calendar
rollover represented a technological beast successfully tamed or a
paper tiger hyped by consultants and programmers, financial
services firms were taking no chances.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in red fleece ``Y2K Response Team'' jackets, Thomson
employees Sunday monitored computer screens and watched market news
from space-age chairs with fold-out trays.
</P>
<P>
   At Visa, the credit-card giant, spokeswoman Susan Forman said:
``Everyone is eager to see how Monday goes, but early indications
are that our payment systems are working.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, New England's largest bank, opened 11 branches Sunday in
Connecticut and Long Island for regular business, just to test the
waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us haven't had a hot meal in three days,'' said Jim
Schepker, who heads Fleet's Y2K team, which has worked around the
clock since Friday. Though Fleet's chief executive, Terrence
Murray, never set foot in the bank's Y2K war room over the weekend,
the company plans to keep its command center staffed through
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Early signs
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, which Fleet owns, kept 100 supermarket branches open
for a second day Sunday. The bank reported ``minor'' computer
viruses on its internal corporate e-mail system but said it had
taken care of the problem and customers would not be affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out of the woods yet _ Monday is our next
significant milestone,'' said Bruce Spitzer, a BankBoston
spokesman. ``But our preliminary assessment looks good.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston, part of the nation's
central bank, staffers spent the weekend completing a checkup of
New England's banking system. A spokesman, Thomas Lavelle, said
that ``the key thing is that on Monday, people are back to real
life, which makes it a key day and a telling day.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments, the world's largest mutual fund firm, did
not have to use a special room at downtown Boston's World Trade
Center that it had booked for an emergency media conference in case
things went haywire. But the Boston company kept 1,000 customer
service representatives at the phones Sunday night (and offered
staffers a catered Mexican feast).
</P>
<P>
   Processing a securities transaction takes three days, and
professional investors who traded securities on Wednesday had
received electronic confirmation of their deals by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But some big tests remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that has not yet happened is to have a trade
entered and cleared, all in the new year,'' said Margaret Draper, a
spokeswoman for the Securities Industry Association, a trade group
for investment banks, broker-dealers, and fund firms.
</P>
<P>
   The longer term will be a testing ground, too: Industry
specialists say any effects from the millennium computer bug could
take weeks and months to manifest themselves in services or
documents, such as a quarterly statement.
</P>
<P>
   Financial services companies seemed reluctant to join a chorus
of questions from reporters and observers over the merits of the
vast and costly efforts launched to protect systems against the
year 2000 bug. Worldwide spending on Y2K is estimated at $250
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But James Chisholm, a senior systems engineer at Thomson ESG,
the electronic settlements group that is part of the Thomson
Financial empire, said the millennial computer glitch had been good
for the securities industry.
</P>
<P>
   Chisholm said that increased trading volumes, after-hours
business, and growth in cross-border trading had put pressures on
the global financial system that needed to be tested in any case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't had a Y2K problem,'' Chisholm said, ``it would
have been good to have invented one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
