<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-HIJACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FEAR, DOCTOR KEPT JOB A SECRET FROM HIJACKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARION LLOYD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURGAON, India _ For the first three days of his nightmarish
captivity, Lalit Verma kept silent, fearfully guarding the secret
that he knew would prolong his ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted to declare that I'm a doctor,'' Verma said
Sunday, two days after he walked free with 154 other hostages who
had been held for more than a week aboard Indian Airlines Flight
814. ``I thought, if they release some people, they will never
release any doctor, because they will need him till the last
minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Verma, a 39-year-old anesthesiologist, was returning home from a
vacation in Nepal with his family on Dec. 24 when their plane was
hijacked by five Islamic militants shortly after it left Katmandu.
</P>
<P>
   Verma's wife, Indu, and their two small children were freed on
the second day of the hijacking, along with 24 other passengers,
during a stop in Dubai, leaving him to survive the ordeal alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I begged them: `Let me go with my children,' '' he said in an
interview at his house in Gurgaon, a satellite town on the
outskirts of New Delhi. ``But they said, `No, get back to your seat
and be quiet.' I didn't speak to anyone for three days.''
</P>
<P>
   Then on the third day, something happened to jolt Verma out of
his cocoon. The passengers had endured four excruciating hours with
heads in laps, while their captors waited for Indian negotiators to
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   The hijackers, wearing face masks and wielding pistols and
grenades, were shouting at a passenger sitting three rows ahead who
had ignored their orders to sit up. Verma saw the passenger slump
over into the aisle and watched with alarm when the man's face
begun to turn blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jumped up and said: `Stay back. I am a doctor. Let me help,'
'' Verma said. He told how he revived the man with CPR and oxygen,
and then began attending to the other passengers. One of those was
another doctor who had suffered a nervous breakdown after trying to
treat the planeful of terrorized hostages alone.
</P>
<P>
   His new role turned out to be a blessing in disguise. While most
of the passengers were ordered to stay in their seats with their
blindfolds on, Verma was allowed to move about the cabin and even
catch glimpses of the desert airstrip where their ordeal was to be
played out. ``What would happen to me, I didn't think about
anymore,'' he said. ``I was too busy.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, it was a horrifying ordeal of frequent death
threats and endless monotony. A dozen men who were segregated in
the first-class cabin watched as the hijackers inflicted the only
casualty, stabbing to death a 25-year-old honeymooner named Rippan
Katyal after he disobeyed their orders not to look at them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hostages were eight pairs of newlyweds, including a
Spanish couple. Verma said that the 25 foreigners on board had been
treated slightly better than their Indian counterparts, but that
they had also been isolated because of the language barrier.
</P>
<P>
   The hijackers alternated speaking in Hindi and Urdu, leaving one
of the Indian passengers to translate into French and English.
</P>
<P>
   Many passengers gave up eating solid food _ what little was
provided by Afghanistan's Taliban leaders _ to avoid having to use
the increasingly foul bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Their moods rose and fell with the moods of their captors,
particularly the one nicknamed Burger, whom they described as
alternately nasty and jovial.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to tell us, `I have a big heart, but I can be cruel
also,' '' Verma said. Other passengers later described feeling
affectionate toward him, calling him ``Burger bhai,'' or brother
Burger. But the relief created by the rare light moments, when
Burger led the passengers in singing Hindi film songs, would vanish
abruptly when their captors felt threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Verma related how the hijackers would stand in the aisles
clutching their grenades and call one another by their assumed
names. ``Shankar, pull the pin,'' or `` `Bhola, now's the time.
Let's end it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The worst moment came late Tuesday night, four days into the
hijacking, when the optimism created by the arrival of an Indian
negotiating team a day earlier was shattered by Burger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us, `We have stopped negotiations, and now you all be
prepared to get killed. . . . We'll start killing you one by one.
And if we kill anyone, don't think anybody will be spared,''' he
said. ``That was the lowest point.''
</P>
<P>
   The hijackers were believed to be members of the
Harkat-ul-Ansar, one of roughly a dozen Islamic militant groups
fighting a 10-year secessionist battle in Indian-controlled
Kashmir. They were demanding the release of 35 fellow militants
held in Indian jails. But they finally accepted the Indian
government's offer to release three _ a Pakistani cleric and two
Kashmiri militants who two of the hijackers said were their
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly, they were angry at our Indian Army. They said the army
is being cruel to the people of Kashmir,'' Verma said. ``They kept
telling us, `We are not bad people. But what would you do if your
brother was in jail?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Those insistences only made the passengers feel more helpless.
``I thought, Why were we hijacked? If the government has captured
their brothers, why should we suffer?''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Burger announced that a deal had been struck for
their release, and that a plane from India was on its way to take
them home.
</P>
<P>
   But freedom was still 24 hours away. At 3 a.m. on Friday, New
Year's Eve, the engines gave out, leaving the passengers to battle
subfreezing temperatures and mounting despair. Finally, at noon on
Friday, the plane's pilot was allowed to meet with the Indian
negotiating team and returned with the news that they were free.
</P>
<P>
   The strangest episode, however, was still to come.
</P>
<P>
   Before fleeing the plane, Verma said, several of the hijackers
demanded the hostages' forgiveness. ``They told us, `We are very
sorry. But you must pardon us,' demanding that all those passengers
who accepted raise their hands. Who would not raise their hand in
that situation?''
</P>
<P>
   Now safely reunited with his family and thronged by an endless
stream of friends and well-wishers, Verma is haunted by Burger's
final words. ``He waved and told us, `See you again.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
