<DOCNO> NYT20000102.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COLTS-BILLS-HNS &LR;      01-02 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLTS-BILLS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ For the first time since Jan. 3, 1993, when
they made the greatest comeback in NFL history, the Buffalo Bills
will play the Tennessee Titans in the playoffs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the last day of the regular season, the Bills improved their
record to 11-5 with a 31-6 tuneup victory over AFC East champion
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills already had secured a wild-card berth. On Sunday, they
learned who their first-round opponent would be, and it didn't take
long for the veterans to start giving history lessons to the
younger players.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than playing the Houston Oilers _ the team they beat
41-38 in overtime after rallying from a 35-3 third-quarter deficit
_ the Bills travel to Nashville, Tenn., to tangle with the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've changed their nickname and their domicile, but the
game will be just as emotional and mean just as much as if they
were still the Oilers playing in Houston,'' said Buffalo's Ralph
Wilson, who, like the Titans' Bud Adams, is an original American
Football League owner. ``At that playoff game, I remember thinking
_ in all sincerity _ there was just no way a team could be behind
35-3 and hope to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think about that game now, all I can remember is that I
did a lot of screaming and shook a lot of hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Titans, the Bills are on a roll. They finished the
season with a three-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of strange to have 11 wins and have to hit the road,
but I think we'll be up to the challenge,'' Bills guard Ruben Brown
said. ``We've been playing well lately, and this is the time of
year you want to be playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to imagine the Bills playing better than Sunday,
when they put on one of their most impressive performances of the
season. After spotting the Colts a 3-0 lead, Buffalo pounded
Indianapolis into submission.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the most excited player on the field was Buffalo
receiver Andre Reed. In what may have been his last regular-season
game for the Bills, Reed caught five passes to give him 941 in his
career. He moved past Art Monk and into second place on the NFL's
all-time list behind Jerry Rice (1,249).
</P>
<P>
   Houston fans will remember that Reed, more than any other
player, was responsible for Buffalo overcoming the 32-point deficit
against the Oilers with three touchdown catches in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   By resting quarterback Doug Flutie against Indianapolis, Bills
coach Wade Phillips created a quarterback controversy. Flutie, who
has been erratic this season and has feuded with the media, watched
Rob Johnson complete 24 of 32 passes for 287 yards and two
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   In his first start since early last season, Johnson wasn't
sacked and didn't throw an interception. He also contributed 36
yards rushing on seven carries.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Phillips insisted there was no quarterback
controversy despite persistent questions from reporters. Flutie
will start at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the mild-mannered Phillips bristled at yet another
Flutie/Johnson question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, hey _ I've already answered all those questions,'' he
said. ``Look, I'm happy Rob played well. He did a tremendous job. I
wanted him to be as good as he could be. If we need him, we'll
utilize him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who left Jacksonville after the 1997 season and signed
with Buffalo as a free agent, began the 1998 season as the starter
but didn't play well. When he was injured, he was replaced by
Flutie, who guided the Bills to the playoffs and became one of the
most popular players in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   After picking apart the Colts and outplaying Indianapolis
quarterback Peyton Manning, who was 18-of-29 for 163 yards and
failed to throw a touchdown pass for the second consecutive game,
Johnson wasn't about to get caught up in a controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get into that,'' Johnson said when asked if he
thought he should start against the Titans. ``It's not my decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would assume so (that it's Johnson's last game to play this
season), unless something happens to Doug. It was nice to play a
game like this because it gives my teammates confidence in me, but
it's not like my entire career was based on this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips made it clear to his players what the team wanted to
accomplish Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention was to win this game against a good team, and we
played that way,'' Phillips said. ``We wanted to get Andre the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy with our vertical passing game, and our defense
played well against an offense that's one of the best in the
league.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Colts knew they had a first-round bye and a
second-round game at home, they didn't play with the intensity that
allowed them to win 10 consecutive games and set an NFL record by
making a 10-game improvement from last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts' only points came on Mike Vanderjagt's field goals of
27 and 24 yards in the first half. Once coach Jim Mora knew that
Jacksonville was going to beat Cincinnati to secure the home-field
advantage in the AFC, he pulled several of his key starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kicked our tail just about every way it can be kicked,''
Mora said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
