<SLUG> BC-YOUTHS-WRECK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE YOUTHS KILLED AFTER 1 TRUCK FLIPS ONTO ANOTHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MELODY McDONALD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Five youths were killed in a wreck Sunday
after the pickup they were riding in somersaulted over the grassy
highway median and landed upside down on another pickup,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the second pickup was transported by air to Harris
Methodist Fort Worth and was listed in serious condition Sunday
night, a police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The force of the wreck melded the cabs of both trucks together
and it took more than two hours for officials to separate the
vehicles. Authorities identified the dead as Edward Jennings, 18;
Hank Gorman, 20; James McDonald, 15; John McDonald, 16; and Martin
McDonald, age unknown. Their hometowns were not released but
several carried driver's licenses from out-of-state, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1 p.m. accident occurred on Interstate 30 in far west Fort
Worth. The eastbound lanes were closed for about four hours while
workers cleared the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter ambulance sat idle in the eastbound lanes while
firefighters, using the jaws of life, freed the sole survivor from
the wreckage. His name was not released.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they believe the youths' red Ford extended-cab
pickup was traveling south on Loop 820 when it exited onto I-30
westbound. The truck, which police say was driven by Jennings, was
going at a high speed and went out of control, authorities said. It
hit the grassy median, flipped through the air and landed upside
down on a green Chevy pickup going east, police spokesman Lt. Ric
Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings was ejected and his body landed in a ditch near a
service road, 70 to 80 feet from the highway, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The victims' relation to each other was unclear Sunday night,
but police Sgt. Anne Cummings said she believed they were related,
possibly cousins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my understanding that the parents live out of state,''
she said. ``The boys were in town working for an uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said there were no signs of alcohol at the scene. It was
not clear whether the victims were wearing seatbelts.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the accident, Larry Wheeler, 56, stood next to the
destruction and said he was lucky. He said he was driving west on
I-30 with his four grandchildren when he noticed the red truck
behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The red truck almost hit us in the side,'' Wheeler said. ``He
just kept on coming. I blew my horn and he came across into the
ditch and then back across.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing everything I could,'' Wheeler said. ``I had my
four grandkids in the vehicle and I was doing everything I could to
keep us safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The pickups were so mangled that it took more than two hours for
emergency workers to determine how many were involved in the crash.
They used a tow truck to lift the red truck so they could see
inside.
</P>
<P>
   They found four bodies, said Cummings, who was visibly shaken.
</P>
<P>
   Clark described the impact as ``tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked Delta 191 (plane crash), but these four kids are
broken up,'' Clark said. ``It is bad. It is very bad.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
