<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday, 01/02/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Jan. 2, 2000 -- 3CENTURY-LIFE -- Charlotte
Green in 1963. Ms. Green was 101 years old when she died of kidney
failure at a hospital in Manhattan on Saturday afternoon, a few
hours after the new century began with the year 2000. By the
ordinary measures of a life in a city of power and riches such as
New York, which had been her lifelong home, she was an unknown
woman. She had never married, and for 60 years had worked for a
Wall Street law firm as a secretary, librarian and chief clerk,
retiring 22 years ago. And if it had not been for the timing of her
death, which gave her a foothold in three centuries, perhaps no one
would have cared enough to write about her. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SUNNYVALE, Calif. -- Jan. 2, 2000 -- COMPUTER-BRIEFS --
Linus Torlvalds, left, and David Ditzel are both involved in
Transmeta, a microprocessor design company in Sunnyvale, Calif.
Transmeta has so far managed to keep its product, scheduled to be
introduced on Jan. 19, a secret. In today's valley, bored with
me-too Internet start-ups, much of the buzz about Transmeta
suggests the company has found a way both to simplify processor
circuitry and to accelerate the running of instructions on other
chips, like Intel's. (Peter DaSilva/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ATHENS, Greece -- Jan. 2, 2000 -- OBIT-ZUMWALT -- Chief
of Naval Operations Admiral Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr., right, talks with
a naval officer upon his arrival for naval activities in the area
in 1972. Zumwalt, who as chief of naval operations in the early
1970s ordered the Navy to end racial discrimination and demeaning
restrictions on sailors, then faced a haunting personal tragedy
that he related to ordering the deployment of the defoliate Agent
Orange in Vietnam, died Sunday at the Duke University Medical
Center in Durham, N.C. He was 79 and lived in McLean, Va. (The New
York Times via The United States Navy)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Jan. 2, 2000 -- ELDERCARE-SHORTAGE-2 --
Gertrude Warren, 52, a health aide, cares for Goldye Saturn, 91,
who suffered a stroke, and her husband, Al, 92, in their home in
the Bronx. A shortage of home health-care nurses and aides and
nursing-home assistants has deepened in the last two years
throughout the country as better-paying jobs with better conditions
have opened up for the women who have traditionally filled those
positions, which have low wages and few benefits. (Joyce
Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PHILADELPHIA -- Jan. 2. 2000 -- ELDERCARE-SHORTAGE-1 --
Charmane Ellis, 33, a home aide in Philadelphia, offers support to
her client Antonietta Mannino, 81. The shortage of home health-care
nurses and aides and nursing-home assistants has deepened in the
last two years as better-paying jobs with better conditions have
opened up for the women who have traditionally filled those
positions, which have low wages and few benefits. ``I feel like
this is my thing to do in life,'' says Ms. Ellis. ``It makes me
feel appreciated. I figure I'm going to be there one day.'' (Tim
Shaffer/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LOS ANGELES -- Jan. 2, 2000 -- Y2K-WORKERS-DISPERSE-2 --
For Randall Bart year 2000 work proved to be a short-lived bonanza.
After being laid off from Unisys, the computer maker, in 1988, Bart
did not find work as a programmer until 10 years later, when Y2K
made what he calls his ``obsolete experience'' worth $45 an hour.
But his last job ended in August and Bart, 43, who lives in Los
Angeles, has been unable to find work since. ``I'm hoping for some
big disaster somewhere to hit,'' he says, only half joking.
(Marissa Roth/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BRIDGEWATER, N.J. -- Jan. 2, 2000 --
Y2K-WORKERS-DISPERSE-1 -- For Paul J. Maszczak, becoming Year 2000
manager for C.R. Bard Inc., a medical-device manufacturer in Murray
Hill, N.J., was a career-transforming experience. The job lifted
him out of the narrow confines of the information technology
department, exposing him to all aspects of his company's business.
Now, with those efforts winding down, Maszczak thinks his broader
business knowledge has prepared him for a bigger management job. As
for day-to-day systems work, ``I could never go back,'' he says.
``We're free agents.'' (Frank C. Dougherty/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 2, 2000 -- ROSTENKOWSKI-PROFILE -- Dan
Rostenkowski, 72, the one-time, all-powerful chairman of the House
Ways and Means Committee, has been well-received in Washington. It
has been two years since he finished his ``sabbatical'' at the
Oxford, Wis., prison compound and the halfway house that came next.
Rostenkowski paid his 17-month penance for using taxpayer money to
buy chairs and crystal domes for his friends and to hire people to
mow his lawn. Suddenly, he's popping up all over Washington, a
place he feared might throw a permanent sneer his way. (Todd
Buchanan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PHILADELPHIA -- Jan. 2, 2000 -- FCC-BARBER -- David J.
Farber, 65, a University of Pennsylvania professor and a pioneering
computer scientist and telecommunications expert, is expected to be
appointed the chief technologist at the Federal Communications
Commission. As a government witness at the Microsoft trial last
year, Farber argued against one of Microsoft's main contentions:
that the way the company had chosen to integrate its browser
software into its Windows operating system was the only possible
technical alternative. (Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MENLO PARK, Calif. -- Jan. 2, 2000 -- KHOSLA-PROFILE --
Vinod Khosla, partner at Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers,
discusses strategy at a meeting. Khosla started his first company
at age 25. Two years later, he co-founded Sun Microsystems. At age
44, his vision has turned metaphysical, to a time when human
thought melds with computer intelligence, blurring the lines
between people and machines. ``In the next 100 years, traditional
religion will be as relevant as witch doctors are today,'' he says.
(Peter DaSilva/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Jan. 2, 2000 -- WRITERS-ON-WRITING -- Thomas
Fleming says he obeys the dictates of his imagination. (Chester
Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
