<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-02 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ARGENTINA-MENEM-NYT &LR;      01-02 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-MENEM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINA'S FORMER PRESIDENT STILL AT CENTER STAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ As president, Carlos Saul Menem
dominated Argentine news coverage for more than a decade by selling
off much of the government and pegging the peso to the dollar _ not
to mention racing sports cars, throwing his wife out of the
presidential palace and dating women half his age.
</P>
<P>
   Now out of power for barely three weeks, Menem has managed to
remain at the center of attention. He has sometimes even managed to
overshadow the always demure President Fernando de la Rua, who
campaigned promising a new style of government.
</P>
<P>
   Menem holds ``shadow Cabinet'' meetings with his former aides,
as early as 8:30 a.m., as if he were still president and they still
had ministries to run. He is serving as broker for his Justicialist
Party ticket for municipal elections in Buenos Aires in 2000,
apparently shoving aside his own former justice minister, who won a
mayoral primary just a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   And with great fanfare, Menem has started an effort to form an
international extension of his party to spread the hard-to-describe
populist ideology and legacy of Gen. Juan D. Peron worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Menem is still the talk of Buenos Aires. His presidential
memoirs are being sold at kiosks and bookstores on every street
corner, and a salacious tell-all biography titled ``Menem: The
Private Life,'' is a runaway best seller. The otherwise serious
political magazine 3 Puntos ran a long article last week on how the
gliterati of Punta del Este, the Uruguayan beach resort that caters
to Argentina's jet set, were waiting for Menem and his entourage to
arrive this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Menem's lingering larger-than-life presence has raised eyebrows
among fellow politicians, some of whom are beginning publicly to
question his sanity. ``He sometimes seems to lose touch with
reality,'' Eduardo Duhalde, Menem's former vice president, said in
a radio interview last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Olga Wornat, the author of the Menem personal biography, said:
``Since leaving power, Menem has been depressed. He loves power
more than anything, including his family. He'll do anything he can
to be in the middle of the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Never shy about throwing his weight around, Menem challenged the
de la Rua administration last week, threatening to tell untold
secrets about the new powers-that-be should his former senior aides
come under too much scrutiny for possible past corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The response has been ferocious. Menem has become the target of
what looks like a carefully choreographed campaign by de la Rua
cabinet members and several leaders of his own party to cut him
down to size once and for all. And the local news media are piling
on.
</P>
<P>
   The brouhaha began over the indictment a week ago of one of the
least illustrious officials of the Menem era _ Victor Alderete, who
ran the national pensioners welfare institute. Alderete is accused
of skimming money that was to be used for hearing aids, taking
kickbacks from companies involved in physical therapy, and keeping
an enemies list and files of critics, including journalists.
</P>
<P>
   So far, de la Rua has been cautious about investigating
corruption, apparently preferring to wheel and deal with the
opposition to get his budget and tax package through Congress. But
several of his aides hope the Alderete case is just the beginning
of a hard look into what the news media here describe as deep
pockets of corruption throughout the Menem government.
</P>
<P>
   Not taking any chances, Menem embraced Alderete as a man ``who
did his best'' and lashed out at his opponents for engaging in a
``witch hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they keep pursuing this,'' Menem said, ``we are going to
have to talk about things we don't necessarily care to talk
about.''
</P>
<P>
   What Menem was suggesting was far from clear, but his comment
sent reporters around town scurrying for a response.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua would not take the bait, refusing to comment with a
wave of his hand and an equally unclear, ``Oh no, not about that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vice President Carlos Alvarez, who has emerged as the most
outspoken member of the administration, said that Menem's
suggestive remarks ``appear to come straight from the script of the
movie `The Godfather.''' He added, ``Nothing will stop the process
under way to shed light on what has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Health Minister Hector Lombardo said of Menem: ``By defending
people who acted corruptly he is involving himself in the
corruption. If he has something to say, he should say it now.''
</P>
<P>
   And Social Welfare Minister Graciela Fernandez Meijide, who has
long called for Menem's prosecution, said, ``If he knew about
corruption and did nothing about it, that amounts to malfeasance.''
</P>
<P>
   Menem says he has nothing to hide and that any investigation
into his actions would merely be a political tactic to stop his
already announced run for the presidency for the 2003 election.
</P>
<P>
   But what has perhaps been most revealing about the dispute is
how leading former Menem allies, including his two vice presidents,
are backing the investigation into Alderete and criticizing Menem's
public support of the former pension manager.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Carlos Ruckauf, who is now governor of
Buenos Aires province, has called Menem's comments ``inexcusable.''
</P>
<P>
   Duhalde, whom de la Rua defeated in the presidential race, said,
``No way is this a witch hunt.'' He went on to blame the declining
fortunes of his party on Menem's personal ambitions and ego. ``I
will make sure that doesn't happen again,'' he said, adding that he
will challenge the former president for leadership of the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   All the tough talk from such a powerful array of people has some
analysts predicting the final downfall of the man who has dominated
Argentine politics ever since he made his appearance on the
national scene in 1989 with his wild sideburns and reckless driving
habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Menemism is going to disappear,'' predicted Domingo Cavallo,
Menem's former economy minister and now a critic.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the last embers will surely be bright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
