<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-CANADIENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS AND CANADIENS TIE, 2-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ If not for Mike Richter, the New York Rangers' first
game of the new century would have ended like so many others here
have concluded in the last century _ with a Canadiens victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens came into the game with a 188-56-37 record in
Montreal against the Rangers, who were 1-12-3 here during their
last 16 regular-season matchups. But even though these Canadiens
hardly resemble their storied forebears, Richter had to be
absolutely brilliant in goal to preserve a 2-2 tie after Rangers
defenseman Sylvain Lefebrve scored _ a rarity for him _ 10 minutes
10 seconds into the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Lefebrve's second goal of the season, a slap shot from the top
of the slot off a Jan Hlavac pass, gave the Rangers the tie. And
the Rangers, who have now played overtime in 9 of their last 12
games, were able to fly home after a three-game road trip with
three of a possible six points in the standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky to get a tie, because we weren't as good as we
could have been,'' said Richter, who is nursing a sore groin. ``We
weren't as good as we should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Richter was not speaking for himself. He stopped 28 shots,
including 8 from point blank range in the last half of the third
period and 4 more in the 4-on-4 overtime, as the Rangers gained a
point in their fourth consecutive game. The tie extended the
Rangers' stretch without a victory to six games (0-3-3 with a
regulation tie). But the Rangers have scored points in four of
those six games thanks to the new rules regarding overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a lot of practice at it,'' Rangers Coach John
Muckler said, referring to the extra session the Rangers seem to be
playing on a nightly basis. ``Maybe we'll get better at it.''
</P>
<P>
   As Theo Fleury said, ``Somewhere along the line here, we have to
win a game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Richter played well,'' said Muckler. ``Especially late in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' first lineup of the new year had a new addition,
and therefore, a new look. Mike York's line, with Adam Graves and
Theo Fleury, remained intact. As did Petr Nedved's with Valery
Kamensky and Jan Hlavac.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Taylor, however, skated with John MacLean and Mike Knuble
(who had been a healthy scratch the last four games). And Radek
Dvorak, obtained Wednesday from Florida in a three-way deal that
saw the popular Todd Harvey go to San Jose, made his Rangers debut
centering a line for Eric Lacroix and the slumping Alexandre
Daigle.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers controlled most of the first period. They took a 1-0
lead on the power play 14 minutes 22 seconds in, when York scored
his 11th goal of the season to retake the National Hockey League
lead for rookies.
</P>
<P>
   The goal came on a tap in from off the left post after a Kevin
Hatcher shot from the right circle had been blocked before it could
reach Montreal goaltender Jeff Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   But the game turned at 18:34 of the first, when Mathieu
Schneider was whistled for holding Arron Asham. Before then, the
Rangers held a 9-3 advantage in shots on goal. But Benoit Brunet
was credited for a power play goal at 19:13 _ Eric Weinrich's shot
from the left point appeared to go in off Rich Pilon's skate as he
attempted to bulldoze Brunet from the slot - and the teams were
tied at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   And then, with 11.3 seconds left in the first, Schneider took
another penalty for high sticking Jason Ward. Thirty-eight seconds
into the second, Rich Pilon was called for hooking Martin Rucinksy.
All of a sudden, the Rangers had taken three consecutive penalties
and were staring at 1:12 of a 5-on-3.
</P>
<P>
   They killed it _ sort of. The second the penalty to Schneider
ended, Sergei Zholtok skated in from the left circle and beat
Richter. And the Canadiens had taken a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Lefebrve evened it. Then _ after Richter pretty much forced the
overtime all by himself _ Lefebrve had a golden chance to win it.
But he could not get a good shot off on a 2-on-1 rush with
Schneider early in the extra session. And the Rangers had to settle
for a single point. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Muckler wasn't going to take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be a big point at the end of the season,'' he said.
``Somewhere down the line, somebody's probably going to miss the
playoffs because they didn't get the two points. You need all the
points you can get.''
</P>
</TEXT>
